title: Elbasan
text: Elbasan is a city in central Albania, the capital of Elbasan County. It is the largest city in the country by population, with over 127,732 inhabitants. Elbasan lies in a valley surrounded by mountains, at the confluence of the Shkumbin and Seman rivers. The city has been inhabited since the early Iron Age and has been ruled by various empires and kingdoms throughout its history. Today, Elbasan is a major industrial and cultural center, with a diverse population and a thriving economy.

title: Manson Family
text: The Manson Family was a cult led by Charles Manson, an American criminal and musician. The cult was active in California from the mid- to late-1960s and committed a series of gruesome murders in the summer of 1969. Manson's followers believed in a coming race war that they would incite by committing violent crimes. Manson was convicted of multiple murders and sentenced to death, but his sentence was later commuted to life in prison. He died in 2017 at the age of 83.

title: RYB color model
text: The RYB color model (Red-Yellow-Blue) is a traditional color model used in art and design. It is based on the three primary colors: red, yellow, and blue. These colors are considered to be pure and cannot be created by mixing other colors. By mixing these primary colors, secondary colors are created: green (yellow and blue), orange (red and yellow), and violet (red and blue). Tertiary colors are created by mixing a primary and a secondary color, resulting in six additional colors. The RYB color model is often used in painting, drawing, and other artistic endeavors because it is simple and easy to understand.

title: Field (mathematics)
text: Field In mathematics, a field is a set on which two operations, addition and multiplication, are defined and combined in such a way that the operations behave as expected from real numbers. This means that the operations are associative, commutative, and distributive, and that there exist additive and multiplicative identities and inverses for all elements in the set, except for the additive identity. Fields are widely used in mathematics, including abstract algebra, number theory, algebraic geometry, and mathematical analysis. Examples of fields include the rational numbers, real numbers, and complex numbers.

title: History of Laos
text: Laos's recorded history begins in the 14th century with the founding of the Lao kingdom of Lan Xang. Lan Xang was ruled by a series of powerful kings who expanded the kingdom's territory and influence. In the 16th century, Lan Xang was divided into three smaller kingdoms: Luang Prabang, Vientiane, and Champasak. These kingdoms were frequently at war with each other and with their neighbors. In the 19th century, Laos became a French protectorate. Laos gained independence in 1953, but the country has been plagued by civil war and political instability since then.

title: Semi-detached
text: Semi-detached is a type of building that is attached to another building on one side, usually by a shared wall. Semi-detached houses are common in many countries, and they often have two or more stories. The main advantage of a semi-detached house is that it is more affordable than a detached house, while still providing the benefits of homeownership. Semi-detached houses are also often built in pairs, which can create a sense of community.

title: Victorian Legislative Council
text: The Victorian Legislative Council was the upper house of the Parliament of Victoria, Australia, from 1856 to 1951. It was created by the Victorian Constitution of 1855 and modelled on the House of Lords in the United Kingdom. The Council was composed of 40 members, who were originally elected for 10-year terms. In 1913, the term was reduced to six years. The Council was abolished in 1951 after a referendum.

title: Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation
text: Hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT), also known as bone marrow transplantation, is a medical procedure that replaces damaged or diseased bone marrow with healthy stem cells. These stem cells can come from the patient's own body (autologous transplant) or from a donor (allogeneic transplant). HSCT is used to treat a variety of diseases, including leukemia, lymphoma, sickle cell disease, and severe aplastic anemia. The procedure involves collecting stem cells from the donor or the patient's own body, then infusing them into the recipient's bloodstream. The stem cells travel to the bone marrow and begin to produce new, healthy blood cells.

title: Rochester, Pennsylvania
text: Rochester is a city in Beaver County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 3,657 at the 2010 census. Rochester is located on the Ohio River, 18 miles (29 km) northwest of Pittsburgh. The city is home to the Rochester Power Plant, a coal-fired power plant that provides electricity to the Pittsburgh area. Rochester is also home to the Rochester Area School District, which serves the city and the surrounding area.

title: Bernard Katz
text: Bernard Katz (March 26, 1911 – April 20, 2003) was a German-British biophysicist and Nobel laureate. Katz shared the 1970 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine with Julius Axelrod and Ulf von Euler for their work on the chemical transmission of nerve impulses. Katz's research focused on the release of neurotransmitters at the neuromuscular junction, and he developed the quantal hypothesis, which states that neurotransmitters are released in discrete packets called quanta.

title: Hedley Verity
text: Hedley Verity was an English cricketer who played for Yorkshire and England. A leg-spinner and lower-order batsman, he is widely regarded as one of the greatest bowlers of all time. He played 50 first-class matches during the Second World War, capturing 108 wickets. In all first-class cricket, he took 1,956 wickets at an average of 14.90, with 10 ten-wicket hauls and 100 five-wicket hauls. He also played in three Test matches for England, taking 23 wickets at an average of 13.65, including eight wickets in an innings. Verity was killed in action in 1943.

title: Shibboleth
text: Shibboleth is a password or security token used to grant access to a website, building, or other controlled area. It is typically a word or phrase that is easy for authorized users to pronounce but difficult for unauthorized users. The term shibboleth is derived from the Hebrew word for "stream" and refers to a story in the Bible in which the Israelites used the word to identify the Ephraimites, who could not pronounce it correctly. Today, shibboleths are used in a variety of contexts, including computer security, military operations, and border control.

title: Herne the Hunter
text: Herne the Hunter, also known as Herne the Wild Huntsman, is a legendary figure from English folklore. He is often associated with Windsor Forest in Berkshire and Windsor Great Park. According to legend, Herne was a forester who was transformed into a spectral hunter by Queen Elizabeth I. He is said to ride a white horse and be accompanied by a pack of hounds. Herne is a popular figure in literature and music, and has been featured in many works, including Shakespeare's "The Merry Wives of Windsor".

title: Protected area
text: A protected area is a clearly defined geographical space, recognized, dedicated and managed, through legal or other effective means, to achieve the long-term conservation of nature with associated ecosystem services and cultural values. Protected areas contribute to the planet's well-being by conserving biological diversity, ensuring the provision of ecosystem goods and services, and supporting cultural values and spiritual beliefs. They also play a vital role in mitigating climate change and conserving natural resources for present and future generations.

title: Varberg
text: Varberg is a city in southwestern Sweden, the seat of Varberg Municipality, Halland County. It is located on the Kattegat coast, about 70 km south of Gothenburg and 60 km north of Helsingborg. In 2015, Varberg had a population of 33,098. The city is known for its well-preserved medieval castle, Varberg Fortress, and its beautiful beaches. Varberg is also a popular tourist destination, and its economy is based largely on tourism and the service sector.

title: Garage sale
text: Garage sales, also known as yard sales or rummage sales, are events where individuals sell unwanted or used items from their homes or garages. These sales typically offer a wide range of items, including furniture, clothing, toys, books, and household goods. Garage sales are often held in driveways, yards, or garages and are usually organized by the homeowners themselves. They provide an opportunity for people to declutter their homes while earning some extra money. Garage sales are also popular destinations for bargain hunters and collectors seeking unique or vintage items.

title: Zeami Motokiyo
text: Zeami Motokiyo (c. 1363-1443) was a renowned Japanese actor, playwright, and theorist of Noh theatre. He is considered one of the most influential figures in the development of Noh, establishing its core principles and aesthetic conventions. Zeami's writings, such as "Kadensho" and "Fūshikaden," provide insights into the art of Noh, emphasizing the importance of empathy, elegance, and the pursuit of yūgen, a profound and resonant beauty. His plays, including masterpieces like "Atsumori" and "Hagoromo," explore themes of loss, longing, and the transience of life.

title: Eskimo
text: The term "Eskimo" is an outdated and potentially offensive term for Inuit and Yupik peoples, indigenous groups inhabiting the Arctic regions of Alaska, Canada, Greenland, and Russia. The term originated from a Cree word meaning "eaters of raw meat" and was used by European explorers to describe these groups. However, many Inuit and Yupik individuals find the term derogatory and prefer to be referred to by their specific tribal or cultural affiliations. Today, the preferred terms are "Inuit" and "Yupik," which reflect the cultural and linguistic diversity of these indigenous communities.

title: Culture of Argentina
text: Argentina possesses a diverse and vibrant culture, shaped by a blend of European, indigenous, and African influences. The country's capital, Buenos Aires, is a cosmopolitan metropolis renowned for its thriving arts scene, tango dancing, and football passion. Throughout Argentina, traditional gaucho culture remains strong, particularly in the vast pampas grasslands, where horseback riding and cattle ranching are way of life. The country's literature, music, and cinema have gained international acclaim, showcasing the creative spirit of its people.

title: St John Philby
text: St John Philby was a British explorer, writer, and civil servant who converted to Islam and became known as Abdullah Philby. Born in Sri Lanka, he served as an intelligence officer in British India before resigning in protest at British policies. He later traveled extensively in the Arabian Peninsula, becoming a close adviser to Ibn Saud, the founder of Saudi Arabia. Philby's writings on the region, particularly his book "The Empty Quarter," helped to shape Western understanding of the Arabian Peninsula.

title: John Robert Seeley
text: John Robert Seeley (1834-1895) was a British historian and political theorist. A Regius Professor of Modern History at the University of Cambridge, he is known for his analysis of British imperialism in "The Expansion of England" (1883). Seeley argued that the British Empire was not merely a collection of colonies but an organic whole that had evolved over centuries. He believed that the empire was a vital part of British identity and a source of national strength. Seeley's ideas influenced the development of British imperial policy in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

title: Ted Danson
text: Ted Danson (born December 29, 1947) is an American actor and producer. He is known for his roles as Sam Malone on the NBC sitcom Cheers, Jack Holden on the HBO comedy-drama series Becker, and Michael Westen on the USA Network action-comedy series Burn Notice. Danson has received 17 Primetime Emmy Award nominations, winning twice for Cheers and Becker. He has also won two Golden Globe Awards for Cheers.

title: Quokka
text: The quokka is a small marsupial native to southwestern Australia. It is known for its short, dense fur, large feet, and friendly demeanor. Quokkas are often called the "happiest animal in the world" because of their constant smiles. Quokkas are herbivores and feed on a variety of plants and grasses. They live in social groups and can often be seen grooming each other or playing. Quokkas are also known for their agility and can often be seen leaping around in the bushes.

title: Fallbrook, California
text: Fallbrook is a city in San Diego County, California, United States, located in the northern coastal region of the county. With a population of approximately 31,000, it is known for its rural character and agricultural industry, particularly its avocado and citrus groves. Fallbrook is home to several historical landmarks, including the historic Fallbrook Inn and the Mission San Luis Rey de Francia. It also offers recreational opportunities such as hiking, biking, and horseback riding in the nearby Cleveland National Forest.

title: Lenzburg
text: Lenzburg is a municipality in the district of Lenzburg in the canton of Aargau in Switzerland. It is located on the banks of the Aare river, about 25 kilometers west of Zurich. Lenzburg is a historic town, with its origins dating back to the early Middle Ages. The town's most famous landmark is Lenzburg Castle, which was built in the 11th century and is now a museum. Lenzburg is also home to several other historical buildings, including the Town Hall, which was built in the 16th century, and the Reformed Church, which was built in the 18th century.

title: Tadao Ando
text: Tadao Ando (born September 13, 1941) is a Japanese architect. Known for his minimalist approach and use of natural materials, Ando's designs often feature concrete structures that harmonize with their surroundings. His notable works include the Church on the Water (1988), the Pulitzer Arts Foundation (2001), and the Chichu Art Museum (2004). Ando has received numerous awards for his work, including the Pritzker Architecture Prize in 1995. He continues to practice architecture and design spaces that celebrate the interplay between light, form, and nature.

title: Tom Coburn
text: Tom Coburn (March 14, 1948 – March 28, 2020) was an American physician and politician. A member of the Republican Party, he served as a United States Senator from Oklahoma from 2005 to 2015. Coburn was a conservative and a fiscal hawk, known for his opposition to pork barrel spending and his efforts to reduce the federal deficit. He retired from the Senate in 2015 due to health reasons and died from prostate cancer in 2020.

title: Richard I of England
text: Richard I, known as Richard the Lionheart, was King of England from 1189 to 1199. He is remembered primarily for his role as a leader of the Third Crusade. Before becoming king, he joined the French forces resisting King Henry II of England, his father. After his succession to the English throne, Richard spent little time in England, instead fighting in France and on crusade. His nickname, Cœur de Lion ("Lionheart") reflects his reputation as a brave and skilled military leader.

title: Zafirlukast
text: Zafirlukast is a medication used to prevent symptoms of asthma. It belongs to a class of medications called leukotriene modifiers. These medications work by blocking the action of leukotrienes, which are chemicals released by the body during the allergic reaction. By blocking the action of leukotrienes, zafirlukast helps to prevent airway narrowing and inflammation. It is taken by mouth, once or twice a day. Common side effects include headache, nausea, and diarrhea.

title: Wally Schirra
text: Wally Schirra, an American naval officer and aviator, was one of the original seven astronauts selected for NASA's Mercury program. He flew on the Mercury-Atlas 8 mission, which orbited Earth six times in 1962, and commanded the Gemini 6A and Apollo 7 missions. Schirra retired from NASA in 1969 and became an author, lecturer, and businessman. He passed away in 2007 at the age of 84. Known for his wit and humor, Schirra was nicknamed "Schirra the Shirker" by his fellow astronauts.

title: Adult education
text: Adult education encompasses any form of learning that occurs beyond the traditional school years. It encompasses a wide range of activities, from formal courses and workshops to informal learning through self-study or participation in community groups. Adult education aims to improve knowledge, skills, and abilities for personal, professional, or civic development. It provides opportunities for individuals to acquire new knowledge, enhance existing skills, and pursue personal interests. Adult education plays a crucial role in promoting lifelong learning, enabling individuals to adapt to changing job markets and societal needs.

title: Book burning
text: Book burning is the intentional destruction of books, usually by burning. It is often carried out as a form of censorship or suppression of ideas. Throughout history, book burning has been used by governments, religious groups, and other organizations to remove or destroy literature that they deem objectionable or offensive. Notable examples include the burning of books in Nazi Germany and the burning of books in China during the Cultural Revolution. Book burning remains a serious problem in many parts of the world today, as it is seen as a way to silence dissenting voices and control the flow of information.

title: The Newlywed Game
text: The Newlywed Game is an American television game show in which a panel of celebrity guests attempt to predict the answers of a newlywed couple to questions about their relationship. The show was created by Chuck Barris and first aired on ABC in 1966. It has been revived several times, most recently in 2021 on TBS. The premise of the show is simple: a newlywed couple is asked a series of questions about their relationship, such as "Who is the better cook?" or "Who is more likely to get lost?" The celebrity guests then try to guess the couple's answers. The couple with the most correct answers wins a prize. The Newlywed Game has been a popular television show for over 50 years. It has been praised for its humor and its insights into the dynamics of marriage.

title: Back walkover
text: Back walkover is a gymnastic move in which the gymnast begins standing and swings their legs forward and over their head, landing on their feet with their back arched. The move is often used as a transition between other moves, such as a handstand or a cartwheel. Back walkovers can also be performed as a standalone skill.

title: Davidson's
text: Davidson's is a pharmaceutical company based in the United Kingdom. It was founded in 1947 by Scottish pharmacist Alexander Taylor Davidson. The company is known for its over-the-counter medicines, such as Davidson's Moisturising Cream and Davidson's Dental Gel. Davidson's products are available in over 50 countries worldwide. The company is headquartered in Dartford, Kent, England. Davidson's is a subsidiary of the German pharmaceutical company Stada Arzneimittel.

title: Danish language
text: The Danish language is a North Germanic language spoken by around 5.6 million people, primarily in Denmark and Southern Schleswig in Germany. It is closely related to Swedish and Norwegian, and the three languages are mutually intelligible to a high degree. Danish is an official language of Denmark, the Faroe Islands, and Greenland. It is also spoken in small communities in Norway, Sweden, Germany, the United States, and Canada. The Danish language has a rich history, dating back to the Viking Age. It has been influenced by a variety of languages, including Old Norse, Low German, and French.

title: Jock Stein
text: Jock Stein, born John Stein, was a Scottish football player and manager. As a player, he represented Albion Rovers, Hibernian, and Celtic, winning the Scottish Cup twice with Celtic. As a manager, he led Celtic to nine Scottish league titles, eight Scottish Cups, and six Scottish League Cups, as well as guiding them to victory in the 1967 European Cup, making them the first British club to win the competition. Stein also managed Scotland, leading them to qualification for the 1982 FIFA World Cup, before his untimely death on September 10, 1985.

title: Trams in Melbourne
text: Trams in Melbourne, Australia, form an extensive and iconic part of the city's public transport system. The network consists of over 250 kilometers of track, with 24 routes operating across the metropolitan area. Trams have been running in Melbourne since 1884, and their distinctive green and gold livery has become synonymous with the city. Trams play a vital role in providing an efficient and environmentally friendly mode of transport, carrying over 200 million passengers annually. Their frequent and reliable services connect major destinations, including the central business district, inner suburbs, and surrounding municipalities.

title: Ammonius Grammaticus
text: Ammonius Grammaticus, a renowned Greek grammarian and lexicographer, flourished in Alexandria during the 5th and early 6th centuries CE. He is primarily known for his monumental work, the "Onomasticon," a comprehensive lexicon that encompasses a vast array of vocabulary and terminology from various fields of knowledge. Ammonius' "Onomasticon" played a pivotal role in preserving and transmitting classical Greek literature and scholarship to future generations. His contributions to Greek grammar and lexicography have left an enduring legacy in the study of ancient Greek.

title: Bank of England
text: The Bank of England is the central bank of the United Kingdom that was established in 1694. Its functions include issuing currency, setting interest rates, and regulating and supervising the financial system. The Bank is owned by the government and is independent in its decision-making. It plays a key role in maintaining the stability of the UK economy. The Bank of England is headquartered in London and has a staff of around 4,000 people.

title: Duncan II of Scotland
text: Duncan II of Scotland, also known as Duncan the Meek, was a Scottish king who ruled from 1094 until his death in 1094. He was the son of Malcolm III and his second wife, Margaret of Wessex. Duncan's reign was a period of relative peace and prosperity, but it was also marked by conflict with his cousin, Donald Bane. Duncan was defeated and killed by Donald Bane in 1094, and Donald Bane became king in his stead.

title: Barton, Maryland
text: Barton, Maryland, is an unincorporated community in Allegany County. It is located 10 miles southwest of Cumberland, at the junction of Maryland Route 36 and Maryland Route 522. The community was originally known as Barrelville, after the barrel factory that was located there. In 1852, the name was changed to Barton, in honor of Benjamin Barton, a local landowner and businessman. Barton was a thriving community in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, with a population of over 1,000 people. However, the decline of the coal industry in the area led to a decline in population, and Barton is now a small community with a population of just over 200 people.

title: Discreet Music
text: Discreet Music is an album by Brian Eno, released in 1975. It is considered one of the first ambient music albums and has been highly influential in the development of the genre. The album consists of four long, gradually evolving pieces that create a sense of calm and tranquility. Eno used a variety of techniques to create the album's distinctive sound, including tape loops, synthesizers, and processed guitars. Discreet Music has been praised for its innovative sound and its ability to create a sense of space and atmosphere.

title: Christopher II of Denmark
text: Christopher II (29 September 1276 – 2 August 1332), of the House of Estridsen, was King of Denmark from 1320 to 1326 and again from 1329 to 1332. He was the eldest son of King Eric V Glipping and Queen Agnes of Brandenburg. His reign was marked by a civil war between him and his brother, Valdemar III, a conflict that weakened the kingdom and led to its conquest by Sweden. Christopher II spent his later years in exile in Germany, where he died in 1332.

title: William Wentworth
text: William Charles Wentworth (1790–1872) was an Australian explorer, politician, and journalist. He was a leading figure in the movement for responsible government in New South Wales. In 1813, he explored the Blue Mountains, opening up the vast interior of Australia to European settlement. He also played a key role in the founding of the University of Sydney. Wentworth was a controversial figure, but he was also a brilliant orator and a tireless advocate for the rights of the Australian people.

title: Alfred Jarry
text: Alfred Jarry (1873–1907) was a French writer, humorist, and playwright. He is best known for his play "Ubu Roi" (1896), a satirical masterpiece that created the grotesque, antiheroic character Ubu. Jarry's work was influenced by Symbolism, Absurdism, and the avant-garde. He was an important figure in the development of French theater and literature. His writings are characterized by their irreverence, absurdity, and poetic imagery.

title: Ontario
text: Ontario, the most populous province of Canada, lies in the country's east-central region. With a population of over 15 million, Ontario is home to multicultural urban centers like Toronto, Ottawa, and Hamilton. The province boasts a diverse landscape spanning from the Great Lakes in the south to the Canadian Shield in the north. Major industries include manufacturing, financial services, and tourism. Ontario's capital city, Toronto, is a global financial and cultural hub, hosting the iconic CN Tower and the Royal Ontario Museum.

title: Lake Cavanaugh, Washington
text: Lake Cavanaugh is a lake in the U.S. state of Washington. It is located in the Cascade Mountains, approximately 50 miles (80 km) northeast of Seattle. The lake is a popular destination for recreation, including fishing, boating, and camping. It is also home to a variety of wildlife, including bald eagles, osprey, and deer. The lake was formed by the retreat of glaciers during the last ice age. It is fed by several small streams and rivers, and its outlet is the South Fork of the Stillaguamish River.

title: Pale Rider
text: Pale Rider is a 1985 American Western film directed by Clint Eastwood, who also stars in the title role as a mysterious preacher who arrives in a gold mining town to avenge the death of a friend. The film is loosely based on the 1975 novel "The Pale Rider" by William Goldman. The supporting cast includes Michael Moriarty, Carrie Snodgress, and Richard Dysart. Pale Rider was a critical and commercial success, grossing over $41 million against a production budget of $6.6 million. It was nominated for two Academy Awards, including Best Cinematography.

title: Hudson Institute
text: The Hudson Institute is a conservative American think tank based in Washington, D.C. Founded in 1961 by Herman Kahn, the institute conducts research and analysis on a wide range of public policy issues, including national security, international relations, economic policy, and social policy. The Hudson Institute is known for its influential publications, such as "The Coming War with Japan" and "The Nuclear Age: Strategy, Doctrine, and Diplomacy." The institute has been criticized for its close ties to the military-industrial complex and its support for US interventionism around the world.

title: Chorath
text: Chorath is a town in the Kannur district of Kerala, India. It is located on the banks of the Valapattanam River, about 25 kilometers from Kannur city. Chorath is known for its beautiful beaches, such as Muzhappilangad Beach, which is the longest drive-in beach in Asia. The town is also home to several historical sites, including the Chorath Siva Temple and the Pazhassi Raja Fort. Chorath is a popular tourist destination, and it offers a variety of activities for visitors, including swimming, sunbathing, fishing, and boating.

title: On the Origin of Species
text: "On the Origin of Species", published in 1859, is a seminal work by Charles Darwin that revolutionized our understanding of evolution. In this book, Darwin introduced his theory of natural selection, which posits that organisms with advantageous traits are more likely to survive and reproduce, passing on their traits to their offspring. The result is the gradual accumulation of advantageous traits within a population, leading to the evolution of new species. Darwin's work sparked a heated debate and remains a cornerstone of modern evolutionary theory.

title: History of Germany (1945–90)
text: The post-World War II history of Germany is characterized by the division of the country into East and West Germany, the reconstruction and economic recovery of West Germany, and the political and economic stagnation of East Germany. The Federal Republic of Germany (West Germany) was founded in 1949, and the German Democratic Republic (East Germany) was founded in 1949. The two German states were reunited in 1990.

title: Adaptive Transform Acoustic Coding
text: Adaptive Transform Acoustic Coding (ATRAC) is a lossy audio coding format developed by Sony. It was first introduced in 1992 and has been used in a variety of Sony products, including the MiniDisc, PlayStation Portable, and Walkman. ATRAC uses a perceptual audio coding algorithm to reduce the size of audio files while maintaining a high level of audio quality. ATRAC files are typically smaller than MP3 files of the same quality, but they may not be as compatible with all devices.

title: Red-bellied woodpecker
text: The red-bellied woodpecker (Melanerpes carolinus) is a medium-sized woodpecker found in eastern North America. It is 20–23 cm (7.9–9.1 in) long with a wingspan of 34–43 cm (13–17 in). The adult has a black back, white rump, and white underparts. The male has a red crown and nape, while the female has a gray crown and nape. The red-bellied woodpecker is a common resident of deciduous and mixed forests. It is a non-migratory bird that can be found in the same area year-round.

title: Mosquero, New Mexico
text: Mosquero is a village in San Miguel County, New Mexico, United States. The population was 87 at the 2010 census. It was founded in 1886 as a stop on the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway, and was named after the nearby Mosquero Creek. The village is located in the dry grassland region of eastern New Mexico, and the economy is based on ranching and agriculture. Mosquero is home to the Mosquero School, which serves grades K-12, and the Mosquero Public Library. The village is also a popular destination for bird watching, with several species of migratory birds stopping in the area during the spring and fall.

title: Vasbert Drakes
text: Vasbert Drakes (born 1956) is a former West Indian cricketer who played seven Tests and 34 One Day Internationals for the West Indies between 1981 and 1994. A right-handed middle-order batsman, Drakes was renowned for his aggressive batting style. He made his Test debut in 1981 against Australia and scored a century in his second Test, against Pakistan in 1982. He was also a useful bowler, taking 23 wickets in Tests at an average of 36.52.

title: George Wyndham
text: George Wyndham (1863-1913), British statesman and author, was an important figure in the Conservative Party. He served as Under-Secretary of State for War (1898-1900) and Chief Secretary for Ireland (1900-1905). Wyndham played a key role in the development of the Irish Land Acts, which aimed to improve the lives of Irish tenant farmers. He was also a prolific writer, publishing poetry, fiction, and essays on political and literary topics. Wyndham's untimely death at the age of 49 cut short a promising career.

title: Joseon
text: Joseon, also known as the Chosŏn dynasty, was a Korean kingdom that ruled the Korean Peninsula from 1392 to 1910. It was founded by Yi Seong-gye, who overthrew the Goryeo dynasty and established a new capital in Seoul. During the Joseon period, Korea experienced significant cultural and economic development, including the invention of the Korean alphabet Hangeul.

title: Small Faces
text: The Small Faces were an English mod and psychedelic rock band from London. They were formed in 1965 and disbanded in 1969. The band consisted of Steve Marriott (vocals, guitar), Ronnie Lane (bass guitar, vocals), Kenney Jones (drums), and Ian McLagan (keyboards, vocals). The Small Faces are best known for their hit singles "Itchycoo Park" and "Lazy Sunday", both of which reached number one on the UK Singles Chart. They also released a number of successful albums, including "Ogden's Nut Gone Flake" and "Small Faces". After the band broke up, Marriott went on to form Humble Pie, while Lane and McLagan formed Faces.

title: Imperial Chemical Industries
text: Imperial Chemical Industries (ICI) was a British multinational chemical company which began in 1926 with the merger of four leading British chemical companies. During the 1920s, ICI rapidly expanded, establishing operations in several countries and becoming one of the world's largest chemical companies. In 1971, ICI built the largest single chemicals complex in the world at Wilton, Teesside, England. ICI was a major producer of a wide range of chemicals, including petrochemicals, fertilizers, plastics, and paints. In 1992, ICI merged with Zeneca Group to form Zeneca, which was later acquired by AstraZeneca in 2000.

title: IEEE 802.11
text: IEEE 802.11 is a set of standards for wireless local area networks (WLANs) from the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE). It is commonly known as Wi-Fi. IEEE 802.11 defines the physical layer (PHY) and medium access control (MAC) layer for WLANs. The PHY layer specifies the modulation and coding schemes used for data transmission, while the MAC layer defines the protocols for accessing the wireless medium and managing data transmission. The most common IEEE 802.11 standards are: 802.11a: Uses the 5 GHz frequency band and offers speeds up to 54 Mbps. 802.11b: Uses the 2.4 GHz frequency band and offers speeds up to 11 Mbps. 802.11g: Uses the 2.4 GHz frequency band and offers speeds up to 54 Mbps. 802.11n: Uses the 2.4 GHz and 5 GHz frequency bands and offers speeds up to 600 Mbps. 802.11ac: Uses the 5 GHz frequency band and offers speeds up to 3.46 Gbps.

title: Moorland, Kentucky
text: Moorland is a census-designated place (CDP) in Jefferson County, Kentucky, United States. The population was 444 at the 2010 census. Moorland is located in eastern Jefferson County, south of Louisville. The community is bordered by Hurstbourne to the north, Middletown to the east, and Douglass Hills to the south.

title: Dara Ó Briain
text: Dara Ó Briain (born 19 February 1972) is an Irish comedian, television presenter, and writer. Born in Dublin, he began his comedy career in the late 1990s, and has since become one of the most popular comedians in the UK and Ireland. Ó Briain is known for his sharp wit and observational humor, and has hosted several popular television shows, including "Mock the Week", "The Panel", and "Stargazing Live". He has also written several books, including "Tickling the English" and "Quantum Physics for Beginners".

title: Ansbach
text: Ansbach is a city and former capital of the principality of Ansbach in Bavaria, Germany. It is located on the Rezat river, 40 kilometers southwest of Nuremberg. Ansbach was first mentioned in 748. In the 14th century, it became the residence of the Hohenzollern counts of Ansbach. In 1791, Ansbach was ceded to Prussia. It remained part of Prussia until 1806 when it was annexed by Bavaria. Today, Ansbach is a prosperous city with a population of around 40,000. It is home to several historic buildings, including the Residenz Ansbach, a Baroque palace that was once the residence of the Hohenzollern counts.

title: Monroe Township, Middlesex County, New Jersey
text: Monroe Township is a township in Middlesex County, New Jersey, United States. As of the 2020 United States census, the township's population was 47,723, an increase of 4,976 (+11.7%) from the 2010 census count of 42,747, which in turn reflected an increase of 10,254 (+31.3%) from the 32,493 counted in the 2000 census.

title: AMC Gremlin
text: The AMC Gremlin is a subcompact automobile manufactured and marketed by American Motors Corporation (AMC) from 1970 to 1978. Introduced in April 1970, the Gremlin was AMC's first subcompact and was based on the rear-wheel drive AMC Hornet. It was the first American-made subcompact with a six-cylinder engine as standard equipment and the first to offer a factory-installed sunroof. Despite its distinctive appearance and innovative features, the Gremlin was not a commercial success, with only 671,475 units produced over its eight-year production run.

title: Chalkyitsik, Alaska
text: Chalkyitsik is a city in Yukon-Koyukuk Census Area, Alaska, United States. The population was 106 at the 2020 census, down from 125 in 2010. Chalkyitsik is located on the Koyukuk River, which is a tributary of the Yukon River. The name "Chalkyitsik" is derived from the Koyukon Athabaskan language and means "place where fish are plentiful."

title: Saint Leo University
text: Saint Leo University is a private, Catholic university located in the Tampa Bay area of Florida. Founded in 1889 by the Benedictine monks of Saint Leo Abbey, the university is the oldest Catholic institution of higher learning in the state. Saint Leo offers undergraduate and graduate degrees in various fields, including liberal arts, business, education, and health sciences. The university has a strong commitment to online education, with over 80% of its students enrolled in online programs. Saint Leo is a vibrant and diverse community with a strong focus on student success. The university offers a variety of student support services, including academic advising, tutoring, and career counseling. Saint Leo also has a number of active student clubs and organizations, providing students with opportunities for leadership and involvement.

title: Cuthbert
text: Saint Cuthbert (c. 634–687 AD) was a Celtic monk and hermit who lived in Northumbria, England. He was a great evangelist and missionary, and his work helped to spread Christianity throughout the region. He was also a skilled craftsman and artist, and many of his works are still preserved today. Cuthbert was a man of great faith and devotion, and he is considered one of the most important saints in the history of the Church in England.

title: Morehouse, New York
text: Morehouse is a town in Hamilton County, New York, United States, with a population of approximately 900 residents. The town is located in the southern portion of the county, approximately 35 miles northeast of the city of Binghamton. Morehouse is a rural community with a rich history dating back to the early 19th century. The town was named after Daniel Morehouse, an early settler who built a saw and grist mill in the area. The town's economy has historically been based on agriculture and logging, and it remains a small but vibrant community today.

title: Anti-nuclear antibody
text: Anti-nuclear antibodies (ANA) are a type of autoantibody that reacts against components of the cell nucleus. They are found in various autoimmune diseases, including systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis, and Sjogren's syndrome. ANA can target a wide range of nuclear antigens, including DNA, histones, and RNA polymerase. The presence of ANA in the blood is a hallmark of autoimmune disease and can aid in diagnosis. Different patterns of ANA staining on laboratory tests can provide clues to the underlying autoimmune condition. Treatment for ANA-associated autoimmune diseases focuses on managing inflammation and preventing tissue damage.

title: Gary Dourdan
text: Gary Dourdan (born December 19, 1966) is an American actor. He is best known for his role as Warrick Brown on the CBS crime drama CSI: Crime Scene Investigation (2000–2008). Dourdan has also appeared in films such as Alien: Resurrection (1997), Along Came a Spider (2001), and Cabin Fever (2002). In recent years, he has starred in the BET series Being Mary Jane (2013–2019). Dourdan has been open about his struggles with drug addiction and has been arrested several times for drug-related offenses.

title: Sebastian Coe
text: Sebastian Coe, Baron Coe, is a British politician, former athlete, and sports administrator. He is currently the President of World Athletics, the international governing body for athletics. Coe won four Olympic medals, including two gold medals, in the 1500 meters and 800 meters events. He set eight world records in middle-distance running events and was voted BBC Sports Personality of the Year in 1979 and 1981. After retiring from athletics, Coe became a politician, serving as a Conservative member of Parliament from 1992 to 2005. He was appointed a life peer in 2000.

title: Pequots
text: The Pequots are a Native American people originally based in southeastern Connecticut. They are one of the Algonquian-speaking peoples, and their language is closely related to the languages of the Mohegans, Narragansetts, and Wampanoags. The Pequots were once a powerful tribe, but their population was decimated by disease and warfare in the 17th century. Today, there are about 2,000 Pequots living in Connecticut and Rhode Island.

title: Norwalk, Iowa
text: Norwalk is a city in Warren County, Iowa, United States. It is part of the Des Moines–West Des Moines Metropolitan Statistical Area. The population was 8,940 at the 2020 census. Norwalk was founded in 1855 and named after Norwalk, Connecticut. The city is home to the Norwalk Historical Museum, which houses a collection of artifacts and documents related to the city's history. Norwalk is also known for its annual Sweet Corn Festival, which is held in August.

title: Creation and annihilation operators
text: In quantum mechanics, creation and annihilation operators are operators that, respectively, create or annihilate a single quantum of excitation in a quantized field. They are essential tools for describing the behavior of bosons and fermions, which are particles that obey Bose-Einstein statistics and Fermi-Dirac statistics, respectively. Creation and annihilation operators are used to construct the Fock space, which is the Hilbert space of a system of non-interacting bosons or fermions.

title: Simon Cowell
text: Simon Cowell is an English television personality, entrepreneur, and record executive. He gained public recognition as a judge on the British television music competition series Pop Idol (2001–2003) and its spin-off American Idol (2002–2010). He later created The X Factor and Got Talent franchises. Cowell has also worked as a record producer and has managed several successful music acts, including Westlife, Leona Lewis, and One Direction. Cowell is known for his sharp wit and critical comments, which have made him a polarizing figure in the entertainment industry.

title: Reserve Bank of Australia
text: The Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) is Australia's central bank, responsible for managing the nation's monetary and banking system. It is responsible for issuing banknotes, managing the Australian dollar, setting interest rates, and regulating the financial industry. The RBA's primary objective is to maintain price stability and promote sustainable economic growth. It was established in 1924 and is headquartered in Sydney. The RBA is led by a board of directors appointed by the Australian government, and is independent in its decision-making.

title: List of Mortal Kombat characters
text: The Mortal Kombat fighting game franchise features a diverse cast of characters, each with unique abilities, fighting styles, and motivations. Some of the most iconic characters in the series include: Scorpion: A vengeful specter seeking revenge against his killer, Sub-Zero. Sub-Zero: A cryomancer who wields ice-based abilities and seeks redemption for his past actions. Raiden: The thunder god who protects Earthrealm from evil. Liu Kang: A Shaolin monk and Earthrealm's champion. Johnny Cage: A Hollywood actor and martial artist who brings humor and bravado to the fight.

title: John F. Kennedy Stadium (Philadelphia)
text: John F. Kennedy Stadium, formerly known as Municipal Stadium, is a former American football stadium in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. It was built in 1926 and hosted its first football game in 1927. The stadium has a capacity of 102,796 and was the home field of the Philadelphia Eagles of the National Football League (NFL) from 1958 to 1970. It also hosted the Army-Navy Game from 1936 to 1979 and the Penn Quakers football team from 1958 to 1996. The stadium was demolished in 1992 and the site is now occupied by a Walmart store.

title: FC St. Pauli
text: FC St. Pauli, founded in 1910, is a German football club based in the St. Pauli district of Hamburg. The club is known for its unique fan culture, which emphasizes social justice, anti-fascism, and left-wing political ideals. In addition to its football team, St. Pauli has departments for handball, basketball, and other sports. Despite its limited success on the pitch, St. Pauli has a large and passionate fan base, both in Hamburg and beyond. The club is seen as a symbol of resistance and a voice for the marginalized. St. Pauli has been involved in various social and political initiatives, including anti-racism campaigns and support for refugee rights.

title: Abiogenic petroleum origin
text: Abiogenic petroleum origin is a hypothesis that suggests that petroleum can be formed from inorganic materials, such as carbon dioxide and water, without the involvement of biological processes. This hypothesis differs from the widely accepted biogenic origin of petroleum, which posits that petroleum is formed from the remains of ancient plants and animals. While the abiogenic origin hypothesis has been around for centuries, it has gained renewed attention in recent years due to the discovery of petroleum in places where biological processes are unlikely to have occurred.

title: The Nature of Things
text: The Nature of Things is a Canadian television documentary series created by David Suzuki. The series explores a wide range of scientific, environmental, and social issues. The series has been broadcast in over 100 countries and has been translated into 34 languages. The Nature of Things has won numerous awards, including eight Gemini Awards and two Peabody Awards.

title: Criminal record
text: A criminal record, also known as a criminal history or rap sheet, is a repository of information about an individual's criminal convictions and other interactions with the criminal justice system. It typically includes details such as the offenses committed, the dates of convictions, the sentences imposed, and any other relevant information. Criminal records are maintained by law enforcement agencies and are used for a variety of purposes, including background checks, sentencing decisions, and parole eligibility determinations.

title: Allen County, Ohio
text: Allen County is a county located in the northwestern part of the U.S. state of Ohio. As of the 2020 census, its population was 104,453. The county seat is Lima. Allen County was formed in 1833 and named after Colonel John Allen, a soldier in the War of 1812. The county is home to a diverse economy, including agriculture, manufacturing, and healthcare. It is also home to several colleges and universities, including Ohio Northern University and the University of Northwestern Ohio.

title: Metro-land
text: Metro-land was a marketing campaign launched by the Metropolitan Railway in 1915 to promote its services and encourage development in the suburban areas it served. The campaign created a romanticized image of the countryside accessible by train from London, depicting it as a place of fresh air, leisure, and affordable housing. Metro-land became synonymous with the suburbs and influenced the development of towns and villages along the railway lines. The campaign's success led to the expansion of the Metropolitan Railway and the creation of new residential areas, transforming the landscape of Greater London.

title: Boise State University
text: Boise State University (BSU) is a public research university in Boise, Idaho. Founded in 1932 as a junior college, it became a four-year institution in 1965 and gained university status in 1974. BSU offers undergraduate and graduate programs in a wide range of disciplines, including business, education, engineering, and health sciences. The university is known for its strong athletic programs, particularly its football team, which plays in the Football Bowl Subdivision. BSU's campus is located in central Boise and features modern academic buildings, residence halls, and athletic facilities.

title: Rennert, North Carolina
text: Rennert is an unincorporated community in Robeson County, North Carolina, United States. The community is located along North Carolina Highway 211, 10 miles (16 km) southwest of Lumberton, the county seat. Rennert is home to the Rennert School, a public elementary school, and the Rennert Methodist Church. The community was founded in 1888 by a group of German immigrants, and it was named after one of the original settlers, George Washington Rennert.

title: British Columbia Liberal Party
text: The British Columbia Liberal Party is a free enterprise, centre-right political party in British Columbia, Canada. It is the current governing party in the province, having formed government after the 2001 provincial election. The party's platform is based on fiscal conservatism, social liberalism, and environmental sustainability. The party's leader is Kevin Falcon.

title: Ernst Lindemann
text: Ernst Lindemann was a German physician and psychiatrist. He is best known for his work on the concept of "grief work" and the "Lindemann Curve", which describes the stages of grief after a loss. Lindemann believed that grief was a normal process that could be facilitated by allowing the bereaved to express their emotions and work through their loss. His work has been influential in the field of grief counseling.

title: Wake
text: Wake is a state of consciousness that occurs between sleep and full wakefulness. It is characterized by reduced awareness of the surroundings, slow reaction times, and difficulty in concentrating. Wakefulness is an active process that requires conscious effort, while sleep is a passive process that occurs without conscious effort. Wakefulness is essential for normal functioning, as it allows us to interact with our environment and respond to stimuli.

title: Ectopic pregnancy
text: Ectopic pregnancy occurs when a fertilized egg implants outside the uterus. The most common site is the fallopian tube, but it can also occur in the ovary, cervix, or abdomen. Symptoms may include vaginal bleeding, abdominal pain, and shoulder pain. Treatment typically involves medication or surgery to remove the ectopic pregnancy. Ectopic pregnancies can be life-threatening if not treated promptly. Risk factors include a history of pelvic inflammatory disease, previous ectopic pregnancy, and use of an intrauterine device (IUD).

title: Canadian Coast Guard
text: The Canadian Coast Guard (CCG) is a Canadian federal agency responsible for maritime safety, security, and environmental protection in Canadian waters. It is part of the Department of Fisheries and Oceans. The CCG provides a wide range of services including search and rescue, icebreaking, environmental response, and aids to navigation. It operates a fleet of over 120 vessels and 10 aircraft, and employs over 6,000 people. The CCG has a long and proud history, dating back to the early 19th century. It has played a vital role in the development of Canada's maritime industry and continues to be an essential part of the country's transportation system.

title: Aaron V. Brown
text: Aaron V. Brown (1892–1984) was an American electrical engineer and professor. He was a pioneer in the field of electrical power systems and made significant contributions to the development of power system analysis and control techniques. Brown was born in Oskaloosa, Iowa, and received his electrical engineering degree from Iowa State College in 1913. He then worked for the General Electric Company for several years before joining the faculty of the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in 1923. Brown's research focused on the stability and control of power systems. He developed several new methods for analyzing power system stability and developed new techniques for controlling power system voltage and frequency. He also made significant contributions to the field of power system protection.

title: Talc
text: Talc is a naturally occurring mineral composed of hydrated magnesium silicate. It has a soft, soapy feel and is widely used in various industries. Talc is primarily employed in the production of paper, paints, ceramics, and cosmetics. The cosmetic industry utilizes talc as an ingredient in face powders, baby powders, and body powders due to its ability to absorb moisture and reduce friction.

title: Fatigue (material)
text: Fatigue is the weakening of a material caused by repeated loading and unloading. It is a gradual process that can eventually lead to failure. Fatigue strength is the maximum stress that a material can withstand before failing due to fatigue. Fatigue life is the number of cycles to failure for a given stress level. Fatigue is a major concern in many engineering applications, particularly in aerospace, automotive, and civil engineering. Fatigue failures can be catastrophic, leading to loss of life and property. Fatigue analysis is used to predict the fatigue life of a material and to design components that are resistant to fatigue failure.

title: Communes of France
text: Communes are the basic administrative units of France. There are over 35,000 communes, each with its own elected mayor and municipal council. Communes are responsible for a wide range of local services, including education, water and sanitation, and public transportation. They also play an important role in the preservation of French culture and heritage. The largest commune in France is Paris, with a population of over 2 million. The smallest commune is Rochefourchat, with a population of just 1 person. Communes are grouped together into departments, which are then grouped into regions.

title: Misplaced Childhood
text: Misplaced Childhood refers to the loss of childhood experiences due to circumstances beyond a child's control. This can include exposure to trauma, poverty, or familial dysfunction. Children who experience a misplaced childhood may face challenges in developing social, emotional, and cognitive skills, as well as an increased risk for mental health issues. Factors contributing to misplaced childhood include abuse, neglect, parental substance use, and chronic poverty. Addressing these issues requires a comprehensive approach involving social, educational, and mental health interventions.

title: Figure skating at the 1998 Winter Olympics
text: Figure skating at the 1998 Winter Olympics was held at the White Ring in Nagano, Japan. The events were held from February 8 to 20, 1998. Four events were contested: men's singles, women's singles, pair skating, and ice dancing. Russian skaters dominated the competition, winning three of the four gold medals. Ilia Kulik won the men's singles, Tara Lipinski won the women's singles, and Oksana Kazakova and Artur Dmitriev won the pair skating. The ice dancing title was won by the French duo Marina Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat.

title: Caucasian Albania
text: Caucasian Albania was an ancient kingdom in the eastern Caucasus region, located in what is now Azerbaijan and southern Dagestan, Russia. Founded in the 4th century BC, Albania played a significant role in the political and cultural development of the Caucasus. It adopted Zoroastrianism as its official religion and developed a distinct alphabet, the Caucasian Albanian alphabet. Albania's strategic location made it a target for conquest, and it was successively ruled by the Persians, Greeks, Romans, and Arabs. In the 8th century AD, Albania was conquered by the Khazars and subsequently absorbed into the Arab Caliphate.

title: Lagro, Indiana
text: Lagro is a town in Wabash County, Indiana, United States. The population was 415 at the 2010 census. The town was laid out in 1836 and named after Lagro, an early settler. Lagro is located along the Wabash River and is home to the Lagro Lock and Dam. The dam was built in 1914 and is one of the oldest dams on the Wabash River.

title: Ontario Film Review Board
text: The Ontario Film Review Board (OFRB) is an independent agency of the Government of Ontario, Canada, responsible for classifying and rating films, videos, and DVDs. The OFRB was established in 1968 and is headquartered in Toronto. The board consists of 13 members who are appointed by the Lieutenant Governor in Council. The OFRB's mandate is to protect children and youth from exposure to harmful or inappropriate content. The board classifies films, videos, and DVDs into one of five categories: G (General), PG (Parental Guidance), 14A (14 years and over), 18A (18 years and over), and R (Restricted).

title: NeWS
text: NeWS (Network Extensible Window System) was an early windowing system developed by Sun Microsystems in the mid-1980s. It was designed as a network-transparent system, allowing windows from different hosts to be displayed on the same screen. NeWS was also notable for its early support for PostScript, a page description language that became widely used in desktop publishing. Although NeWS was technically advanced, it never gained widespread acceptance. One reason was its high cost, as it required expensive hardware to run smoothly. Another reason was the rise of the X Window System, which was a more open and flexible system that quickly became the de facto standard for Unix-based graphical user interfaces.

title: Wireless Internet service provider
text: A wireless internet service provider (WISP) is a company that offers internet access to customers using wireless technology. Unlike wired internet providers that use cables to deliver internet, WISPs use radio waves to transmit data. This allows them to provide internet access to areas that are not served by wired broadband, such as rural or sparsely populated areas. WISPs typically use a variety of technologies to deliver internet access, including Wi-Fi, WiMAX, and satellite.

title: Vince Ditrich
text: Vince Ditrich (born October 24, 1973) is an American country music singer-songwriter. He has released six studio albums and has charted 11 singles on the Billboard Country Airplay chart. His highest-charting single, "Ain't in It for the Money," reached number 14 in 2004. Ditrich has written songs for other artists, including Tim McGraw and George Strait. He has also starred in the reality television show "Nashville Star."

title: Madrigal comedy
text: Madrigal comedy is a genre of musical theater that developed in Italy during the Renaissance and Baroque periods. Madrigals, the primary musical form used in these comedies, are polyphonic vocal compositions characterized by their intricate harmonies and complex rhythms. Madrigal comedies typically feature plots that are lighthearted and humorous, often involving romantic entanglements, mistaken identities, and social satire. They often incorporate elements of dance and spectacle, as well as spoken dialogue. Some of the most famous madrigal comedies include "La Pellegrina" by Adriano Banchieri (1599) and "L'Amfiparnaso" by Orazio Vecchi (1597).

title: Mountain View, California
text: Mountain View, California is a city in the San Francisco Bay Area, located in Santa Clara County. It is bordered by Los Altos, Los Altos Hills, Palo Alto, Sunnyvale, and Cupertino. With a population of around 82,000, Mountain View is the third-largest city in Santa Clara County. It is home to several major technology companies, including Google, YouTube, and LinkedIn. The city is also known for its vibrant downtown area, which features numerous restaurants, shops, and cultural attractions.

title: Midnight Run
text: Midnight Run is a 1988 American action comedy film directed by Martin Brest and starring Robert De Niro and Charles Grodin. The film follows a bounty hunter, Jack Walsh (De Niro), who is tasked with tracking down a mob accountant, Jonathan "The Duke" Mardukas (Grodin). Walsh and Mardukas form an unlikely bond during their journey, and Walsh eventually decides to protect Mardukas from the mobsters who are after him. Midnight Run was a critical and commercial success, grossing over $100 million worldwide. It was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay.

title: Oklahoma Territory
text: Oklahoma Territory was an organized incorporated territory of the United States that existed from May 2, 1890, to November 16, 1907, when it was admitted to the Union as the State of Oklahoma. The territory was created from the western part of Indian Territory and the public land in the Panhandle of Texas, which was added to the United States after the Texas–New Mexico border dispute. The territory's capital was Guthrie. Oklahoma Territory was a popular destination for settlers, and its population grew rapidly in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.

title: Henry Taylor (dramatist)
text: Henry Taylor (1800-1886) was a British dramatist, civil servant, and poet. He was born in Bishopwearmouth, Durham, and educated at Trinity College, Cambridge. After graduating, he entered the Colonial Office, where he eventually rose to the position of Permanent Under-Secretary of State. Taylor is best known for his plays, which are characterized by their intellectual content and their use of blank verse. His most famous play is "Philip van Artevelde" (1834), a historical drama about the Flemish rebellion against French rule. He also wrote several other plays, including "Edwin the Fair" (1842) and "St. Clement's Eve" (1862).

title: Electoral system of Australia
text: Australia's electoral system is based on a preferential voting system known as instant-runoff voting (IRV). Voters rank candidates in order of preference, with the candidate receiving the majority of first-preference votes winning the election. If no candidate receives a majority, the candidate with the fewest first-preference votes is eliminated, and their votes are redistributed to the remaining candidates based on the next preferences indicated on the ballot. This process continues until one candidate has a majority. This system ensures that the elected candidate has the support of the majority of voters.

title: Roatán
text: Roatán is the largest of the Bay Islands off the northern coast of Honduras. It is about 65 kilometers long and 8 kilometers wide, and has a population of around 100,000 people. The main town on the island is Coxen Hole, and the official language is Spanish. Roatán is known for its beautiful beaches, coral reefs, and diving opportunities. The island is also a popular destination for cruise ships.

title: Water frame
text: The water frame, also known as the spinning jenny, was a machine that transformed the production of cotton thread. Invented by Richard Arkwright in 1769, it revolutionized the textile industry. The water frame used rollers and spindles powered by water to draw and twist cotton fibers into yarn. This automated process increased yarn production efficiency, enabling manufacturers to produce large quantities of cotton thread at a lower cost. The water frame played a pivotal role in the Industrial Revolution, contributing to the rise of factories and the mechanization of production.

title: IChat
text: iChat was an instant messaging, file transfer, and video chat client developed by Apple Inc. for macOS and iOS. It was based on the Jabber instant messaging protocol and was first released in 2002 as part of the Mac OS X v10.2 Jaguar operating system. iChat supported text messaging, file transfers, and video conferencing, and could be integrated with other Apple applications such as Address Book and iCal. iChat was discontinued in 2012, with its features being integrated into the Messages app in macOS and iOS.

title: Uniontown, Alabama
text: Uniontown is a city in Perry County, Alabama, United States. It is located near the center of the county, at the junction of State Route 14 and State Route 5. Uniontown was incorporated in 1837. As of the 2020 census, the population of the city was 2,701. The city has a total area of 9.1 square miles (23.6 km2).

title: Barbarian
text: Barbarian is a 2022 American horror film directed by Zach Cregger and written by Cregger and Robb Savage. It stars Georgina Campbell, Bill Skarsgård, Justin Long, Matthew Patrick Davis, and Richard Brake. The film follows a young woman who rents a house for a weekend getaway, only to find herself sharing it with a strange, unsettling man. Barbarian received generally positive reviews from critics, with praise for its performances, direction, and original premise. The film was a box office success, grossing over $45 million worldwide.

title: Gertrude Bell
text: Gertrude Bell (1868-1926) was a British explorer, archaeologist, and political officer. She played a significant role in shaping the political boundaries of the Middle East after World War I. Bell traveled extensively throughout the region, documenting archaeological sites and assisting with the establishment of modern states. Her knowledge of the region and its people made her influential in shaping British policy in the Middle East, and she became known as "the uncrowned Queen of Iraq." Bell's legacy includes contributions to archaeology, diplomacy, and the understanding of Middle Eastern culture and history.

title: Ben Dunkelman
text: Ben Dunkelman (born March 20, 1989) is an American professional basketball player for Hapoel Gilboa Galil of the Israeli Basketball Premier League. He played college basketball for the University of Michigan. A 6 ft 7 in (2.01 m) forward, he was an honorable mention All-Big Ten selection in 2010 and 2011. After going undrafted in the 2011 NBA draft, he played professionally in Israel, Finland, Italy, Russia, and Spain. Dunkelman returned to Israel in 2022.

title: Beam (structure)
text: A beam is a structural element that is designed to withstand loads primarily by resisting bending. Beams are typically used in buildings, bridges, and other structures to support floors, roofs, and other loads. They can be made of a variety of materials, including wood, steel, concrete, and composite materials. Beams are classified according to their shape and the way they are supported. Common types of beams include: - Simple beams: These beams are supported at both ends and are subjected to loads that are applied between the supports. - Cantilever beams: These beams are supported at only one end and are subjected to loads that are applied at the unsupported end. - Continuous beams: These beams are supported at more than two points and are subjected to loads that are applied between the supports.

title: The Empire (Warhammer)
text: The Empire is a fictional nation in the Warhammer Fantasy setting. It is a vast and ancient realm located in the Old World, and is home to a diverse population of humans, dwarves, elves, and halflings. The Empire is ruled by the Emperor, who is chosen by the Elector Counts, the leaders of the Empire's provinces. The Empire is constantly at war with its enemies, including the Orcs, Goblins, Skaven, and Chaos. The Empire's army is one of the most powerful in the Old World, and is known for its disciplined infantry, skilled cavalry, and powerful artillery.

title: Millersburg, Pennsylvania
text: Millersburg is a borough in Dauphin County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located on the west bank of the Susquehanna River, approximately 12 miles north of Harrisburg. The borough was founded in 1764 by John Miller, a German immigrant. Millersburg was an important center for the iron industry in the 19th century. The borough is home to the Millersburg Ferry, which has been in operation since 1792. Millersburg is also the site of the Pennsylvania Military Museum.

title: Anita Mui
text: Anita Mui Yim-fong, MH (Chinese: 梅艷芳; 10 October 1963 – 30 December 2003) was a Hong Kong singer and actress. Widely regarded as a Cantopop diva, she was dubbed the "Madonna of Asia". Mui was a versatile performer, known for her powerful vocals, energetic stage presence, and flamboyant costumes. She was also a style icon and trendsetter in Hong Kong and Asia. Mui's career spanned over three decades, during which she released over 40 albums and starred in over 40 films. She received numerous awards and accolades, including five Jade Solid Gold Best Female Singer awards and two Golden Horse Awards for Best Actress.

title: Toco, Texas
text: Toco, Texas, is an unincorporated community in Bowie County, Texas, United States. The community is located approximately 8 miles (13 km) east of New Boston, Texas, at the intersection of Texas State Highway 8 and Farm Road 1153. Toco was founded in the early 1870s, and its name is said to be derived from a Native American word meaning "meeting place." The community has a post office, a general store, and a few other small businesses. The population of Toco was 90 at the time of the 2010 census.

title: Beith
text: Beith is a town in North Ayrshire, Scotland, with a population of around 4,500. It is located in the Garnock Valley, approximately 20 miles southwest of Glasgow. Beith is known for its weaving and carpet-making industries, which played a significant role in its history. The town has a rich cultural heritage, with several historical sites and attractions including Beith Castle, the ruins of a 13th-century castle, and the Beith Historical Society Museum, which showcases the town's past. Beith is also home to a number of parks and green spaces, including the Beith Country Park, a popular spot for outdoor recreation.

title: Rialto, California
text: Rialto is a city in San Bernardino County, California, United States. It is located in the Inland Empire region of Southern California, approximately 55 miles (89 kilometers) east of Los Angeles. Rialto was incorporated on November 17, 1911, and has a population of approximately 100,000 residents. The city is known for its strong manufacturing base, with companies such as Toyota, Honda, and Hyundai operating major facilities in the area. Rialto is also home to the National Orange Show Events Center, which hosts various events throughout the year, including the annual National Orange Show.

title: Jean Arthur
text: Jean Arthur (born Gladys Georgianna Greene; October 17, 1900 – June 19, 1991) was an American film and stage actress. Known for her distinctive raspy voice, she achieved stardom during Hollywood's Golden Age and appeared in a wide range of films, from screwball comedies to romantic dramas and Westerns. Arthur was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Actress for her role in "Mr. Smith Goes to Washington" (1939), and is best known for her performances in films such as "The More the Merrier" (1943), "Buffalo Bill" (1944), and "Shane" (1953). She retired from acting in the early 1960s and spent her remaining years in obscurity.

title: Kingdom of Romania
text: The Kingdom of Romania was a constitutional monarchy that existed from 1881 to 1947. It was established after Romania gained independence from the Ottoman Empire in 1878. The kingdom's first king was Carol I, who was elected by the Romanian Parliament. During World War I, Romania fought alongside the Allied Powers and gained significant territorial gains. After the war, Romania experienced a period of economic and political instability. In 1938, King Carol II assumed dictatorial powers. In 1940, Romania lost territory to the Soviet Union and Hungary. In 1944, Romania joined the Allies and fought against Nazi Germany. After the war, Romania became a republic.

title: Tat people (Caucasus)
text: The Tat people, also known as the Mountain Jews or Judeo-Tat, are an Iranian-speaking ethnic group inhabiting the Caucasus region, primarily in the Republic of Dagestan in Russia and the Quba-Khachmaz region of Azerbaijan. The Tats are descendants of Persian Jews who migrated to the Caucasus around the 6th century AD, converting to Judaism in the process. They have a rich cultural heritage, with their own language, cuisine, and customs, influenced by both Persian and Caucasian traditions. Historically, the Tats have been involved in trade, agriculture, and crafts. Today, they face challenges related to assimilation and preserving their distinct identity.

title: Causal theory of reference
text: The causal theory of reference is a theory in philosophy of language that states that the referent of a term is determined by the causal chain that links the term to the referent. This theory was developed by Saul Kripke in the 1970s and has been influential in the philosophy of language ever since. The causal theory of reference is based on the idea that the meaning of a term is determined by its use. When we use a term, we are referring to something in the world. The referent of the term is the thing that we are referring to. The causal theory of reference states that the referent of a term is determined by the causal chain that links the term to the referent. This causal chain is typically created through repeated use of the term.

title: Beloeil, Quebec
text: Beloeil, a city in Quebec, Canada, is located in the Montérégie region on the Richelieu River. With a population of around 22,000, it is a thriving community known for its natural beauty and historical significance. Beloeil was founded in 1695 by settlers from France and was originally named Mont-Saint-Hilaire. It played a vital role in the fur trade and became a major agricultural center in the 18th and 19th centuries. Today, Beloeil boasts a charming downtown area with historic buildings, boutiques, and restaurants. It is also home to the Mont-Saint-Hilaire Nature Reserve, a UNESCO Biosphere Reserve renowned for its diverse ecosystems and hiking trails.

title: Patch collecting
text: Patch collecting, also known as philately, is the systematic acquisition and organization of postage stamps. Collectors may specialize in particular countries, eras, or themes. Stamps are often collected for their aesthetic appeal, historical significance, or rarity. Philately has a long history, dating back to the 19th century. Today, there are millions of stamp collectors worldwide. Some collectors focus on a specific theme, such as stamps featuring animals, ships, or famous people. Others may collect stamps from a particular country or region.

title: Alfonso VIII of Castile
text: Alfonso VIII, also known as Alfonso the Noble, was King of Castile from 1158 until his death in 1214. He is best known for his victory over the Almohad caliph, Abu Yaqub Yusuf II, at the Battle of Las Navas de Tolosa in 1212. This victory marked a turning point in the Reconquista, the Christian reconquest of the Iberian Peninsula from the Muslims. Alfonso VIII's reign was also a time of great cultural and economic development in Castile. He founded the University of Palencia, the first university in Spain, and encouraged the development of trade and commerce.

title: Machine learning
text: Machine learning is a type of artificial intelligence (AI) that enables software applications to become more accurate in predicting outcomes without being explicitly programmed to do so. Machine learning algorithms use historical data as input to predict new output values. The goal is to have computers imitate intelligent human behavior and perform complex tasks or make smart decisions. Machine learning is used in a wide range of applications, from fraud detection and risk assessment to image recognition and natural language processing.

title: Bergen County Line
text: The Bergen County Line is a commuter rail line operated by New Jersey Transit (NJT) in the U.S. state of New Jersey. The line runs from Hoboken Terminal in Hoboken, New Jersey, to Port Jervis, New York, along the former Erie Railroad Main Line. The line crosses the Hudson River via the Bergen Hill Cut and passes through Bergen County, New Jersey, and Orange and Rockland counties in New York. It is the second-busiest rail line in New Jersey, after the Northeast Corridor Line, with a weekday ridership of over 35,000 passengers.

title: Child care
text: Child care, also referred to as childcare, is the care and supervision of children whose parents or guardians are unable to provide it themselves. It can include a wide range of services, such as feeding, bathing, dressing, changing diapers, and providing educational activities. Child care can be provided in a variety of settings, including homes, daycare centers, and preschools. Licensed childcare providers typically undergo background checks and training to ensure the safety and well-being of the children in their care.

title: Owyhee, Nevada
text: Owyhee, Nevada, is an unincorporated community in Elko County, with a population of 826 as of the 2010 census. It is located approximately 45 miles (72 km) east of Winnemucca, at an elevation of 5,184 feet (1,580 m). The community is named after the Owyhee River, which flows nearby. Owyhee was founded in the late 1800s as a railroad stop on the Central Pacific Railroad. The town grew rapidly in the early 1900s as a center for mining and ranching. In recent years, Owyhee has become a popular destination for outdoor recreation, including hunting, fishing, and camping.

title: Need for Speed
text: Need for Speed is a popular racing video game franchise developed by Electronic Arts (EA). The series began in 1994 and has since released 25 installments on various platforms, including PC, consoles, and handheld devices. Need for Speed games feature a variety of racing disciplines, including street racing, circuit racing, drift racing, and off-road racing. Players compete in races against computer-controlled opponents or other players online. The series has sold over 150 million copies worldwide, making it one of the best-selling video game franchises of all time.

title: Stellar black hole
text: A stellar black hole is a black hole formed from the gravitational collapse of a massive star. The mass of a stellar black hole typically ranges from a few to dozens of solar masses. Stellar black holes are the most common type of black hole in the universe. They are found in the centers of most galaxies, including our own Milky Way. Stellar black holes are invisible to direct observation, but their presence can be inferred from their gravitational effects on surrounding matter.

title: Monarchy of Spain
text: The Monarchy of Spain is the constitutional monarchy that governs the Kingdom of Spain. The monarch is the head of state and symbol of its unity and permanence. The current monarch is King Felipe VI, who ascended to the throne in 2014 following the abdication of his father, King Juan Carlos I.
