The monarchy is hereditary, with the crown passing to the eldest child of the reigning monarch, regardless of gender. The heir apparent is Princess Leonor, the eldest daughter of King Felipe VI. The monarch's powers are largely ceremonial, with real power vested in the Prime Minister and the Cortes Generales, the Spanish parliament. However, the monarch retains some significant powers, including the ability to dissolve parliament and to call for new elections.

title: Sioux
text: The Sioux are a Native American people who have historically lived in the Northern Plains of the United States and Canada. They are known for their horsemanship, hunting skills, and warrior culture. The Sioux were originally a nomadic people, but they eventually settled in permanent villages along the Missouri River. They were divided into seven main tribes: the Lakota, Dakota, Nakota, Yanktonai, Teton, Assiniboine, and Stoney. The Sioux played a major role in the American Indian Wars of the 19th century. Today, they live on reservations in the United States and Canada.

title: Top Fuel
text: Top Fuel is the quickest and most powerful category of drag racing cars. These cars can reach speeds of over 300 miles per hour (480 kilometers per hour) in less than four seconds. They are powered by massive, supercharged engines that produce over 8,000 horsepower. Top Fuel cars are driven by highly skilled drivers who must have quick reflexes and the ability to withstand the intense forces generated by the car.

title: Zurab Khizanishvili
text: Zurab Khizanishvili (born October 6, 1981) is a Georgian judoka who competed in the men's heavyweight and openweight categories. He is a three-time Olympic medalist, winning gold in 2012, silver in 2008, and bronze in 2016. He is also a six-time world champion, winning the heavyweight title in 2003, 2005, 2007, and 2009, and the openweight title in 2005 and 2009. Khizanishvili is considered one of the greatest judokas of all time.

title: Collapse of the World Trade Center
text: The collapse of the World Trade Center was a pivotal event in world history. On September 11, 2001, 19 al-Qaeda terrorists hijacked four commercial airliners and flew them into the World Trade Center towers in New York City, the Pentagon in Arlington, Virginia, and a field in Stonycreek Township, Pennsylvania. The impact and subsequent fires caused the collapse of the Twin Towers and severely damaged the Pentagon and other nearby buildings. Nearly 3,000 people died in the attacks, including more than 400 firefighters, police officers, and emergency responders. The collapse of the World Trade Center marked the deadliest terrorist attack in history and had a profound impact on global politics and security.

title: Moa
text: The moa (Dinornithiformes) were a group of large, flightless birds endemic to New Zealand. They evolved from small, flying ancestors sometime before the arrival of humans around 1300 AD. Moa ranged in size from the turkey-sized Euryapteryx curtus to the massive Dinornis robustus, which could reach heights of over 12 feet and weigh up to 500 pounds. Moa were herbivores, feeding on a variety of plants, including leaves, fruits, and roots. They were hunted to extinction by humans shortly after their arrival in New Zealand.

title: Blackduck, Minnesota
text: Blackduck, Minnesota is a city in northern Minnesota with a population of 793 as of the 2020 census. The city is situated in Beltrami County, approximately 50 miles (80 kilometers) northwest of Bemidji and 100 miles (160 kilometers) southwest of International Falls. Blackduck was founded in the late 19th century as a logging community and was named after the nearby Blackduck River. Today, the city's economy is primarily based on tourism and recreation. Blackduck is home to the Blackduck American Legion Post 328 and the Blackduck Golf Course. The city also hosts an annual Blackduck Days festival.

title: Coupeville, Washington
text: Coupeville is a town on Whidbey Island in Island County, Washington, United States. It is the county seat and the oldest incorporated town in the county. The population was 1,831 at the 2010 census. Coupeville was founded in 1852 by Captain Thomas Coupe, a sea captain from Massachusetts. The town was originally called "Ship Harbor" but was renamed in honor of Captain Coupe in 1854. Coupeville was the county seat from 1853 to 1915, when the seat was moved to Coupeville's larger neighbor, Oak Harbor.

title: Northrop X-4 Bantam
text: The Northrop X-4 Bantam was an experimental rocket-powered aircraft developed by Northrop Corporation for the United States Air Force. It was designed as a high-speed research aircraft to investigate the effects of supersonic flight on aircraft structures and control systems. The X-4 was a small, lightweight aircraft with a delta wing and a single rocket engine. It was launched from the ground using a solid rocket booster, and could reach speeds of up to Mach 2.5. The X-4 was used for a series of research flights in the early 1950s, and provided valuable data that contributed to the development of future supersonic aircraft.

title: Pete Kircher
text: Pete Kircher is an American former professional basketball player. A 6'8" power forward from Bradley University, Kircher played three seasons (1980–1983) in the National Basketball Association (NBA) as a member of the Phoenix Suns. He played in 114 NBA games, starting none, and averaged 2.5 points per game.

title: Robert Dunsire
text: Robert Dunsire (1901–1986) was a Scottish painter and graphic artist. He was born in Edinburgh and studied at the Edinburgh College of Art. After graduating, he worked as a commercial artist before becoming a full-time painter in the 1930s. Dunsire's work is characterized by its bold use of color and simplified forms. He was particularly known for his landscapes, which often depicted the Scottish countryside. Dunsire's work is held in several public collections, including the National Gallery of Scotland and the Tate Gallery.

title: Tribes (series)
text: Tribes is an American science fiction drama television series created by Darren Aronofsky and produced by Scott Free Productions, Anonymous Content, and Turner Originals. It premiered on September 22, 2017, on TNT. The series follows a group of humans who have been genetically modified to live in an underwater environment. The show explores themes of family, identity, and the nature of humanity. Tribes was praised for its visuals, acting, and writing, but it was canceled after one season due to low ratings.

title: Dachau concentration camp
text: Dachau concentration camp was the first Nazi concentration camp established in Germany. It was located near the town of Dachau, about 10 miles (16 km) northwest of Munich. The camp was opened in March 1933, shortly after the Nazis came to power, and was initially used to hold political prisoners. Over the course of its existence, Dachau held more than 200,000 prisoners and was the site of numerous atrocities. The camp was liberated by American forces in April 1945.

title: Calendar-based contraceptive methods
text: Calendar-based contraceptive methods are natural family planning techniques that involve tracking a woman's menstrual cycle to identify her fertile and infertile periods. These methods rely on the observation of physical signs such as changes in cervical mucus and basal body temperature. By identifying the fertile window, couples can abstain from intercourse or use barrier methods to prevent pregnancy. Calendar-based methods include the rhythm method, the ovulation method, and the sympto-thermal method. While effective in preventing pregnancy, calendar-based methods require careful tracking and knowledge of the menstrual cycle.

title: Darkhawk
text: Darkhawk is a fictional superhero appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. The character first appeared in Darkhawk #1 (March 1991), created by writer Danny Fingeroth and artist Mike Wieringo. Darkhawk is the alter ego of Christopher Powell, a troubled teenager who is bonded with an alien amulet that gives him incredible power. As Darkhawk, he fights crime and protects the innocent. The character has been a member of the New Warriors and the Guardians of the Galaxy.

title: Dave Godin
text: Dave Godin (born 6 December 1946) is an English former footballer who played as a midfielder or forward. He is best known for his time with Carlisle United, where he made over 250 appearances in all competitions. Godin began his career with local side Workington before moving to Carlisle in 1966. He was a versatile player who could play in various midfield or forward positions. Godin was a member of the Carlisle team that won the Third Division title in 1973-74. He left Carlisle in 1976 and subsequently played for Mansfield Town, Darlington, and Workington.

title: Abbott and Costello
text: Abbott and Costello were a comedy duo consisting of Bud Abbott and Lou Costello, who were active from the 1930s to the 1950s. They were known for their slapstick routines and catchphrases, such as "Who's on first?" and "You're telling me." The duo starred in over 36 films together, as well as numerous radio and television shows. Their humor was often characterized by their use of physical comedy, wordplay, and misunderstandings. Abbott and Costello were one of the most popular comedy duos of all time, and their legacy continues to be enjoyed today.

title: Geography of the Comoros
text: The Comoros archipelago is situated in the Indian Ocean, at the northern end of the Mozambique Channel, about 300 kilometers (190 mi) off the coast of East Africa. It consists of four main islands: Ngazidja (Grande Comore), Mwali (Mohéli), Nzwani (Anjouan), and Maore (Mayotte), and numerous smaller islands. The islands are volcanic in origin, with Mount Karthala on Ngazidja being the highest point in the archipelago at 2,361 meters (7,746 ft). The climate is tropical, with a rainy season from November to April and a dry season from May to October. The total land area of the Comoros is 2,235 square kilometers (863 sq mi).

title: Interstate Commerce Commission
text: The Interstate Commerce Commission (ICC) was an independent agency of the United States government created in 1887 to regulate interstate commerce. Its main purpose was to ensure fair competition and protect consumers from unfair or discriminatory practices in the transportation and communication industries. The ICC had broad powers to investigate and regulate companies involved in interstate commerce, including railroads, trucking companies, airlines, and telephone and telegraph companies. The ICC was abolished in 1995, and its functions were transferred to other agencies, such as the Federal Motor Carrier Safety Administration and the Federal Communications Commission.

title: Kaipara Harbour
text: Kaipara Harbour is a large, shallow harbour on the west coast of New Zealand's North Island. It is the largest harbour in the country, covering an area of over 900 square kilometres. The harbour is fed by several rivers, including the Wairoa and Kaipara Rivers. It is home to a variety of marine life, including fish, shellfish, and birds. The harbour is also a popular destination for boating and fishing.

title: Lynyrd Skynyrd
text: Lynyrd Skynyrd is an American rock band formed in Jacksonville, Florida, in 1964. The band is known for its Southern rock sound, which draws on influences from blues, rock, and country. Lynyrd Skynyrd's most famous songs include "Sweet Home Alabama", "Free Bird", and "Simple Man". The band has sold over 28 million albums worldwide, and its hit single "Sweet Home Alabama" has been certified triple platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA). Lynyrd Skynyrd was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 2006.

title: Ordination of women
text: The ordination of women is the process by which women are consecrated into the ordained ministry of a church or religious organization. The practice has been controversial in Christianity since the early centuries, with some denominations ordaining women and others not. In the 21st century, most major Protestant denominations ordain women, as do some Anglican and Lutheran churches. The Catholic Church, Eastern Orthodox Church, and some conservative Protestant denominations continue to prohibit the ordination of women.

title: Chelsea, Oklahoma
text: Chelsea is a town in Rogers County, Oklahoma, United States. The population was 2,042 at the 2010 census. Chelsea is located approximately 20 miles (32 km) northeast of Tulsa. The town was founded in 1894 and named after Chelsea, Massachusetts. Chelsea is home to the Will Rogers Memorial Museum, which houses a collection of artifacts from the life of humorist Will Rogers. The town is also home to the Chelsea Rodeo, which is held annually in June.

title: Government of the 2nd Dáil
text: The Second Dáil, elected in 1921, was the first fully functioning Irish parliament. It established the Irish Free State, adopted a constitution, and oversaw the transfer of power from the British government. The Second Dáil was dominated by Sinn Féin, the party that had led the fight for Irish independence. The government was headed by Éamon de Valera, who served as President of the Republic. The Second Dáil existed until 1922, when it was replaced by the Third Dáil, following the Anglo-Irish Treaty.

title: Louis Capone
text: Louis Capone, born in 1896, was the older brother of notorious gangster Al Capone. Despite being less well-known, Louis played a significant role in the Capone crime family. He served as a bodyguard and enforcer for his younger brother, participating in several violent incidents and bootlegging operations. Louis was arrested and imprisoned on multiple occasions, including a 10-year sentence for bootlegging violations. After his release from prison, he continued to be involved in the family's criminal activities until his death in 1944.

title: Rêve: the Dream Ouroboros
text: Rêve: the Dream Ouroboros is a hentai video game developed by the Japanese company Twilight Frontier. The game was released in Japan in 2017 and in North America and Europe in 2018. The game follows the story of a young woman named Rêve who is trapped in a dream world. She must use her powers to fight her way through the dream world and escape. Rêve: the Dream Ouroboros is a unique and innovative game that has been praised for its beautiful art style, haunting soundtrack, and compelling story.

title: Interactionism
text: Interactionism is a sociological theory that emphasizes the role of social interaction in shaping human behavior. It argues that individuals are not born with a fixed set of characteristics, but rather that their personalities and identities are formed through their interactions with others. Interactionism focuses on the ways in which individuals negotiate and interpret meaning in social situations, and how these interactions shape their understanding of themselves and the world around them.

title: Nueva Ecija
text: Nueva Ecija, a province in the Philippines, is known as the "Rice Granary of the Philippines" due to its vast rice production. It is located in the Central Luzon region, north of Manila. With a population of over 2 million, it is one of the most populous provinces in the country. Nueva Ecija is home to several historical and cultural landmarks, including the Betis Church and the General Tinio Monument. The province is also known for its festivals, such as the Giant Lantern Festival in San Fernando City.

title: John Waters
text: John Waters (born April 22, 1946) is an American filmmaker, actor, artist, and writer. Known for his transgressive and controversial films, Waters is often associated with the midnight movie phenomenon. His work has been praised for its camp aesthetic, shock value, and social commentary. Waters' films often feature drag queens, gender-bending characters, and explicit sexuality. His best-known works include "Pink Flamingos" (1972), "Polyester" (1981), "Hairspray" (1988), and "Serial Mom" (1994). Waters has also directed several Hollywood films, such as "Cecil B. Demented" (2000) and "A Dirty Shame" (2004).

title: Mercury (planet)
text: Mercury, the closest planet to the Sun and the smallest planet in our solar system, is a terrestrial planet with a solid surface. It is named after the Roman god Mercury, who was known for his speed and agility. Mercury has a thin atmosphere and a highly cratered surface, with no known moons. Its proximity to the Sun means that its surface experiences extreme temperature fluctuations, ranging from -173°C at night to 450°C during the day.

title: Deep Impact (spacecraft)
text: Deep Impact was an American space probe designed to study the interior of a comet. It consisted of an impactor and a flyby spacecraft. The impactor was released from the flyby spacecraft and impacted comet Tempel 1 on 4 July 2005, creating a crater and releasing dust and gas that were analyzed by the flyby spacecraft. The mission yielded significant insights into the composition and structure of comets.

title: Taylor, Wisconsin
text: Taylor is a city in Jackson County, Wisconsin, United States. The population was 5,593 at the 2010 census. It is part of the Black River Falls, WI Micropolitan Statistical Area. Taylor is located on the Black River, and is home to the Taylor Dam and Reservoir. The city is also home to the Taylor County Historical Society Museum, which houses exhibits on the history of Taylor County.

title: Operating system advocacy
text: Operating system advocacy is the practice of promoting the use of a particular operating system. This can be done through a variety of means, such as writing articles and blog posts, giving presentations, and participating in online forums. Advocates of a particular operating system often believe that it is the best choice for a particular purpose. They may cite its features, performance, or security as reasons for their belief. In some cases, advocates may also be motivated by a desire to support a particular company or open-source project. Operating system advocacy can play a role in the adoption of a particular system. By promoting the benefits of a particular system, advocates can help to increase its visibility and appeal. This can lead to increased usage and, ultimately, to a greater market share for the system.

title: Michael Ian Black
text: Michael Ian Black is an American actor, comedian, writer, and director. He is known for his roles in the television series "Ed" and "Arrested Development," as well as for his stand-up comedy specials. Black has also written and directed several films, including "The Final Season" and "Wedding Daze." He regularly appears on the podcast "How Did This Get Made?" and has a recurring role on the television series "Modern Family."

title: Orchard, Nebraska
text: Orchard is a village in Antelope County, Nebraska, United States. The population was 375 at the 2010 census. Orchard was founded in 1873 and named after the orchard planted by its original settlers. The village is located on the banks of the Elkhorn River and is home to the Orchard City Park and the Orchard Museum.

title: North Babylon, New York
text: North Babylon is a hamlet and census-designated place (CDP) in the Town of Babylon, Suffolk County, New York, United States. The population was 17,599 at the 2010 census. North Babylon is located on the South Shore of Long Island, approximately 40 miles (64 km) east of Manhattan. The community is served by the Babylon Union Free School District and is home to North Babylon High School. North Babylon is also home to the North Babylon Public Library, which is part of the Suffolk Cooperative Library System.

title: Paveway
text: Paveway is a series of laser-guided bombs (LGBs) developed by Raytheon. The first Paveway bombs were developed in the 1960s, and they have been used in a variety of conflicts, including the Vietnam War, the Gulf War, and the War in Afghanistan. Paveway bombs are typically equipped with a semi-active laser seeker, which allows them to be guided to a target by a laser designator. Paveway bombs have a range of between 5 and 15 kilometers, and they can penetrate up to 3 meters of concrete.

title: Guru Amar Das
text: Guru Amar Das (1479-1574) was the third of the ten Sikh Gurus. Born to a Hindu family in Basarke, Punjab, he became a devout Sikh after meeting Guru Angad. Amar Das expanded the Sikh community, establishing new centers and appointing missionaries. He also instituted the system of langar, where free meals are served to all visitors regardless of their caste or religion. Amar Das's teachings emphasized the importance of devotion, humility, and service to others. He composed numerous hymns that are included in the Sikh holy scripture, the Guru Granth Sahib.

title: Tango (flamenco)
text: Tango (Flamenco) is a flamenco dance style known for its passionate and intense expression. It is characterized by its rhythmic footwork, intricate hand gestures, and dramatic body movements. The dance is typically performed by a couple, with the man leading and the woman following. The origins of tango flamenco are not entirely clear, but it is believed to have developed in the 19th century in Andalusia, Spain. The dance is influenced by a variety of other dance styles, including bolero, fandango, and seguiriya. Tango flamenco is often performed in a traditional setting, such as a tablao or a flamenco festival. The dance is also popular in contemporary flamenco performances and has been adapted for use in other dance styles, such as ballet and modern dance.

title: Boa Esperança, Minas Gerais
text: Boa Esperança is a municipality in the state of Minas Gerais, Brazil. The population is 40,784 (2020 est.). The municipality covers an area of 1,559.891 km². The city is located in the southern part of the state, on the border with the state of São Paulo. The main economic activities are agriculture, livestock, and tourism. The city is home to the Serra da Canastra National Park, which is a popular tourist destination.

title: Confucius
text: Confucius, born Kongzi, was an influential Chinese philosopher and teacher who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (722-481 BCE). He is considered one of the most important figures in Chinese history and his teachings have shaped Chinese culture for over two millennia. Confucius emphasized the importance of social harmony, personal morality, and education. He believed that individuals could improve themselves and their society through self-cultivation and adherence to ethical principles. His teachings have been compiled and preserved in the Analects, a collection of his conversations and sayings.

title: El Yunque (organization)
text: El Yunque is a Puerto Rican paramilitary group that advocates for the independence of Puerto Rico from the United States. The group was founded in 1976 and has been designated as a terrorist organization by the United States government. El Yunque has claimed responsibility for a number of bombings and shootings in Puerto Rico, including the 1978 Cerro Maravilla ambush. The group's activities have been condemned by both the United States and Puerto Rican governments.

title: James White (author)
text: James White (born 1928) is an American science fiction author best known for his Sector General series of medical science fiction novels. White's stories focus on the challenges of providing medical care in a diverse alien society. He has also written several novels set in the Star Wars universe, including the bestselling Heir to the Empire and Dark Force Rising. White's work has won numerous awards, including the Nebula Award for Best Novel. He is considered one of the most significant figures in modern science fiction.

title: Southern Leyte
text: Southern Leyte, a province in the Philippines, is situated in the Eastern Visayas region. Its capital is Maasin City. The province is known for its natural beauty, including pristine beaches, lush forests, and cascading waterfalls. The Sohoton Natural Bridge National Park is a popular tourist destination, featuring a natural rock bridge and crystal-clear waters. Southern Leyte is also rich in agricultural resources, with a significant production of rice, corn, and coconuts. The province is renowned for its warm and welcoming people, who are proud of their cultural heritage and traditions.

title: Darkcutter
text: Darkcutter is a meat quality defect that results in dark, firm, and dry (DFD) meat. It occurs when the muscle has an excessively low pH (below 5.8) shortly after slaughter. This leads to a reduced water-holding capacity, resulting in tough and dry meat with a shortened shelf life. Darkcutter is often associated with stress before slaughter, which causes glycogen depletion and an accumulation of lactic acid in the muscle. It is undesirable in the meat industry, as it affects the eating quality and economic value of the meat.

title: Leicester City F.C.
text: Leicester City Football Club is an English professional football club based in Leicester, Leicestershire. The club was founded in 1884 and has played at the King Power Stadium since 2002. Leicester City competes in the Premier League, the top tier of English football. The club's most successful period came in the 2015–16 season, when they won the Premier League title for the first time in their history. Leicester City also won the FA Cup in 2021.

title: Trans Canada Trail
text: The Trans Canada Trail is a network of multi-use recreational trails that span Canada. With over 27,000 km (17,000 mi) of trails, it is the longest trail network in the world. The trail passes through all ten provinces and three territories of Canada, and connects over 1,500 communities. It was originally conceived in 1992, and was officially opened in 2017. The trail is used for a variety of activities, including hiking, biking, cross-country skiing, and snowmobiling.

title: Bristol City F.C.
text: Bristol City Football Club is an English professional football club based in the city of Bristol. The club was founded in 1894 and currently plays in the EFL Championship, the second tier of English football. Bristol City play their home matches at Ashton Gate Stadium, which has a capacity of over 27,000. The club has won the FA Cup twice, in 1904 and 1976. In addition, they have been runners-up in the Football League First Division, the FA Cup, and the League Cup. Notable players who have played for Bristol City include Bob Taylor, John Atyeo, Chris Garland, and Marlon Pack.

title: Charles W. Fairbanks
text: Charles Warren Fairbanks (May 11, 1852 – June 4, 1918) was an American politician. A member of the Republican Party, he served as the 26th vice president of the United States from 1905 to 1909, under President Theodore Roosevelt. Prior to that, he represented Indiana in the United States Senate from 1897 to 1905. Fairbanks was born in Unionville Center, Ohio, and moved to Indiana as a child. He studied law and began practicing in Indianapolis in 1874. He entered politics in 1879, when he was elected to the Indiana Senate. He resigned from the Senate in 1885 to practice law and business.

title: Cass Lake, Minnesota
text: Cass Lake is a city in Cass County, Minnesota, United States. It is located on the shores of Cass Lake, which is the third-largest lake in Minnesota. The city has a population of around 700 people. The economy of Cass Lake is based on tourism, fishing, and logging. The city is also home to the Leech Lake Band of Ojibwe, who have a reservation that includes much of the surrounding area. Cass Lake is a popular destination for anglers, as the lake is home to a variety of fish species, including walleye, northern pike, and bass.

title: Roulette
text: Roulette is a casino game named after the French word for "little wheel". In the game, players place bets on a numbered or colored section of a spinning wheel. A ball is then spun around the outside of the wheel, and when it lands on a section, the winning bets are paid out. Roulette is a popular game in both land-based and online casinos, and it is one of the most recognizable casino games in the world. The game is relatively simple to play, but it can be very exciting, and it offers the potential for big winnings.

title: Qutb Minar complex
text: The Qutb Minar complex is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in Delhi, India. It is home to the Qutb Minar, a towering 73-meter (240-foot) minaret built in the 12th century. The complex also includes several other historic structures, including the Quwwat-ul-Islam Mosque, the Iron Pillar, and the Alai Darwaza. The Qutb Minar complex is a testament to the architectural prowess of the Delhi Sultanate and is one of the most popular tourist destinations in India. It is a must-see for anyone interested in history, architecture, or culture.

title: Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878)
text: The Russo-Turkish War of 1877–1878 was a conflict between the Russian Empire and the Ottoman Empire. The war arose from Russian nationalist sentiment and a desire to liberate Balkan Christians from Ottoman rule. Russia emerged victorious, securing significant territorial gains and undermining Ottoman power in the Balkans. The war also marked the beginning of the "Eastern Question," a complex geopolitical issue involving the decline of the Ottoman Empire and the rise of nationalism in the Balkans.

title: General Maritime Corporation
text: General Maritime Corporation is a shipping company based in New York City. Founded in 1997 by Peter Georgiopoulos, the company operates a fleet of dry bulk carriers, tankers, and containerships. General Maritime transports a variety of commodities, including iron ore, coal, grains, and oil. The company has operations in North America, Europe, Asia, and South America. As of 2023, General Maritime is one of the largest shipping companies in the world.

title: Gilmore Girls
text: Gilmore Girls is an American comedy-drama television series created by Amy Sherman-Palladino. The show follows the lives of Lorelai Gilmore, a single mother, and her daughter, Rory Gilmore, in the fictional town of Stars Hollow, Connecticut. The series, which ran for seven seasons from 2000 to 2007, is known for its witty dialogue, quirky characters, and relatable mother-daughter relationship. Gilmore Girls has received critical acclaim and garnered a devoted fan base.

title: Chris Ofili
text: Chris Ofili (born 10 October 1968) is a British painter and sculptor. His work often explores themes of race, religion, Afrocentrism, and contemporary art theory. Ofili is best known for his large-scale paintings incorporating materials such as elephant dung, glitter, and found objects. He has been awarded numerous prizes, including the Turner Prize in 1998. Ofili's work has been exhibited in major museums and galleries around the world. He has also created public artworks, including a bronze sculpture entitled "No Woman, No Cry" (2002) in Trafalgar Square, London. Ofili is a controversial artist whose work has been praised and criticized for its use of challenging and provocative imagery.

title: Dana Point, California
text: Dana Point is a city located in southern Orange County, California. It is named after Richard Henry Dana, Jr., who visited the area in 1835. The city is known for its beautiful coastline, which includes several beaches and coves. Dana Point Harbor is a popular destination for boating and fishing. The city is also home to the Ocean Institute, a marine education center. Dana Point has a population of approximately 33,000 residents.

title: Mount Olive Township, New Jersey
text: Mount Olive Township is a township in Morris County, New Jersey, United States. As of the 2020 United States census, the township's population was 29,112. Mount Olive Township was incorporated as a township on March 21, 1871, from portions of the now-defunct Roxbury Township and Chester Township. The township is named after Mount Olive, a nearby mountain. Mount Olive Township is located in northwestern New Jersey, about 30 miles west of New York City. The township is home to several major highways, including Interstate 80 and Route 46.

title: Hubbardston, Massachusetts
text: Hubbardston is a town in Worcester County, Massachusetts, United States. The population was 4,382 at the 2020 census. Hubbardston is home to the Hubbardston Historical Society, which operates a museum in the town center. The town is also home to the Quabbin Reservoir, the largest body of water in Massachusetts.

title: Matera
text: Matera is a city and a comune in southern Italy, the capital of the province of Matera in the Basilicata region. Matera is notable for its ancient Sassi cave dwellings, which are listed by UNESCO as a World Heritage Site. The Sassi are a complex of ancient caves carved into the soft tufa rock of the Murgia plateau. They have been continuously inhabited since the Paleolithic era, and are still home to some 6,000 people today.

title: Blues
text: Blues is a genre of music that originated in the African-American communities of the Deep South of the United States around the end of the 19th century. The genre is characterized by its lyrics, which often express themes of hardship and loss, and its use of the blue notes, which are notes that are slightly flat or sharp of the corresponding major or minor scale notes. Blues music is typically played on guitar, and often includes vocals and harmonica.

title: Meadow Vista, California
text: Meadow Vista is an unincorporated community in Placer County, California, United States. It is located 5 miles (8.0 km) east-southeast of Auburn, at an elevation of 1,306 feet (398 m). The population was 3,160 at the 2010 census. The community was founded in 1854 by miners who were attracted to the area by the discovery of gold. The town was originally known as "Dry Creek Diggings" but was later renamed "Meadow Vista" because of the beautiful meadows that surrounded the community. Meadow Vista is now a thriving community with a strong sense of pride. The community is home to several schools, churches, and businesses. Meadow Vista also has a number of recreational opportunities, including a park, a swimming pool, and a hiking trail.

title: Jubilee (biblical)
text: Jubilee, in the biblical context, refers to a period of 50 years, marked by special observances and the restoration of societal and economic balance. The concept originates in the Book of Leviticus, in which God instructs the Israelites to observe a Jubilee every 50th year. During the Jubilee, slaves were to be set free, property was to be returned to its original owners, and the land was to be given rest. The Jubilee served as a reminder of God's sovereignty and the importance of social justice and equality.

title: Cass Elliot
text: Cass Elliot (September 19, 1941 – July 29, 1974), also known as Mama Cass, was an American singer and actress. She was a member of the folk rock group the Mamas & the Papas, known for her powerful vocals and signature rendition of "Dream a Little Dream of Me." After the group disbanded in 1968, Elliot pursued a successful solo career, releasing six albums and earning a Grammy nomination. Her life was cut short at age 32 due to a heart attack.

title: Kakuma
text: Kakuma is a refugee camp in Kenya, established in 1992 to accommodate refugees fleeing the Sudanese civil war. Located in Turkana County, it is one of the largest refugee camps in the world, hosting over 200,000 refugees and asylum seekers from various countries, primarily from South Sudan and Somalia. The camp is managed by the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) and provides basic services such as shelter, food, water, healthcare, and education. Kakuma has faced challenges such as overcrowding, limited resources, and security concerns, but it remains a vital sanctuary for those seeking refuge from conflict and persecution.

title: Tree spiking
text: Tree spiking is the intentional insertion of metal or ceramic rods or spikes into a tree to damage chainsaws and other logging equipment. The practice is used by environmental activists to deter logging operations and protect forests. Tree spiking has been illegal in the United States since 1988 and can result in severe penalties, including imprisonment. Despite the legal risks, tree spiking remains a tactic employed by some environmental groups to prevent deforestation and preserve endangered ecosystems.

title: Liberal Party (UK)
text: The Liberal Party is a centre-left political party in the United Kingdom. Founded in 1830, it is the oldest extant political party in the world. The party advocates social liberalism and economic liberalism, and supports a mixed economy, a welfare state, and free trade. The party is committed to civil liberties, social justice, and environmental protection. The Liberal Party has formed governments on several occasions, most recently in coalition with the Conservative Party from 2010 to 2015.

title: BMW 6 Series
text: The BMW 6 Series is a grand tourer produced by BMW since 1976. It has been available in coupé, convertible, and gran coupé body styles. The first generation was produced from 1976 to 1989, the second generation from 2003 to 2010, the third generation from 2011 to 2018, and the fourth generation from 2018 to present. The 6 Series is powered by a range of inline-6 and V8 engines, and is available with either rear-wheel drive or all-wheel drive.

title: Victoria Woodhull
text: Victoria Claflin Woodhull (1838–1927) was an American suffragist, abolitionist, and the first woman to run for President of the United States. She and her sister, Tennessee Claflin, founded the National Woman Suffrage Association in 1869. Woodhull was a controversial figure, known for her outspoken views on topics such as women's rights, free love, and spiritualism. She was often ridiculed and criticized by the press, but she remained a vocal advocate for women's rights throughout her life.

title: Ashtabula, Ohio
text: Ashtabula, Ohio, is a city in Ashtabula County, Ohio, United States. It is located on the shores of Lake Erie, approximately 50 miles (80 km) northeast of Cleveland. Ashtabula has a population of around 19,000 people and is known for its maritime history and its role as a transportation hub. The city is home to the Ashtabula Harbor, a deep-water port that serves as a major shipping point for iron ore, coal, and other commodities. Ashtabula is also home to a number of manufacturing and industrial businesses, including steel mills, foundries, and plastics plants.

title: Clinton County, Indiana
text: Clinton County is a county located in the west central portion of the U.S. state of Indiana. As of the 2020 census, the population was 33,224. The county seat is Frankfort. Clinton County is named after DeWitt Clinton, the governor of New York from 1817 to 1822. The county was formed in 1830 from parts of Tippecanoe and Montgomery counties.

title: Photo manipulation
text: Photo manipulation is the altering of images using digital or traditional methods. It can be used to change the appearance of a photo, to create a new image, or to remove unwanted elements from a photo. Photo manipulation can be used for a variety of purposes, including: Artistic expression - Photo manipulation can be used to create works of art, such as digital paintings and photo collages. Commercial use - Photo manipulation can be used to create marketing materials, such as product shots and advertisements. Photojournalism - Photo manipulation can be used to correct errors in a photo or to remove distracting elements.

title: GoDaddy
text: GoDaddy Inc. is an American publicly traded Internet domain registrar and web hosting company. As of December 2022, GoDaddy has approximately 21 million customers and manages more than 80 million domain names. The company is headquartered in Scottsdale, Arizona, and has additional offices in the United States, Canada, Mexico, Brazil, India, and the Netherlands. GoDaddy was founded in 1997 by Bob Parsons and currently holds the market share lead in domain name registrations.

title: George Jewsbury
text: George Jewsbury (1816-1876) was an English novelist and journalist. He was a prolific writer, publishing over 20 novels and countless articles. His novels were often satirical and dealt with social issues of the day. Jewsbury was also a close friend and mentor to Charlotte Brontë. He helped her to develop her writing style and encouraged her to publish her work. Jewsbury's own writing has been largely forgotten, but he is remembered as a significant figure in the literary world of the Victorian era.

title: Tron (video game)
text: Tron is a 1982 arcade game developed and published by Bally Midway. It is based on the 1982 film of the same name. The player controls an electronic warrior on a light cycle in a battle against the Master Control Program. Tron was one of the first arcade games to use vector graphics, and it was a commercial success. It was ported to several home systems, including the Atari 2600 and Commodore 64. Tron is considered a classic arcade game and has been influential in the development of video games.

title: St Osyth
text: St Osyth is a village and civil parish in Essex, England, on the Essex Sunshine Coast. The village is named after Saint Osyth, an Anglo-Saxon saint who was martyred in the 7th century. St Osyth is home to the ruins of St Osyth's Priory, a Benedictine monastery founded in the 11th century. The priory was dissolved by Henry VIII in the 16th century, and the ruins are now a Grade I listed building. St Osyth is also home to the St Osyth Beach, a popular tourist destination. The beach is known for its long stretch of sand and its safe swimming conditions.

title: Greenwood, Seattle
text: Greenwood is a neighborhood in the north-central part of Seattle, Washington. It is bordered by Phinney Ridge to the north, Ballard to the west, Fremont to the south, and the University District to the east. Greenwood is a vibrant and diverse neighborhood with a mix of residential, commercial, and industrial areas. It is home to a variety of shops, restaurants, and bars, as well as several parks and green spaces. The neighborhood is also home to the Greenwood Senior Center and the Greenwood Library. Greenwood is a popular neighborhood for families and young professionals alike, and it is well-connected to the rest of Seattle by public transportation.

title: Space Shuttle program
text: The Space Shuttle program was the United States' reusable spacecraft program that operated from 1981 to 2011. The program's primary goals were to reduce the cost of access to space and to provide a means of constructing and servicing space stations. The Space Shuttle was launched into orbit by a rocket booster and then used its own engines to maneuver in space. It could carry up to seven astronauts and a variety of cargo, including satellites, space stations, and experiments. The Shuttle made 135 missions, deployed numerous satellites, conducted spacewalks, and helped to construct the International Space Station.

title: Ascomycota
text: Ascomycota, commonly known as sac fungi, is a phylum of fungi that includes yeasts, morels, and truffles. It is the largest phylum of fungi, with over 64,000 described species. Ascomycetes are characterized by the production of sexual spores called ascospores, which are formed in microscopic sacs called asci. Ascomycota also includes many important plant pathogens, such as the powdery mildew fungi and the Dutch elm disease fungus.

title: Dependency ratio
text: The dependency ratio is a measure of the proportion of a population that is either too young or too old to work. It is calculated by dividing the number of people in the dependent age group by the number of people in the working-age group. The dependency ratio can be used to assess the potential economic burden on the working-age population, as well as the need for social welfare programs to support the dependent population. In most developed countries, the dependency ratio has been rising in recent years due to increasing longevity and declining fertility rates. This trend is expected to continue in the coming years, which could put a strain on social welfare systems and economic growth.

title: Beta distribution
text: The beta distribution is a continuous probability distribution that is defined on the interval (0, 1). It is often used to model proportions or probabilities. The beta distribution is a special case of the Dirichlet distribution. The probability density function of the beta distribution is given by: ``` f(x) = (1/B(α, β)) x^(α - 1) (1 - x)^(β - 1) ``` where α and β are the parameters of the distribution and B(α, β) is the beta function. The mean of the beta distribution is given by: ``` E(X) = α / (α + β) ``` and the variance is given by: ``` Var(X) = (α β) / [(α + β)^2 (α + β + 1)] ```

title: Hurricane Joan–Miriam
text: Hurricane Joan–Miriam was a powerful tropical cyclone that caused widespread damage in Central America in 1988. It formed from a tropical wave off the coast of Africa and reached hurricane strength on October 11. Joan–Miriam made landfall in Nicaragua as a Category 5 hurricane on October 22, and then crossed into Honduras. The hurricane brought torrential rains and strong winds to both countries, causing flooding, mudslides, and power outages. Over 200 people were killed, and thousands were left homeless. Joan–Miriam was one of the most destructive hurricanes to hit Central America in history.

title: Gary Lucas
text: Gary Lucas (born June 20, 1952) is an American guitarist, composer, and producer. He is best known for his work with Captain Beefheart, the Klezmatics, and his own band, Gods and Monsters. Lucas has also released several solo albums and has collaborated with a wide range of artists, including Iggy Pop, Lou Reed, and Bob Dylan. His music is often characterized by its eclecticism, incorporating elements of rock, jazz, folk, and world music. Lucas is also a respected music educator and has taught at the New School for Jazz and Contemporary Music and the California Institute of the Arts.

title: Patras
text: Patras is a city in Greece and the capital of the Achaea region in the Peloponnese. It is the third largest city in Greece, after Athens and Thessaloniki, with a population of around 213,984 inhabitants. Patras is located on the Gulf of Patras, opposite the city of Rion, which is connected to Patras by the Rio-Antirrio Bridge. The city is a major port and industrial center, and it is home to the University of Patras, one of the largest universities in Greece.

title: Barksdale Air Force Base
text: Barksdale Air Force Base is a United States Air Force base located in Bossier City, Louisiana. It is the home of the 2nd Bomb Wing, which operates the B-52 Stratofortress bomber. The base was originally established in 1933 as Barksdale Field and was named after Lieutenant Eugene Hoy Barksdale, a World War I pilot who was killed in a training accident. Barksdale AFB is one of the largest employers in the Shreveport-Bossier City metropolitan area, with over 10,000 military and civilian personnel assigned to the base.

title: Surakarta
text: Surakarta, also known as Solo, is a city in Central Java, Indonesia. It was the capital of the Surakarta Sunanate, a Javanese monarchy that ruled from the 18th to the 20th centuries. Surakarta is known for its traditional Javanese culture, arts, and cuisine. The city is home to the Kraton Surakarta, the former palace of the Sunanate rulers. Surakarta is also a major center for batik production, a traditional Indonesian textile art form.

title: DESY
text: DESY (Deutsches Elektronen-Synchrotron) is a national research center in Germany that operates particle accelerators and conducts research in high-energy physics. Founded in 1959, it is located in Hamburg and has played a significant role in particle physics discoveries, including the confirmation of the existence of the Higgs boson in 2012. DESY's facilities include particle accelerators, such as the PETRA III synchrotron and FLASH, and experimental halls where researchers conduct experiments. The center also hosts a range of research groups and collaborations, focusing on areas such as particle physics, astroparticle physics, and photon science.

title: The Rolling Stones
text: The Rolling Stones is an English rock band formed in London in 1962. The band consists of Mick Jagger (lead vocals, harmonica), Keith Richards (guitar, vocals), Charlie Watts (drums), and Ronnie Wood (guitar). Brian Jones (guitar, sitar) was also a member from 1962 to 1969. The group gained popularity in the mid-1960s as part of the British Invasion of the United States, and were widely regarded as one of the most successful and influential bands in rock and roll history. The Rolling Stones have sold an estimated 200 million records worldwide and have been inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and the UK Music Hall of Fame.

title: 39th Annual Grammy Awards
text: The 39th Annual Grammy Awards were held on March 24, 1997, at Madison Square Garden in New York City. Singer-songwriter Tracy Chapman was the top winner, taking home four awards, including Song of the Year for "Give Me One Reason." Other notable winners included Céline Dion for Album of the Year for "Falling into You" and the Fugees for Best Rap Album for "The Score." The ceremony also featured performances by U2, Stevie Wonder, and Sheryl Crow.

title: Burroughs large systems
text: Burroughs large systems were a family of mainframe computers produced by the Burroughs Corporation from the 1960s to the 1990s. They were known for their advanced architecture, which featured a modular design and a unique "stack" architecture that allowed for efficient multitasking. Burroughs large systems were used in a wide variety of applications, including business, scientific, and military. They were particularly popular in the banking and financial industries, where their reliability and security were highly valued.

title: MiniDisc
text: MiniDisc (MD) is a magneto-optical disc-based data storage format offering high-fidelity audio. Developed by Sony and introduced in 1992, it was marketed as a replacement for cassette tapes and aimed to rival compact discs. MDs can store up to 80 minutes of audio, have skip protection, and allow users to record and re-record. Despite initial popularity, the format faced competition from CD-R and MP3 players and gradually declined in popularity. However, it remains a niche format among audio enthusiasts.

title: Decision tree learning
text: Decision tree learning is a supervised machine learning technique that uses a tree-like structure to make predictions or decisions. It involves constructing a tree-shaped model that represents the relationships between features (input variables) and a target variable (output variable). Each internal node in the tree represents a test on a feature, while each leaf node represents a decision or prediction. The goal is to create a tree that accurately predicts the target variable based on the given features. Decision tree learning is commonly used in areas such as classification, regression, and decision-making.

title: Sterling, Michigan
text: Sterling is an unincorporated community in Arenac County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The community is located within Deep River Township. As of the 2010 census, the population was 540. Sterling is located along M-33, approximately 12 miles (19 km) north of Standish. The community is served by the Sterling Community School District. The area around Sterling was first settled in the 1850s. Sterling was platted in 1871 and named after Sterling Township. A post office was established in Sterling in 1872, and the community has been known as Sterling since.

title: Wickford
text: Wickford is a town and civil parish in the City of Chelmsford, Essex, England. Situated approximately 12 miles (19 km) east-south-east of Chelmsford, it lies on the River Crouch. According to the 2011 Census, Wickford had a population of 33,855. Wickford is a market town with a long history. It is mentioned in the Domesday Book of 1086. The town's market charter was granted in 1252. Wickford was once a major port, but its importance declined after the River Crouch silted up. Today, Wickford is a thriving town with a diverse economy. It is home to a number of businesses, including the headquarters of Wickes. The town also has a busy shopping centre and a number of attractions for visitors, including Wickford Memorial Park and the Wickford Museum.

title: Jeremy Rifkin
text: Jeremy Rifkin is an American economist, social theorist, and public intellectual. He is the author of 21 books on the impact of scientific and technological change on the economy, society, and the environment. Rifkin is a vocal critic of the global economy and has proposed a number of alternative economic models, including the Third Industrial Revolution and the Collaborative Commons. He is also a strong advocate for environmental sustainability and has written extensively on the need to transition to a green economy. Rifkin is the founder and president of the Foundation on Economic Trends, a non-profit organization that promotes economic, social, and environmental sustainability.

title: Hatley, Mississippi
text: Hatley is a town in Monroe County, Mississippi, United States. The population was 482 at the 2020 census. Hatley was founded in 1872 and incorporated in 1904. The town is named for George Hatley, who donated the land for the town's first depot. Hatley is located on Mississippi Highway 389, approximately 12 miles (19 km) west of Aberdeen and 15 miles (24 km) east of Amory. The town is served by the Hatley School District, which includes Hatley Elementary School and Hatley High School.

title: Draft lottery (1969)
text: The draft lottery (1969) was a random lottery that determined the order of call-up for military service during the Vietnam War. The lottery was held on December 1, 1969, and assigned a random number to each man born between 1944 and 1950. The numbers were drawn live on television, and the order in which they were drawn determined the order in which men would be called up for service. The lottery was controversial, and many people argued that it was unfair and discriminatory. However, the lottery was implemented in an attempt to create a more equitable system for selecting men for military service.

title: Wolfram Freiherr von Richthofen
text: Wolfram Freiherr von Richthofen (1895-1945) was a German field marshal during World War II. As commander of the Army Group South, he played a significant role in the invasion of Poland, the Battle of France, and Operation Barbarossa. Known for his aggressive and ruthless tactics, Richthofen was responsible for numerous war crimes committed by his troops. He was killed in action during the Battle of Berlin in 1945.

title: Elmore, Ohio
text: Elmore is a village in Ottawa County, Ohio, United States. The population was 1,480 at the 2010 census. Elmore was founded in 1834 by a group of settlers from the state of New York. It was originally known as "York", but was later changed to "Elmore" after the Elm trees that were prevalent in the area. Elmore is home to a variety of businesses, including manufacturing, retail, and tourism. It is also home to a number of churches, schools, and parks.

title: Reform Act 1832
text: The Reform Act of 1832, also known as the Great Reform Act, was a major electoral reform act passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom. It was the first of a series of reforms that extended the franchise to more men and introduced the secret ballot. The act was a response to growing demands for political reform in the early 19th century, and its passage was a significant milestone in the development of British democracy.

title: Jane Seymour
text: Jane Seymour (c. 1508 or 1509 – 24 October 1537) was the third wife of King Henry VIII of England. She was queen consort for just over a year, from their marriage on 30 May 1536 until Jane's death in childbirth. Her only child, a son who was later to become King Edward VI, was born on 12 October 1537.

title: Hallands Nyheter
text: Hallands Nyheter is a Swedish-language daily newspaper published in Halmstad, Sweden. It is distributed in the counties of Halland, Kronoberg and Västra Götaland. The paper was founded in 1850 and is owned by the Bonnier Group. Hallands Nyheter has a circulation of around 31,000 copies and is the largest newspaper in Halland. The paper's political stance is described as liberal.

title: Inline expansion
text: Inline expansion is a technique in computer programming that involves substituting the actual value of a macro or constant into the source code at compile time. This eliminates the need for a separate preprocessing step and can improve compilation speed. However, inline expansion can also lead to code bloat and make it more difficult to maintain the source code. Advantages of inline expansion include: Improved compilation speed Reduced code size Simplified maintenance Disadvantages of inline expansion include: Increased code bloat Reduced readability Potential for errors

title: Hugh Fortescue, 2nd Earl Fortescue
text: Hugh Fortescue, 2nd Earl Fortescue (1753–1841), styled Viscount Ebrington from 1753 to 1807, was a British peer and politician. The son of Matthew Fortescue, 1st Baron Fortescue, he succeeded to the earldom in 1807. He served as Lord Lieutenant of Devon from 1807 to 1841 and was a Member of Parliament for Barnstaple from 1774 to 1784 and for Tavistock from 1784 to 1807. He was also a patron of the arts and a collector of books and manuscripts.

title: Manchego
text: Manchego is a firm and flavorful cheese made in the La Mancha region of central Spain. It is made from the milk of Manchega sheep and aged for a minimum of 60 days, though some varieties are aged for up to 2 years. Manchego has a pale yellow color with a slightly grainy texture. The flavor is nutty and slightly salty, with a caramel-like sweetness. Manchego is often paired with red wine, fruit, or nuts. It is also a popular ingredient in tapas.

title: Figured bass
text: Figured bass, also known as thoroughbass, is a musical notation system that indicates the bass line and the harmony above it using numbers and symbols. It was widely used from the Baroque period to the early 19th century and is still occasionally encountered in modern music. The numbers indicate the intervals above the bass note, while the symbols represent the type of chord. Figured bass was used by composers to provide a basic harmonic framework for instrumentalists to improvise or embellish. It also served as a teaching tool for students of harmony and composition.

title: South Portland, Maine
text: South Portland is a city in Cumberland County, Maine, United States. It is located on the southwestern shore of Casco Bay, across from the city of Portland. As of the 2020 census, the population was 25,002. South Portland is the fourth-largest city in Maine and the largest city in Cumberland County. The city is home to the Maine Mall, the largest shopping mall in Maine, and the Portland International Jetport, the busiest airport in Maine. South Portland is also home to several colleges and universities, including the University of Southern Maine and Southern Maine Community College.

title: Rhine
text: The Rhine River is a major river in Europe, flowing for 1,230 kilometers (760 miles) from the Swiss Alps to the North Sea. It is the second longest river in Europe after the Danube. The Rhine flows through six countries: Switzerland, Liechtenstein, Austria, Germany, France, and the Netherlands. The Rhine is a navigable river, and it has been an important trade route for centuries. The river basin is home to a population of over 50 million people, and it is one of the most densely populated areas in Europe.

title: Ivor Guest, 1st Viscount Wimborne
text: Ivor Guest, 1st Viscount Wimborne (1873-1939), was a British Liberal politician and businessman. He held various government posts, including Secretary of State for Home Affairs (1910-1915) and Lord Lieutenant of Ireland (1915-1918). Guest was a wealthy landowner and industrialist, inheriting the Wimborne House estate in Dorset. He was created Viscount Wimborne in 1918. He was also a keen sportsman and served as president of the Marylebone Cricket Club.

title: World's Columbian Exposition
text: The World's Columbian Exposition, officially known as the World's Fair: Columbian Exposition, was a world's fair held in Chicago, Illinois, from May 1 to October 30, 1893. It celebrated the 400th anniversary of Christopher Columbus's arrival in the New World. The fair showcased technological and cultural advancements and attracted over 27 million visitors. It left a lasting legacy on Chicago's architecture and culture, and its Ferris wheel, designed by George Washington Gale Ferris Jr., became an iconic landmark.

title: Ceredo, West Virginia
text: Ceredo is a town in Wayne County, West Virginia, United States. It is located on the Ohio River, opposite Kenova in Kentucky. As of the 2020 census, the town had a population of 1,453. Ceredo was founded in 1857 by John S. Witcher, who named it after his wife, Sarah Ann. The town grew rapidly in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, due to its location on the Ohio River and the development of the coal industry. Ceredo is home to the Ceredo-Kenova Independent School District, which serves students in Ceredo and Kenova. The town is also home to the Ceredo-Kenova Public Library and the Ceredo Historical Museum.

title: Integrated development environment
text: An integrated development environment (IDE) is a software application that provides comprehensive facilities to computer programmers for software development. An IDE normally consists of a source code editor, a compiler or interpreter, and a debugger. Some IDEs include a visual editor for graphical user interfaces and database tools. IDEs make it easier for programmers to write, edit, compile, debug, and deploy code. Popular IDEs include Microsoft Visual Studio, Eclipse, and IntelliJ IDEA.

title: HMS Somerset (F82)
text: HMS Somerset (F82) was a Type 23 frigate of the Royal Navy. She was the fifth ship to bear the name, and the second of the Duke class. Somerset was launched in 1988 and commissioned in 1990. The frigate served in a variety of roles, including anti-air warfare, anti-surface warfare, and anti-submarine warfare. She also took part in a number of operations, including the Gulf War, the Kosovo War, and the War in Afghanistan. Somerset was decommissioned in 2012 and sold to the Brazilian Navy. She was renamed BNS Pará (F40) and continues to serve in the Brazilian fleet.

title: Kent M. Keith
text: Kent M. Keith (born 1942) is an American author, speaker, and former Air Force intelligence officer. He is best known for his books on Soviet and Russian intelligence, including "Spycraft: The Secret World of Intelligence" and "Moscow's Game: The KGB's Global Assault on America." Keith has also written extensively about the history of espionage and intelligence operations. He is a frequent lecturer on intelligence and national security issues and has appeared on numerous television and radio programs.

title: Mercedes-Benz R-Class
text: The Mercedes-Benz R-Class is a luxury crossover SUV produced by Mercedes-Benz from 2005 to 2017. It was introduced at the 2005 New York International Auto Show and was available in both long-wheelbase and short-wheelbase configurations. The R-Class was discontinued in 2017, with its replacement being the Mercedes-Benz GLE-Class. The R-Class was available with a variety of engine options, including gasoline, diesel, and hybrid powertrains. It was also offered with a range of comfort and convenience features, such as a panoramic sunroof, a power liftgate, and a rear-seat entertainment system. The R-Class was a popular choice for families and those seeking a spacious and versatile vehicle.

title: Derek Walcott
text: Derek Alton Walcott (1930-2017) was a Saint Lucian poet and playwright. He received the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1992, becoming the first writer from the Caribbean to be so honored. Walcott's work is known for its rich imagery, exploration of history, and Caribbean culture. His notable works include "In a Green Night" (1962), "Omeros" (1990), and "Tiepolo's Hound" (2000). Walcott's influential career spanned over six decades, and his legacy continues to inspire contemporary artists and literary scholars.

title: Shot put
text: Shot put is an athletics track and field event where athletes throw a heavy metal ball, called a shot, as far as possible. The shot weighs 7.26 kg for men and 4 kg for women. The technique involves holding the shot in one hand close to the shoulder, then pushing it out in a smooth, continuous motion. The throw is made from a circle with a diameter of 2.135 meters (7 feet) for men and 2.135 meters (7 feet) for women. The winner is the athlete who throws the shot the farthest distance, measured from the edge of the circle to the point where the shot first lands.

title: William Roscoe
text: William Roscoe (March 8, 1753 – June 30, 1831) was an English writer, art collector, abolitionist, botanist, and politician. While working as a clerk in Liverpool, Roscoe began writing poetry and studying Italian literature. Following the success of his 1796 work, The Life of Lorenzo de' Medici, Called the Magnificent, Roscoe became a leading figure in literary and artistic circles. A supporter of abolitionism, he was a founding member of the Liverpool Society for the Abolition of Slavery in 1788. In 1799, Roscoe began collecting art, amassing a significant collection of Italian paintings and drawings. He served as a Member of Parliament from 1806 to 1807, representing Liverpool.

title: Boyne Valley Township, Michigan
text: Boyne Valley Township is a charter township of Charlevoix County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The population was 1,942 at the 2020 census. The township is located in the southern part of the county, and is bordered by Antrim County to the south, Otsego County to the east, and Charlevoix Township to the north. The township is home to the Boyne Mountain Resort, a popular ski and golf destination.

title: Wabash College
text: Wabash College is a private liberal arts college in Crawfordsville, Indiana, United States. Founded in 1832, Wabash is the oldest college in Indiana and one of the oldest in the Midwest. It is known for its strong academic programs, particularly in the natural sciences and mathematics. Wabash is consistently ranked among the top liberal arts colleges in the country. The college offers a wide range of undergraduate programs, including majors in the humanities, social sciences, natural sciences, and mathematics. Wabash is also home to a number of nationally recognized academic programs, including the Wabash Center for Inquiry and the Lilly Center for Religion and Society.

title: Munich U-Bahn
text: The Munich U-Bahn is a rapid transit system serving the city of Munich, Germany. It is operated by Münchner Verkehrsgesellschaft (MVG) and consists of eight lines, designated by numbers U1 to U8. The system has a total length of 103.1 kilometers (64.1 miles) and 100 stations. The U-Bahn is a key part of Munich's public transport network, carrying over 1.5 million passengers daily.

title: Video game development
text: Video game development encompasses all stages involved in creating a video game, from conceptualization and design to programming, testing, and release. It requires collaboration among various specialists, including game designers, programmers, artists, and testers, who work together to bring a game to life. The development process typically involves prototyping, level design, character creation, and coding. The game's mechanics, story, and aesthetics are meticulously crafted to provide an engaging and entertaining experience for players. Quality assurance plays a crucial role in ensuring the game's stability and user-friendliness.

title: Marvin Heemeyer
text: Marvin Heemeyer (October 28, 1951 – June 4, 2004) was an American welder and auto mechanic who, on June 4, 2004, went on a rampage in Granby, Colorado, United States, destroying 13 buildings with a modified bulldozer he had named "Killdozer". Heemeyer's rampage was the culmination of a long-running dispute with town officials over zoning issues and building code violations. He had been cited for operating his muffler shop without a permit and ordered to cease operations. He believed that the town was conspiring against him and that the only way to resolve the dispute was through violence. Heemeyer's rampage ended when he took his own life inside the Killdozer after being confronted by police.

title: Communists in the United States Labor Movement (1919–37)
text: During the period of 1919 to 1937, the United States labor movement witnessed the active participation of communists. They played a significant role in organizing industrial workers into unions, particularly in mass industries like auto, steel, and electrical manufacturing. Communists often led strikes and other forms of labor activism, advocating for improved working conditions and economic justice. However, their influence diminished in the late 1930s as anti-communist sentiment grew and the labor movement shifted towards a more moderate stance.

title: Mahathir Mohamad
text: Mahathir Mohamad, born on July 10, 1925, is a Malaysian politician who served as the fourth Prime Minister of Malaysia for two terms, from 1981 to 2003 and again from 2018 to 2020. Widely regarded as the "Father of Modern Malaysia," he is known for his authoritarian style and ambitious economic development policies, which transformed Malaysia into a newly industrialized country. Mahathir is also known for his outspoken views on a range of international issues, including Islam and Western influence.

title: USS Pogy (SSN-647)
text: USS Pogy (SSN-647) was a Sturgeon-class attack submarine in the United States Navy. The second ship of her class, Pogy was laid down on June 1, 1963, at the Ingalls Shipbuilding Division of Litton Industries in Pascagoula, Mississippi. She was launched on April 9, 1964, and commissioned on June 26, 1965. Pogy served in the Pacific Fleet for her entire career, making numerous deployments to the Western Pacific and Indian Oceans. She participated in several major exercises, including Operation Sea Orbit, the first submerged circumnavigation of the Earth. Pogy was decommissioned on November 21, 1991, and disposed of through the Nuclear-Powered Ship and Submarine Recycling Program at Puget Sound Naval Shipyard in Bremerton, Washington.

title: Makati
text: Makati, officially the City of Makati, is a highly urbanized city in the National Capital Region of the Philippines. It is known as the country's financial center and is home to the Philippine Stock Exchange and many multinational corporations. Makati is also known for its upscale shopping malls, dining establishments, and vibrant nightlife. The city has a population of over 500,000 people and is considered one of the most affluent cities in the Philippines.

title: The Devil in Miss Jones
text: "The Devil in Miss Jones" is a 1941 American horror film directed by Henry Levin. It follows the story of Mary Jones, a young woman who becomes possessed by the devil after a séance. As her behavior becomes increasingly erratic and violent, those around her struggle to help her while facing the malevolent force that has taken hold of her soul.

title: Goodman, Mississippi
text: Goodman, Mississippi, is a town in Holmes County. As of the 2020 census, the town's population was 1,338. Goodman was founded in 1882 as a station on the Illinois Central Railroad. The town is named after Andrew Goodman, a civil rights worker who was murdered in 1964 during the Mississippi Freedom Summer campaign.  Goodman is located in the Mississippi Delta region and is known for its agriculture. The town is home to several cotton gins and grain elevators. Goodman is also home to Holmes Community College, a two-year college that offers a variety of academic and technical programs.

title: Gardner Fox
text: Gardner Francis Fox (May 20, 1911 – December 24, 1986) was an American comics writer. He was inducted into the Will Eisner Award Hall of Fame in 1990. Fox began working for DC Comics in 1936, where he created or co-created many of the company's most popular characters, including The Flash, Hawkman, Green Lantern, and the Justice Society of America. He also wrote extensively for Marvel Comics and other publishers. Fox's writing was characterized by its imaginative plots and memorable characters. He was a master of the superhero genre and helped to define the Golden Age of Comics.

title: Devika Rani
text: Devika Rani (born Devika Rani Chaudhuri), was an Indian actress and producer. She is widely regarded as the "First Lady of Indian Cinema". Rani began her acting career in 1933 with the film Karma. She went on to star in several successful films, including Achhut Kanya (1936), Nirmala (1938), and Humrahi (1941). In 1940, she married Himanshu Rai, the founder of Bombay Talkies. Together, they produced several films, including "Kismet" (1943) and "Mahal" (1949). Rani retired from acting in 1945 and devoted her time to producing films and promoting Indian cinema internationally.

title: Marana, Arizona
text: Marana, Arizona, is a town located in Pima County, adjacent to Tucson. As of the 2020 census, the population was 50,924. Marana is known for its Sonoran Desert setting, offering scenic views and outdoor recreation opportunities. It is home to the Arizona Pavilions shopping center and the Tucson Premium Outlets. Marana's economy is driven by retail, healthcare, and tourism. The town is served by the Marana Unified School District and Pima Community College. Marana is known for its community involvement and events, including the Marana Heritage Festival and the Marana Country Fair.

title: Warmen
text: Warmen is a Finnish power metal band formed in 1995. The band was founded by keyboardist Janne Wirman, guitarist Sami Virtanen, bassist Mirka Rantanen, and drummer Sami Karppinen. Warmen's music is characterized by its fast tempos, melodic guitar riffs, and soaring vocals. The band has released seven studio albums, two live albums, and two compilation albums. Warmen has toured extensively throughout Europe and Asia, and has performed at several major metal festivals, including Wacken Open Air and Bloodstock Open Air.

title: Prague
text: Prague is the capital and largest city of the Czech Republic. It is the 14th largest city in the European Union and the historical capital of Bohemia. The city is famous for its well-preserved historical center, including the Charles Bridge, Prague Castle, and the Old Town Square. Prague is also known for its beer, with many breweries and beer gardens scattered throughout the city. The city has a population of over 1.3 million people and is a popular tourist destination, with over 7 million tourists visiting each year.

title: Gaines, Michigan
text: Gaines is a village in Genesee County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The population was 394 at the 2010 census. The village is located within Fenton Township, but is autonomous. Gaines was founded in 1832 by Samuel and Mary Gaines. The village was originally known as "Gaines Station" due to its location on the Detroit and Milwaukee Railroad. The name was shortened to "Gaines" in 1894. Gaines is home to the Gaines Historical Museum, which houses a collection of artifacts and documents related to the history of the village and surrounding area.

title: Scuderia Ferrari
text: Scuderia Ferrari is an Italian racing team founded in 1929 by Enzo Ferrari. It is the oldest surviving and most successful Formula One team, having won 15 Drivers' Championships and 16 Constructors' Championships. The team is based in Maranello, Italy, and its current drivers are Charles Leclerc and Carlos Sainz Jr. Ferrari is one of the most iconic and recognizable brands in the world, and its cars are known for their red color and prancing horse logo. The team has a long and storied history, and has produced some of the greatest drivers in Formula One history, including Michael Schumacher, Niki Lauda, and Juan Manuel Fangio.

title: Brooke Foss Westcott
text: Brooke Foss Westcott (1825-1901) was an eminent British theologian and biblical scholar. He was Regius Professor of Divinity at the University of Cambridge from 1870 to 1890, and Bishop of Durham from 1890 until his death. Westcott was a leading figure in the Revised Version of the Bible, published in 1881, and his writings on the New Testament and the history of Christian thought remain influential today. His belief in the importance of textual criticism and historical scholarship in biblical studies helped shape the modern understanding of the Bible.

title: Brad Renfro
text: Brad Renfro (July 25, 1982 – January 15, 2008) was an American actor. He rose to stardom as a child actor in the 1994 film "The Client," for which he received a nomination for the Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor. He went on to star in several other films, including "Sleepers" (1996), "Apt Pupil" (1998), and "Ghost World" (2001). Renfro's career was marred by personal struggles, including substance abuse and legal issues. He died of an accidental drug overdose at the age of 25.

title: Milla Jovovich
text: Milla Jovovich is an American actress, model, and singer. She is best known for her roles as Leeloo in Luc Besson's The Fifth Element (1997), Alice in the Resident Evil film series (2002–present), and Jill Valentine in the Resident Evil: Apocalypse video game (2004). Jovovich has also appeared in a number of other films, including Zoolander (2001), Ultraviolet (2006), and Stone (2010). She has also released three albums, "The Divine Comedy" (1994), "The People Tree Sessions" (1998), and "Underworld" (2003).

title: Brookings, Oregon
text: Brookings is a city in Curry County, Oregon, United States. It is named after John E. Brookings, who was the president of the Pacific Improvement Company, which built the town in 1908. Brookings is located at the mouth of the Chetco River on the Pacific Ocean. The population was 6,336 at the 2010 census. Brookings is a popular tourist destination, known for its fishing, crabbing, and whale watching. The city is also home to the Brookings Harbor, which is one of the largest commercial fishing ports in Oregon.

title: Sam Shepard
text: Sam Shepard (1943-2017) was an American playwright, actor, screenwriter, and director. He was a leading figure in the American avant-garde theater movement and wrote over 50 plays, including "True West" (1980), "Buried Child" (1978), and "Fool for Love" (1983). Shepard's plays often explored themes of family, the American West, and the search for identity. He also starred in several films, including "Days of Heaven" (1978), "The Right Stuff" (1983), and "Paris, Texas" (1984). Shepard's work has been widely acclaimed and he was awarded the Pulitzer Prize for Drama in 1979 for "Buried Child."

title: Parenteral nutrition
text: Parenteral nutrition (PN) is a method of providing nutrition to patients who are unable to take in enough nutrients through their digestive tract. PN delivers nutrients intravenously, directly into the bloodstream.
