It is used in a variety of clinical settings, including: - Short-term use: For patients who are unable to eat or drink for a short period of time, such as after surgery or during an illness. - Long-term use: For patients who have a chronic condition that prevents them from absorbing nutrients from food, such as Crohn's disease or cancer. PN can be a life-saving treatment for patients who are unable to meet their nutritional needs through oral intake. However, it is important to note that PN is a complex therapy that requires careful monitoring and management by a healthcare professional.

title: Hiram Walker
text: Hiram Walker (May 4, 1816 – January 12, 1899) was a Canadian-American businessman and distiller. He founded Hiram Walker & Sons, Ltd., one of the largest distilleries in the world. Walker was born in Amherstburg, Ontario, Canada. He moved to Detroit, Michigan, in 1834 and established a general store. In 1858, he founded Hiram Walker & Sons, Ltd., which initially produced whiskey, gin, and other spirits. The company grew rapidly and became one of the largest distilleries in the world. Walker was a prominent figure in Detroit and was involved in many civic and charitable activities. He served as a member of the Detroit Board of Education and was a generous donor to the city's hospitals and churches.

title: Contemporary Sant Mat movements
text: Contemporary Sant Mat movements trace their origins to the teachings of Sant Mat, a spiritual path originating in India. These movements emphasize meditation, self-realization, and ethical living. Prominent lineages include the Radha Soami Satsang Beas, the Sant Nirankari Mission, and the Divine Light Mission. Their teachings focus on uniting with the divine through inner practices such as Surat Shabd Yoga (union of consciousness and the inner sound current). Contemporary Sant Mat movements have gained global followers, offering a path to spiritual growth and a deeper understanding of the self.

title: Flook (band)
text: Flook is an English folk group formed in 1995. The band is composed of Brian Finnegan (mandolin, vocals), Sarah Allen (concertina, fiddle, vocals), and Ed Boyd (guitar, vocals). Their music is a blend of traditional folk tunes and original compositions, often featuring intricate harmonies and virtuosic instrumental playing. Flook has released six studio albums and toured extensively throughout the UK, Europe, and North America. They have won several awards, including two BBC Radio 2 Folk Awards for Best Group. The band's name comes from the Cornish word for "wave," reflecting their shared love for the sea and coastal landscapes.

title: Juniata Township, Blair County, Pennsylvania
text: Juniata Township is a township in Blair County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 4,722 at the 2010 census. It is part of the Altoona, PA Metropolitan Statistical Area. The township surrounds the borough of Williamsburg. The Frankstown Branch Juniata River flows through the township. Juniata Township was founded in 1844. It was named after the Juniata River, which flows through the township. The township is home to a number of businesses and industries, including the Williamsburg Generating Station, a coal-fired power plant.

title: Richard's paradox
text: Richard's paradox, proposed by Jules Richard in 1905, questions the logical validity of defining a set of all sets that do not contain themselves. If such a set, denoted R, exists, it leads to a contradiction. If R contains itself, it should not, by its own definition. If it does not contain itself, by definition, it should. This paradox exposes a fundamental limitation in set theory, known as Russell's paradox, which highlights the need for a rigorous axiomatic foundation for mathematics.

title: Jacobaea vulgaris
text: Jacobaea vulgaris, commonly known as ragwort, is a widespread and toxic herbaceous plant found throughout Europe and North America. It has distinctive bright yellow flowers that bloom in summer. The plant is biennial, meaning it takes two years to complete its life cycle. Jacobaea vulgaris is known for its ability to accumulate pyrrolizidine alkaloids, which are toxic to both humans and animals. Ingestion of the plant can cause severe liver damage, leading to liver failure in extreme cases. Due to its toxicity, ragwort is considered a nuisance plant and efforts are made to control its spread.

title: Commodity
text: A commodity is a good or service that can be bought and sold in the market. It is usually interchangeable with other commodities of the same type. Commodities are often raw materials or agricultural products, such as oil, gold, wheat, and coffee. They are traded on commodity exchanges, where buyers and sellers can agree on a price and quantity. Commodity prices are influenced by supply and demand, as well as by global economic conditions.

title: Londinium
text: Londinium was a Roman city founded around 43 AD on the north bank of the River Thames. It was the capital of Roman Britain for over 300 years and grew to become one of the largest and most important cities in the Roman Empire. Londinium was a major center of trade and commerce, and it was home to a large population of merchants, artisans, and government officials. The city was also a major cultural center, with theaters, amphitheaters, and public baths. Londinium was abandoned around the end of the 4th century AD, possibly due to political instability or economic decline. However, the city was reoccupied by the Anglo-Saxons in the 6th century and became the nucleus of modern London.

title: Military science
text: Military science is the study of the application of scientific principles to military operations. It includes the study of weapons, tactics, strategy, and logistics. Military science is used to develop new technologies and strategies for the military, and to train military personnel in the use of these technologies and strategies. Military science is a complex field that draws on a variety of disciplines, including physics, chemistry, biology, mathematics, and computer science. It is also a constantly evolving field, as new technologies and strategies are developed.

title: Ferdinand Anton Ernst Porsche
text: Ferdinand Anton Ernst Porsche, also known as Ferry Porsche, was a German automotive engineer and industrialist. The son of Ferdinand Porsche, Ferry is best known for his role in developing the Porsche 356, the first production Porsche automobile. He also played a key role in the development of the Porsche 911, one of the most iconic sports cars in history. Ferry Porsche led Porsche AG for over 50 years, transforming it into one of the world's most successful automotive companies.

title: Albion (video game)
text: Albion is an action role-playing game developed by Blue Byte and published by Ubisoft in 2005. The game is set in the fictional world of Albion, a mystical and dangerous realm where players assume the role of a hero tasked with saving the land from an ancient evil. Albion features a vast open world, real-time combat, and a rich storyline. Players can explore the world, interact with characters, complete quests, and develop their character's abilities. The game received positive reviews for its immersive gameplay, stunning visuals, and engaging story.

title: Knuth–Bendix completion algorithm
text: The Knuth–Bendix completion algorithm is a method for deciding the word problem for a finitely presented group. It takes a finite set of rewriting rules as input and, if the input defines a finitely presented group, produces a decision procedure for the word problem. The algorithm works by repeatedly applying the rewriting rules to all possible pairs of words in the group until no more reductions are possible. If the input is finite and defines a finitely presented group, then the algorithm will eventually terminate and produce a decision procedure for the word problem. However, the algorithm is not guaranteed to terminate if the input is infinite or does not define a finitely presented group.

title: That's My Bush!
text: "That's My Bush!" is a humorous point-and-click adventure game developed by LucasArts and released in 1995. The player controls President George H. W. Bush as he travels the world and solves puzzles to thwart the evil Dr. Evil. The game features parodies of real-world events and people, including Bill Clinton, Fidel Castro, and Margaret Thatcher. "That's My Bush!" was a critical and commercial success, selling over 1 million copies worldwide. It was praised for its humor, puzzles, and voice acting.

title: Lamborghini
text: Lamborghini is an Italian manufacturer of luxury sports cars and SUVs. Founded in 1963 by Ferruccio Lamborghini, the company is headquartered in Sant'Agata Bolognese, Italy. Lamborghini's early success was with the Miura, a mid-engine sports car that was considered one of the most beautiful and technologically advanced cars of its time. Today, Lamborghini produces a range of high-performance cars, including the Aventador, Huracán, and Urus. The company is known for its innovative design, engineering, and performance.

title: Frank Wead
text: Frank Wead (1895-1947) was an American inventor and engineer known for his contributions to aviation and automotive technology. As an employee of the Delco Remy Division of General Motors, he invented the first practical electric fuel pump in 1927, revolutionizing fuel delivery systems. He also developed the Wead roller camshaft, a key component in high-performance engines. Wead's inventions significantly improved the efficiency, reliability, and performance of aircraft and automobiles.

title: Farmington, Washington
text: Farmington is an unincorporated community in Whitman County, Washington, United States. It is located approximately 12 miles (19 km) southeast of Pullman, at the junction of State Route 27 and State Route 194. The elevation is 2,464 feet (751 m). Farmington was founded in 1881 by settlers from the Midwest. Its economy was primarily based on agriculture, with wheat and barley being the main crops. Farmington has a post office with the ZIP code 99128. The community is served by the Farmington School District.

title: Isle of Mull Railway
text: The Isle of Mull Railway is a heritage railway on the Isle of Mull, Scotland. It runs for 6.5 miles (10.5 km) between the village of Craignure and the town of Tobermory. The railway was built in the 19th century to transport fish and other goods from the island to the mainland. It closed in 1930 but was reopened in 1975 as a heritage railway. The railway is now operated by a volunteer-run charity. It is a popular tourist attraction, and it also provides a valuable transport service for the island's residents.

title: Mount Carmel
text: Mount Carmel is a coastal mountain range in northern Israel extending from the Mediterranean Sea towards the southeast. The range rises to 546 meters (1,791 feet) above sea level at its highest point. Mount Carmel is known for its abundant vegetation, including forests, shrubs, and wildflowers. The area is also home to a variety of wildlife, including deer, gazelles, and wild boars. Mount Carmel has been inhabited since prehistoric times, and it has been the site of many battles and religious conflicts throughout history. Today, Mount Carmel is a popular tourist destination and a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

title: WeatherTech Raceway Laguna Seca
text: WeatherTech Raceway Laguna Seca is a renowned 2.238-mile road course nestled in the picturesque Salinas Valley of California. It has hosted legendary races such as the Monterey Grand Prix and the Rolex Monterey Motorsports Reunion. This iconic track is known for its challenging twists and turns, including the famous "Corkscrew" descent. Drivers navigate through undulating hillsides, testing their skills and the limits of their machines. The raceway offers a thrilling experience for competitors and spectators alike, set against a breathtaking natural backdrop.

title: Triple J
text: Triple J is an Australian radio station owned and operated by the Australian Broadcasting Corporation (ABC). It is the national youth radio station, broadcasting a mix of alternative rock, indie, electronic, hip hop, and world music. Triple J is known for its support of new and emerging artists, and its annual Hottest 100 countdown of the most popular songs of the year is a major cultural event in Australia. The station also produces a number of popular podcasts, including The J Files, Hack, and The Weekly Planet.

title: Process-oriented psychology
text: Process-oriented psychology is a holistic approach to psychotherapy that focuses on the ongoing process of experiencing rather than on past events or future goals. It emphasizes the importance of understanding the present moment and how it is shaped by past experiences and future expectations. Process-oriented psychology aims to help individuals become more aware of their inner world and to develop the skills to manage their emotions and relationships more effectively. It is based on the belief that people have the potential to change and grow throughout their lives.

title: Pickering, North Yorkshire
text: Pickering is a small market town in the North York Moors National Park, North Yorkshire, England. It is situated in the Ryedale district, 23 miles (37 km) north-east of York. Pickering is known for its historical sites, including Pickering Castle, a 12th-century Norman castle, and the ruins of Rievaulx Abbey, a former Cistercian abbey founded in the 12th century. The town is also a popular tourist destination, with visitors attracted to its charming streets, independent shops, and traditional pubs.

title: John Peckham
text: John Peckham (c. 1230 – 8 December 1292), also known as Pecham or Peccham, was an English Franciscan friar, Archbishop of Canterbury, and a philosopher and theologian. As Archbishop, he was a strong supporter of the mendicant orders, and his writings on poverty and the nature of the Church were influential in the development of Franciscan thought. His writings on optics were influential in the development of the science of optics, and he is also known for his work on the calendar.

title: Courtyard
text: Courtyard is a brand of upscale hotels owned by Marriott International. The brand was launched in 1983 and has since grown to over 1,200 hotels in more than 50 countries and territories. Courtyard hotels are typically located in urban and suburban areas and offer a variety of amenities, including free Wi-Fi, fitness centers, and swimming pools. The brand also offers a loyalty program, Marriott Rewards, which allows guests to earn points towards free nights, upgrades, and other rewards.

title: Vesicle (biology and chemistry)
text: A vesicle is a small, fluid-filled sac within a cell or organism. Vesicles serve a variety of functions, including transport, storage, and protection. In biology, vesicles are often used to transport materials between different parts of a cell, while in chemistry, vesicles are used to encapsulate and deliver drugs or other substances. Vesicles can be formed from a variety of materials, including lipids, proteins, and carbohydrates. They range in size from a few nanometers to several micrometers in diameter.

title: Agricultural history of Peru
text: The agricultural history of Peru spans thousands of years, dating back to the pre-Incan period. The ancient Peruvians were skilled farmers who developed advanced irrigation systems and domesticated a wide variety of crops, including potatoes, maize, and quinoa. During the Inca Empire, agriculture was further developed and became the foundation of the economy. The Incas built vast networks of terraces and irrigation canals, allowing them to cultivate crops in even the most arid regions. After the Spanish conquest, Peruvian agriculture was transformed by the introduction of new crops and livestock, such as wheat, sugar, and cattle. Today, Peru remains a major agricultural producer, exporting a variety of crops, including coffee, cocoa, and asparagus.

title: Eyepiece
text: An eyepiece, also known as an ocular lens, is the optical element in a telescope or microscope that is closest to the viewer's eye. It is typically a simple lens, but can also be a compound lens consisting of multiple elements. The eyepiece serves to magnify the image formed by the objective lens, and its focal length determines the magnification of the instrument. Eyepieces are typically interchangeable, allowing the user to select the desired magnification for a given application.

title: Tusk
text: Tusk is a 1980 American horror film written, co-produced, and directed by Kevin Smith and starring Justin Long and Michael Parks. It follows a podcaster who travels to Canada to interview a reclusive former walrus hunter and becomes trapped in his remote cabin. The film received generally negative reviews from critics, who found it to be too repetitive and lacking in suspense, but it grossed over $1.5 million worldwide against a production budget of $100,000.

title: Battle of Kursk
text: The Battle of Kursk was a pivotal battle of World War II, fought between the German Wehrmacht and the Soviet Red Army in July and August 1943. It was the largest tank battle in history, involving over 6,000 tanks. The battle began with a massive German offensive, but the Soviets gradually blunted the attack and launched a counteroffensive that ultimately forced the Germans to retreat. The Soviet victory at Kursk marked a turning point in the war on the Eastern Front, and the German army never regained the initiative.

title: Chipotle Mexican Grill
text: Chipotle Mexican Grill is an American fast-casual restaurant chain that specializes in tacos, burritos, bowls, and salads. Founded in Denver, Colorado, in 1993, Chipotle has since expanded to over 2,500 locations worldwide. The company is known for its customizable menu, which allows customers to create their own dishes by choosing from a variety of meats, vegetables, sauces, and toppings. Chipotle has been praised for its fresh ingredients, affordable prices, and commitment to sustainability.

title: National Park Service
text: The National Park Service (NPS) is a federal agency of the United States Department of the Interior that manages the 423 national parks, national monuments, and other protected areas and historical sites across the country. The NPS was established on August 25, 1916, by President Woodrow Wilson. Its mission is to "conserve the scenery and the natural and historic objects and the wild life therein and to provide for the enjoyment of the same in such manner and by such means as will leave them unimpaired for the enjoyment of future generations." The NPS is also responsible for managing the National Trails System and the National Wild and Scenic Rivers System.

title: Law & Order
text: Law & Order is an American crime drama television franchise created by Dick Wolf. The franchise began in 1990 with the original series, Law & Order, which follows the detectives and prosecutors of the New York City Police Department and the Manhattan District Attorney's office as they investigate and prosecute crimes. The franchise has since expanded to include several spin-offs, including Law & Order: Special Victims Unit, Law & Order: Criminal Intent, and Law & Order: Trial by Jury. The franchise has been praised for its realistic portrayal of the criminal justice system and its exploration of complex social issues.

title: Cambridge University Press
text: Cambridge University Press is the publishing house of the University of Cambridge. It is the oldest university press in the world, and one of the largest and most prestigious. The Press publishes a wide range of academic books, journals, and other materials, and is known for its high quality and scholarship. It is also a major publisher in the field of English language teaching.

title: Elkhart County, Indiana
text: Elkhart County is a county located in the north-central portion of the U.S. state of Indiana. As of the 2020 census, the population was 204,483. The county seat is Goshen. Elkhart County is part of the South Bend-Elkhart-Mishawaka, IN-MI Metropolitan Statistical Area. The county is home to a large Amish and Mennonite population. Elkhart County is also known for its recreational opportunities, including fishing, boating, and camping.

title: Golden Gate Park
text: Golden Gate Park is a large urban park in San Francisco, California. It is 1,017 acres (412 ha) in size and is bordered by the Pacific Ocean on the west, the Richmond District to the north, the Sunset District to the south, and the Haight-Ashbury neighborhood to the east. The park is home to a variety of attractions, including the Japanese Tea Garden, the Conservatory of Flowers, and the California Academy of Sciences. It is also a popular spot for picnicking, biking, and walking.

title: Art colony
text: An art colony is a community of artists who live and work together in close proximity. Art colonies have existed since the 19th century, and they have been a major force in the development of modern art. Some of the most famous art colonies include the Barbizon School in France, the Newlyn School in England, and the Taos Society of Artists in the United States. Art colonies provide artists with a supportive environment in which to create and share their work. They also offer opportunities for collaboration and cross-pollination of ideas.

title: Psychology of religion
text: Psychology of religion, a subfield of psychology, investigates the intersection of religion and psychology. It explores religious beliefs, practices, and experiences and their impact on individuals and society. Psychologists study the cognitive, emotional, and behavioral aspects of religiosity, examining how religious beliefs shape personality, coping mechanisms, and mental health outcomes. By integrating psychological principles with theological perspectives, the psychology of religion aims to understand the complex interplay between faith and human behavior.

title: Flagler Beach, Florida
text: Flagler Beach is a city in Flagler County, Florida, United States. It is located on the Atlantic coast, approximately halfway between Jacksonville and Daytona Beach. The city is named after Henry Morrison Flagler, who built the Florida East Coast Railway in the late 19th century. Flagler Beach is a popular tourist destination, known for its beaches, surfing, and fishing. The city is also home to the Flagler Beach Historical Museum, which houses exhibits on the history of the area.

title: Ertuğrul Osman
text: Ertuğrul Osman (1814-1861) was the 30th head of the Ottoman dynasty. He reigned from 2 July 1839 to 25 June 1861. Born in Constantinople to the Sultan Mahmud II, Ertuğrul Osman was renowned for his liberal views and progressive reforms. He implemented reforms in education, agriculture, and the military. He also established the first modern postal system in the empire. Despite his reforms, his reign was marked by increasing foreign influence and internal unrest. He died in 1861 at the age of 47, leaving behind a legacy of modernization and attempts to bridge the gap between the Ottoman Empire and the West.

title: Motorola 68040
text: The Motorola 68040 is a 32-bit microprocessor introduced by Motorola in 1990. It was the successor to the Motorola 68030 and was designed to be used in high-performance personal computers and workstations. The 68040 featured a number of improvements over the 68030, including a faster clock speed, larger data and instruction caches, and an improved memory management unit. It was also the first Motorola microprocessor to implement the IEEE 754 standard for floating-point arithmetic. The 68040 was used in a number of popular computers, including the Apple Macintosh Quadra and the NeXTstation.

title: Homosassa, Florida
text: Homosassa, Florida, is an unincorporated community located in Citrus County. It is situated on the west coast of Florida, approximately 70 miles north of Tampa. Homosassa is known for its natural beauty, particularly its crystal-clear waters and diverse wildlife. The Homosassa River, which flows through the community, is home to a wide variety of fish, including manatees, dolphins, and tarpon. Homosassa also boasts several parks and nature preserves, offering opportunities for fishing, kayaking, and hiking. The community is a popular destination for tourists and nature enthusiasts.

title: Jack Palance
text: Jack Palance (born Walter Jack Palahniuk; February 18, 1919 – November 10, 2006) was an American actor. He was known for his deep, resonant voice, menacing screen presence, and distinctive, one-eyed squint, the result of a World War II injury. Palance won three Golden Globe Awards, an Emmy Award, and was nominated for three Academy Awards, including Best Supporting Actor for his roles in "Shane" (1953) and "City Slickers" (1991). He also received the Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Award in 1992.

title: United States men's national soccer team
text: The United States men's national soccer team represents the United States in international soccer and is governed by the United States Soccer Federation (USSF). The team has been a member of FIFA since 1913 and CONCACAF since 1961. The United States has participated in ten FIFA World Cups, with their best result being third place in 1930. The team has also won seven CONCACAF Gold Cups, the most of any team in the tournament's history.

title: Umbra, penumbra and antumbra
text: Umbra, penumbra, and antumbra are three regions of a shadow cast by an opaque object in the path of light. The umbra is the darkest region, where no light reaches. The penumbra is the partially shaded region, where some light reaches. The antumbra is the region outside the umbra and penumbra, where full light reaches. During a solar eclipse, the umbra is the area of complete darkness on the ground, where the Moon completely blocks the Sun. The penumbra is the area of partial darkness, where the Moon partially blocks the Sun. The antumbra is the area of full light, where the Moon does not block the Sun.

title: Wesleyan University
text: Wesleyan University is a private liberal arts college in Middletown, Connecticut. Founded in 1831 by a group of Methodist ministers, the university is named after John Wesley, the founder of Methodism. Wesleyan is a member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference (NESCAC) and the American Association of Universities (AAU). It is consistently ranked among the top liberal arts colleges in the United States, and its alumni include many notable figures in academia, politics, business, and the arts.

title: Proof (play)
text: "Proof" is a play by David Auburn that premiered on Broadway in 2000. It tells the story of Catherine, a brilliant but troubled young woman who struggles with schizophrenia. After her father's death, she is left to care for his mathematical proofs, which may or may not be groundbreaking. As she delves into her father's work, she must confront her own mental illness and the legacy of her family. "Proof" won the 2001 Pulitzer Prize for Drama and the Tony Award for Best Play.

title: Saskatchewan Government Insurance
text: Saskatchewan Government Insurance (SGI) is a provincial Crown corporation that provides automobile insurance, home insurance, farm insurance, and commercial insurance in the province of Saskatchewan, Canada. SGI is the only provider of auto insurance in the province, and it has a monopoly on the sale of home, farm, and commercial insurance. SGI was created in 1946 by an act of the Saskatchewan Legislature, and it is headquartered in Regina.

title: Floyd Gottfredson
text: Floyd Gottfredson (1905-1986) was an American cartoonist best known for his work on the Mickey Mouse comic strip. He joined the Disney Studios in 1930 and quickly became one of the main artists on the strip. Gottfredson's stories were characterized by their detailed artwork, humorous dialogue, and exciting adventures. He also created many iconic Disney characters, including Goofy, Pluto, and Donald Duck. Gottfredson's work on Mickey Mouse continued for over 40 years, and he is considered one of the most influential cartoonists of all time.

title: Ted Cassidy
text: Ted Cassidy (July 31, 1932 – January 16, 1979) was an American actor known for his tall, imposing stature (6'9"), booming voice, and memorable character roles in film and television. He is best remembered for his performances as Lurch in the Addams Family television series and Thing in The Addams Family movie. Cassidy's other notable roles include the giant Ro-Man in the science fiction film Robot Monster (1953), the android Adam Strange in the CBS series Lost in Space (1965), and the villain MODOK in the Marvel Comics' animated series The Incredible Hulk (1978).

title: Addressing mode
text: An addressing mode is a computer instruction that specifies how to calculate the effective address of an operand. The addressing mode is typically encoded in the opcode of the instruction. Common addressing modes include immediate, register, direct, indirect, and indexed. The immediate addressing mode specifies that the operand is contained in the instruction itself. The register addressing mode specifies that the operand is contained in a register. The direct addressing mode specifies that the operand is located at the address specified in the instruction. The indirect addressing mode specifies that the operand is located at the address stored in the location specified in the instruction. The indexed addressing mode specifies that the operand is located at the address computed by adding the contents of a register to the address specified in the instruction.

title: Red Bird Records
text: Red Bird Records was an American record label founded in 1929 by J. Mayo Williams. Based in Richmond, Indiana, the label specialized in hillbilly and old-time music. Artists such as the Carter Family, Jimmie Rodgers, and Bill Monroe recorded for Red Bird. The label folded in 1933 during the Great Depression, but its recordings have been reissued on numerous compilations. Red Bird Records played a significant role in the development and popularization of country music.

title: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band
text: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band is the eighth studio album by the English rock band the Beatles, released in 1967. It is regarded as one of the greatest and most influential albums of all time. The album abandoned the Beatles' earlier pop style for a more experimental and sophisticated sound, incorporating elements of psychedelic rock, Indian classical music, and avant-garde music. The album's lyrics are often surreal and nonsensical, but they also explore themes of love, loss, and the search for meaning in life. Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band was a commercial and critical success, and it helped to solidify the Beatles' status as one of the most important and innovative bands in history.

title: Mexico, Juniata County, Pennsylvania
text: Mexico is an unincorporated community in Juniata County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located along Pennsylvania Route 35 south of the borough of Port Royal. The community was named for the country of Mexico by early settlers. The Mexico post office, established in 1826, closed in 1993. The community is home to Mexico Presbyterian Church, which was organized in 1837.

title: Cermet
text: Cermets, a class of composite materials, comprise a combination of ceramic and metallic components. These materials exhibit desirable attributes of both constituents, including high hardness and strength from the ceramic phase, combined with the toughness and thermal conductivity of the metallic phase. Cermets find applications in various industries due to their unique combination of properties, such as cutting tools, wear-resistant coatings, and high-temperature components. Prominent examples include titanium carbide-based cermets utilized in cutting tools and tungsten carbide-cobalt cermets employed in wear-resistant applications.

title: Spenser (character)
text: Spenser is a fictional private investigator created by author Robert B. Parker. Introduced in the 1973 novel "The Godwulf Manuscript," Spenser is a former Boston police detective who left the force after being framed for a crime he didn't commit. He is known for his quick wit, martial arts skills, and unwavering sense of justice. Spenser typically works alone but often collaborates with his friend and legal counsel, Susan Silverman. The character has appeared in over 40 novels and has been portrayed in several television adaptations.

title: Kooskia, Idaho
text: Kooskia, Idaho, is a city in Idaho County. It is the county seat of and is located on the Clearwater River, approximately 80 miles (130 km) southeast of Lewiston. The population was 606 at the 2010 census. Kooskia is home to the Kooskia National Fish Hatchery, which raises Chinook salmon and steelhead trout. The city is also a popular destination for fishing, rafting, and camping.

title: Toronto
text: Toronto, the provincial capital of Ontario, is the most populous city in Canada. With a metropolitan population of over 6 million, it is also the fourth most populous city in North America. Located on the northwestern shore of Lake Ontario, Toronto is a major economic, cultural, and tourist center. The city is home to the Toronto Stock Exchange, the largest stock exchange in Canada, and is a major center for banking, finance, and insurance. Toronto is also a major cultural center, with a vibrant arts scene and a large number of museums and theaters. The city is also a popular tourist destination, with attractions such as the CN Tower, the Hockey Hall of Fame, and the Royal Ontario Museum.

title: Giambattista della Porta
text: Giambattista della Porta (1535–1615) was an Italian polymath who made substantial contributions to diverse fields, including physics, astronomy, cryptography, alchemy, and even agriculture. He is best known for his work on optics, where he developed the concept of the camera obscura and advocated the use of lenses for correcting visual defects. Porta's scientific writings were instrumental in the development of experimental science and the scientific revolution.

title: File (tool)
text: A file is a tool used to shape and smooth metal, wood, or other materials. There are many different types of files, each designed for a specific purpose. Files are typically made from hardened steel, and they have a series of sharp teeth that cut into the material being worked. The teeth are usually arranged in a crosshatch pattern, which helps to create a smooth surface. Files are used in a variety of trades, including metalworking, woodworking, and jewelry making.

title: Universal Esperanto Association
text: The Universal Esperanto Association (UEA) is the world's largest organization dedicated to promoting the Esperanto language. Founded in 1908, UEA has members in over 120 countries and works to foster the use of Esperanto for communication, education, and cultural exchange. The association organizes conferences, publishes books and magazines, and provides support for Esperanto teachers and learners. UEA is a non-profit organization and is recognized as an NGO by the United Nations. It is headquartered in Rotterdam, Netherlands.

title: Brazilian Carnival
text: Brazilian Carnival is an annual festival held before Lent and is considered the biggest carnival in the world with two million people per day on the streets of Rio de Janeiro. The first Carnival was held in 1921 on the city's Avenida Rio Branco. The festival features a parade of escolas de samba, which are samba schools with elaborate costumes and floats. The parade is judged by a panel of experts and the winning escola is awarded a trophy. The festival also includes street parties, concerts, and other events.

title: Fortepiano
text: The fortepiano, an 18th-century keyboard instrument, preceded the modern piano. Invented by Bartolomeo Cristofori in Florence around 1700, it featured a mechanism that allowed for both loud (forte) and soft (piano) sounds. The term "fortepiano" is derived from the Italian words meaning "loud" and "soft". Unlike the harpsichord, which produced sound by plucking strings, the fortepiano used hammers to strike the strings. This hammer-action mechanism gave it a wider dynamic range and expressive capabilities. The fortepiano quickly gained popularity, becoming the dominant keyboard instrument in Europe by the early 19th century.

title: Murder of Scott Amedure
text: The murder of Scott Amedure, a gay teenager from Rotterdam, New York, occurred on March 17, 2013. He was sexually assaulted and beaten to death by James Burns, John Riccardi, and Kyle Shilling. All three individuals were convicted of murder and other charges. Burns was sentenced to life without parole, while Riccardi and Shilling received sentences of 25 years to life. The case gained national attention and sparked discussions about hate crimes and the need for increased acceptance of LGBTQ+ youth. The murder also led to the passage of Scott's Law in New York State, which increased penalties for hate crimes motivated by sexual orientation or gender identity.

title: Football chant
text: A football chant is a repetitive song sung by fans at football matches. Chants are often used to show support for the team, to mock the opposition, or to create a sense of atmosphere. They can be simple or complex, and often involve call-and-response elements. Some chants are traditional and have been sung for many years, while others are more recent. Chants can be sung a cappella or accompanied by drums or other instruments.

title: Williams Creek, Indiana
text: Williams Creek, Indiana, is an unincorporated community in Owen County, Indiana, United States. As of 2020, its population was 202. The community is located along State Road 115 and is home to the Williams Creek Covered Bridge, one of the longest remaining all-wooden covered bridges in the United States. Williams Creek was founded in 1832 by Jonathan Williams and was originally known as "Williamsport." It is located in eastern Owen County, approximately 10 miles east of Spencer, the county seat.

title: Godwin, Earl of Wessex
text: Godwin, Earl of Wessex (c. 1001-1053), was a powerful Anglo-Saxon nobleman who played a prominent role in the political landscape of 11th-century England. He rose to prominence during the reign of Edward the Confessor, his brother-in-law, and served as Earl of Wessex from 1020 until his death. Godwin's influence extended beyond his own earldom, and he became one of the most powerful men in England. His son, Harold Godwinson, succeeded him as Earl of Wessex and later became King of England in 1066. Godwin's family, known as the House of Godwin, continued to play a significant role in English history for several generations.

title: Lemur
text: Lemurs are primates that are native to the island of Madagascar. They are known for their large, expressive eyes and their long, bushy tails. Lemurs are social animals that live in groups of up to 100 individuals. They are primarily herbivorous, feeding on fruits, leaves, and flowers. Lemurs are threatened by habitat loss and hunting, and several species are considered endangered. Conservation efforts are underway to protect these unique and fascinating animals.

title: Janet Dean
text: Janet Dean (born 1955) is an American artist known for her large-scale public art installations and sculptures. Her work often explores themes of social justice, environmentalism, and the relationship between humans and nature. Dean has created numerous notable works, including the "Light Up the Night" project in New York City and the "Water is Life" sculpture at the National Museum of the American Indian in Washington, D.C. Her work has been widely exhibited and is held in the collections of major museums and institutions around the world.

title: Gilbert and Sullivan
text: Gilbert and Sullivan were a celebrated English theatrical partnership during the Victorian era. W. S. Gilbert wrote the librettos, and Sir Arthur Sullivan composed the music for 14 comic operas. Their works are known for their witty and satirical lyrics, memorable melodies, and clever plots. Gilbert and Sullivan's most famous operas include "H.M.S. Pinafore," "The Pirates of Penzance," and "The Mikado." Their operas continue to be performed and enjoyed by audiences worldwide.

title: Operation Northwoods
text: Operation Northwoods was a proposed false flag operation prepared by the Joint Chiefs of Staff of the United States in 1962. The plan called for a series of covert operations to create the impression of Cuban aggression against the United States, justifying a war against Cuba. The operations included plans to hijack American aircraft and sink ships, and to stage attacks on American military bases to trick the American public into supporting a war. Operation Northwoods was never approved by President John F. Kennedy, and was eventually scrapped.

title: Galatian language
text: The Galatian language was a Celtic language spoken in Galatia, a region in central Anatolia, Turkey. It is known from inscriptions and loanwords in Greek texts. The language was closely related to Gaulish and was likely brought to Anatolia by Celtic tribes who settled there in the 3rd century BC. The Galatian language gradually declined in use during the Roman period and eventually died out in the 4th century AD.

title: Start-stop system
text: A start-stop system is a fuel-saving technology used in vehicles with internal combustion engines. It automatically shuts off the engine when the vehicle is stationary, such as at traffic lights or in traffic jams, and restarts it when the driver presses the accelerator pedal. Start-stop systems can reduce fuel consumption by up to 5% in urban driving conditions, and they also help to reduce emissions. The technology is particularly beneficial in vehicles that spend a lot of time in stop-and-go traffic.

title: Ventura Freeway
text: The Ventura Freeway is a 50-mile (80 km) stretch of U.S. Route 101 in Southern California, running from Los Angeles County to Ventura County. It is one of the busiest freeways in the region, carrying over 300,000 vehicles per day. The freeway was built in the 1950s and 1960s and has undergone several expansions and improvements over the years. It is a major north-south artery for commuters, tourists, and businesses alike. The freeway has been featured in numerous films and television shows, including "Thelma & Louise" and "CSI: Miami."

title: Batasuna
text: Batasuna (English: Unity) was a Basque nationalist and separatist political party in the Basque Country. Founded in 1978, it was the successor to the banned party Herri Batasuna and became part of the broader Abertzale left. Batasuna supported the armed campaign of the separatist militant organization ETA until 2009 when it declared a ceasefire. In 2003, Batasuna was declared illegal by the Spanish Supreme Court for its links to ETA, and it was dissolved in 2008.

title: Joh Bjelke-Petersen
text: Joh Bjelke-Petersen (1911-2005) was a prominent Australian politician who served as the 36th Premier of Queensland for 19 years, from 1968 to 1987. A member of the National Party, he is known for his conservative policies and his strong stance on law and order. During his premiership, Queensland experienced significant economic growth and infrastructure development, though his government also faced criticism for its authoritarian tendencies and suppression of dissent.

title: San Francisco City Hall
text: San Francisco City Hall is the seat of government for the City and County of San Francisco, California. Completed in 1915, it is an example of Beaux-Arts architecture and is one of the most iconic buildings in San Francisco. The building is topped by a 307-foot (93 m) dome and features a rotunda with a 90-foot (27 m) ceiling. City Hall is open to the public and offers tours of the building and its facilities. It is also a popular destination for weddings and other special events.

title: Monticello, Louisiana
text: Monticello is a town in East Carroll Parish, Louisiana, United States. The population was 4,822 at the 2020 census. Monticello was founded in 1822 by a group of settlers from Kentucky. The town was named after Monticello, the home of Thomas Jefferson. Monticello is located on the banks of the Mississippi River. The town is a major center for agriculture and forestry. Monticello is also home to the University of Louisiana at Monroe.

title: Marina Beach
text: Marina Beach, also known as 'Marina Sands', is a popular urban beach in Chennai, India. It stretches for about 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) along the Bay of Bengal. The beach is renowned for its golden sands, clear waters, and scenic views. It is a popular spot for swimming, sunbathing, and strolling. Marina Beach is also home to several landmarks, including the Anna Memorial, the MGR Memorial, and the Vivekananda House. The beach is well-maintained and provides various amenities for visitors, making it a popular destination for locals and tourists alike.

title: Howard Zinn
text: Howard Zinn (1922-2010) was an American historian, political scientist, and social activist. He is best known for his groundbreaking work "A People's History of the United States" (1980), which challenged traditional historical narratives and explored the experiences of marginalized groups. Zinn's writings and activism were deeply influenced by his participation in the civil rights and anti-Vietnam War movements. He remained a vocal critic of US foreign policy and economic inequality throughout his life.

title: Organic certification
text: Organic certification is a process by which agricultural products are certified to meet specific standards of environmentally friendly production. These standards typically include the use of natural fertilizers and pest control, as well as the avoidance of synthetic chemicals and genetically modified organisms (GMOs). Organic certification is designed to assure consumers that the food they are purchasing has been produced in a sustainable and ethical manner. The requirements for organic certification vary from country to country, but they typically include the following: The use of natural fertilizers and pest control The avoidance of synthetic chemicals and GMOs Crop rotation Soil management Livestock welfare

title: Mount Lycabettus
text: Mount Lycabettus is a prominent limestone hill in Athens, Greece. At 277 meters (909 feet) above sea level, it offers panoramic views of the city and the surrounding Attica region. Lycabettus is believed to have been formed by a large piece of limestone that broke away from Mount Penteli during the uplift of the Attica peninsula. The hill is home to the Lycabettus Hill Theater, a popular open-air theater that hosts concerts and performances during the summer months. A winding road leads to the summit of Mount Lycabettus, where visitors can also reach the chapel of Saint George and a small café.

title: IV Corps (United Kingdom)
text: IV Corps was an Army Corps of the British Army, formed in 1902. It served in the Second Boer War, the First World War, and the Second World War. In the Second Boer War, the corps fought at the Battle of Paardeberg and the Battle of Poplar Grove. In the First World War, the corps fought at the Battle of the Somme and the Battle of Passchendaele. In the Second World War, the corps fought in the Battle of France and the Battle of Normandy. It was disbanded in 1945.

title: Comitology
text: Comitology is a system of committees that assist the European Commission in implementing and enforcing European Union (EU) legislation. These committees are composed of representatives from the EU member states and are chaired by a Commission official. Comitology committees provide a forum for the member states to discuss and vote on proposed measures from the Commission. The Commission must take into account the opinions of the committees before adopting final measures. Comitology is an essential part of the EU's decision-making process, as it ensures that the member states have a voice in the implementation of EU law.

title: Clyde F.C.
text: Clyde Football Club is a Scottish professional football club based in the town of Cumbernauld, North Lanarkshire. Formed in 1877, the club competes in the Scottish League One, the third tier of the Scottish football league system. Clyde has won the Scottish Cup twice, in 1939 and 1955. The club's home ground is Broadwood Stadium, which it shares with Cumbernauld Colts. Clyde is known by the nickname "The Bully Wee", which is a Scots term of endearment.

title: L.A. Confidential (film)
text: L.A. Confidential is a 1997 American neo-noir crime thriller film directed by Curtis Hanson and starring Kevin Spacey, Russell Crowe, Guy Pearce, Kim Basinger, Danny DeVito, and James Cromwell. The film is based on the 1990 novel of the same name by James Ellroy. Set in Los Angeles in 1953, the film follows three LAPD officers who investigate the unsolved murder of a call girl and her pimp, which is linked to corruption within the department.

title: Jack Ruby
text: Jack Ruby, born Jacob Leon Rubenstein, was an American nightclub owner best known for fatally shooting Lee Harvey Oswald, the assassin of U.S. President John F. Kennedy. Ruby's motive for the killing remains unclear, but it is believed he may have been driven by a desire for publicity, sympathy, or both. Ruby was convicted of murder and sentenced to death, but died in prison in 1967 from lung cancer before his appeals could be exhausted. His death has been the subject of numerous conspiracy theories.

title: Cataño, Puerto Rico

title: EMusic
text: eMusic is a digital music store and streaming service that offers millions of songs in various genres. Founded in 1998, it was one of the first music download services. title: Donald M. Payne
text: Donald Milford Payne (December 17, 1934 – March 6, 2012) was an American politician who served as a U.S. Representative from New Jersey for 12 terms from 1989 until his death in 2012. title: Jim Higgins (Irish politician)
text: Jim Higgins (born 20 May 1947) is an Irish Fine Gael politician. He has served as a Teachta Dála (TD) for the Carlow–Kilkenny constituency since 2011. Higgins was first elected to the Dáil in 2011 as a member for the Carlow–Kilkenny constituency. He was re-elected in 2016 and 2020. title: Arithmetic mean
text: The arithmetic mean, also known as the average, is the sum of a set of numbers divided by the number of numbers in the set. It is a measure of the central tendency of a set of data. The arithmetic mean is often used to summarize a set of data and to compare different sets of data. For example, the arithmetic mean of the set of numbers {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} is 3.

title: Aberration of light
text: Aberration of light is an apparent change in the direction of a light source due to the relative motion between the source and observer. This phenomenon is caused by the finite speed of light, which means that light takes time to travel from one point to another. As a result, when an observer is moving relative to a light source, the light will appear to come from a slightly different direction than it actually does. The amount of aberration depends on the relative speed between the source and observer.

title: Waterford Harbour
text: Waterford Harbour, also known as Loch Da Chaoch, is a natural harbour located in the south-east of Ireland, in the county of Waterford. The harbour is formed by the confluence of three rivers: the Suir, the Nore, and the Barrow. Waterford Harbour is a significant commercial port and fishing harbour, and it also supports a variety of recreational activities, such as sailing, kayaking, and fishing.

title: 1960s
text: The 1960s, also commonly referred to as the "Swinging Sixties," was a decade of significant social and cultural change. The decade saw the rise of counterculture movements, such as the hippie movement, and the emergence of the civil rights movement. title: Nescopeck, Pennsylvania

title: Kensington, Minnesota

title: Uppsala General Catalogue
text: The Uppsala General Catalogue (UGC) is a catalogue of 129,211 galaxies and groups of galaxies that is based on data from the Uppsala Observatory's Third Catalogue of Galaxies. The catalogue was published in 1973 by astronomers Per Olof Lindblad and Bertil Lindblad. The UGC contains information on the positions, magnitudes, sizes, and morphological types of the galaxies. It is one of the most comprehensive and widely used catalogues of galaxies. The data in the UGC have been used to study a wide range of topics, including the large-scale structure of the universe.

title: Lehigh, Iowa
text: Lehigh is a city in Webster County, Iowa, United States. The population was 414 at the 2020 census, a decline from the 440 population in 2000. title: Broad Street Line
text: The Broad Street Line is a subway line in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, operated by the Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority (SEPTA). title: Ovarian cancer
text: Ovarian cancer is a type of cancer that starts in the ovaries, two small organs located on either side of the uterus in women. It is the most common type of gynecological cancer worldwide, affecting approximately one in every 70 women. The majority of cases occur in women over the age of 50, but it can also affect younger women. The symptoms of ovarian cancer can be vague and often go unnoticed until the cancer has spread, making it difficult to diagnose early. Common symptoms include bloating, pelvic or abdominal pain, difficulty eating or feeling full quickly, and frequent urination.

title: Siletz Reservation
text: The Siletz Reservation is a federally recognized Indian reservation in the U.S. state of Oregon. title: Mark Lanegan
text: Mark Lanegan (November 25, 1964 – February 22, 2022) was an American singer, songwriter, and musician. He was known for his distinctive baritone voice and his dark and introspective lyrics. title: Sardine v
text: Sardine v is a slang term for the McDonnell Douglas F-15 Eagle, a twin-engine, all-weather tactical fighter aircraft developed in the United States. title: Contradiction
text: Contradiction, in logic and rhetoric, is a statement that asserts the opposite of another statement. Contradictions are often used to create a paradox, or a statement that seems contradictory but may actually be true. For example, the statement "This statement is false" is a contradiction. If the statement is true, then it must be false, and if it is false, then it must be true. This paradox can be resolved by considering the statement in a different way. For example, the statement can be interpreted as saying "This statement is not true." In this case, the statement is true, because it is not true.

title: Non-measurable set
text: A non-measurable set is a set of real numbers that cannot be assigned a Lebesgue measure. The existence of non-measurable sets was first established by Giuseppe Vitali in 1905. Vitali's construction is based on the well-ordering of the real numbers, which allows him to define a set of real numbers that has no smallest element. The Vitali set is an example of a non-measurable set.

title: Danby, Vermont

title: Self-driving car
text: Self-driving cars, also known as autonomous vehicles, are vehicles that are capable of driving themselves without human input. Self-driving cars have the potential to make transportation safer, more efficient, and more accessible. They could also help to reduce traffic congestion and pollution. However, there are still some challenges that need to be overcome before self-driving cars can become commonplace. These challenges include developing reliable and safe software, addressing regulatory issues, and ensuring that self-driving cars are affordable for consumers.

title: Yuba City, California

title: Present Laughter
text: Present Laughter is a three-act play by Noël Coward. It was first staged in 1942 and has been revived several times, most recently in 2019. title: Alfred Matthew Hubbard
text: Alfred Matthew Hubbard (1839-1915) was an American architect and writer. title: Edward Bernays
text: Edward Bernays (November 22, 1891–March 9, 1995) was an Austrian-American public relations and propaganda specialist. title: Kavitrayam
text: Kavitrayam, meaning "trio of poets," refers to three eminent Marathi poets of the 17th century: Moropant, Vaman Pandit, and Mahipati. title: Penrose stairs
text: Penrose stairs are an impossible staircase that appears to continually ascend or descend, forming a loop. Penrose stairs are often depicted as a series of steps that turn 90 degrees at each corner, creating a continuous loop. However, it is impossible to actually construct such a staircase, as it would violate the laws of physics.

title: Griffith, Indiana

title: Villain
text: A villain is a character in a story or drama who opposes the protagonist. Villains may be motivated by a variety of factors, including greed, power, revenge, or a desire to cause chaos. title: Kensington, California

title: Quaternary
text: The Quaternary is the current and most recent geological period. It began 2.58 million years ago and continues to the present. The Quaternary is characterized by significant climatic fluctuations, particularly the cyclical occurrence of glacial and interglacial periods. These fluctuations have had a profound impact on the Earth's ecosystems and human evolution. The Quaternary is further divided into two epochs: the Pleistocene and the Holocene. The Pleistocene, which began around 2.58 million years ago, was marked by repeated periods of glaciation and deglaciation. The Holocene, which began around 11,700 years ago, has been a relatively stable period with a warm climate and relatively minor climatic fluctuations.

title: Metropolitan Borough of Paddington
text: The Metropolitan Borough of Paddington was a metropolitan borough in London, England, from 1900 to 1965. It was created from the former parish of Paddington, and was one of the 28 metropolitan boroughs that constituted the County of London. The borough was named after the Paddington Canal, which in turn was named after the village of Paddington. The borough was situated in the west of London, and covered an area of 1,356 acres. The population of the borough was 140,185 in 1901, and had risen to 158,920 by 1961. The borough was abolished in 1965, and its area was transferred to the new London Borough of Westminster.

title: Stephen W. Kearny

title: Iona College (New York)

title: Symbel
text: Symbel, also known as the feast of winter solstice, was a communal feast held in ancient Germanic societies, particularly among the Anglo-Saxons and Norsemen. It marked the end of the old year and the beginning of the new, and was a time for feasting, drinking, and storytelling. The feast was presided over by a leader or chieftain, who would offer a toast to the gods and ancestors. Animals were sacrificed and their flesh was eaten, while mead and ale were consumed in great quantities. Entertainment included music, dancing, and poetry recitals. Symbel was a significant social and religious event that strengthened community bonds and honored Germanic traditions.

title: Austin Osman Spare
text: Austin Osman Spare (1886-1956) was an English artist, writer, and occultist. Born in London, Spare developed an early interest in art and the occult. Spare also wrote several books on magic and the occult, including "The Book of Pleasure" (1913) and "The Focus of Life" (1921). He was a controversial figure in his lifetime, but his work has since gained recognition for its originality and influence on subsequent generations of artists and occultists.

title: Chippewa County, Michigan

title: Cullompton

title: Sexual dimorphism
text: Sexual dimorphism, in biology, refers to the differences in physical or behavioral characteristics between males and females of the same species. These differences can range from subtle variations in size and shape to striking disparities in coloration, ornamentation, and behavior. Examples of sexual dimorphism can be seen throughout the animal kingdom. Male lions, for instance, have manes that give them a distinctive appearance from females. Peacock males exhibit elaborate tail feathers used in courtship displays. In humans, men tend to be taller and heavier than women, with broader shoulders and narrower hips.

title: Entity–relationship model
text: The entity-relationship model (ERM) is a data modeling technique that is used to create a graphical representation of the entities and relationships within a system. ERMs are often used to design databases, but they can also be used to create other types of models, such as business process models and object-oriented models. An ERM consists of two main components: entities and relationships. Entities represent the objects in the system, such as customers, products, and orders. Relationships represent the connections between entities, such as the relationship between a customer and an order. ERMs are a powerful tool for visualizing and understanding the structure of a system. They can be used to identify potential problems in a system, such as data redundancies and inconsistencies. ERMs can also be used to communicate the structure of a system to other stakeholders, such as developers and users.

title: Nirvana
text: Nirvana, an American rock band formed in Aberdeen, Washington, in 1987, is considered one of the most influential and important rock bands of all time. title: Rex Carver
text: Rex Carver was an American actor, known for his roles in "The Big Sleep" (1946), "Sorry, Wrong Number" (1948), and "The Violent Men" (1955). title: Larry Flynt

title: Gilbertville, Iowa

title: Óðr

title: Trading Spaces

title: Dallas Cowboys

title: Teddy Wilson

title: Woodcrest, California

title: Orchestra of the Eighteenth Century
text: The Orchestra of the Eighteenth Century is a period instrument ensemble founded in 1986 by the violinist and conductor Frans Brüggen. The orchestra specializes in performing music from the 18th century on period instruments, using historically informed performance practices. The orchestra has toured extensively throughout Europe, North America, and Asia, and has released over 100 recordings. It is considered one of the leading period instrument ensembles in the world.

title: Burlington, Ontario
text: Burlington is a city in the Regional Municipality of Halton, Ontario, Canada. Located on Lake Ontario, it is adjacent to Hamilton to the west and Oakville to the east. Burlington is the seat of Halton County and the fourth-largest municipality in the Greater Toronto Area. As of the 2021 census, Burlington had a population of 233,298, and a population density of 1,027.5/km2. The city is home to the Royal Botanical Gardens, Canada's largest botanical garden, and is known for its diverse cultural scene and vibrant downtown core.

title: Lake Park, Florida
text: Lake Park is a town in Palm Beach County, Florida, United States. The population was 8,754 at the 2010 census. Lake Park is a suburban community located on the shores of the Intracoastal Waterway, just north of the city of Palm Beach Gardens. The town is home to several parks and recreation areas, including Lake Park Beach, which offers swimming, fishing, and boating opportunities. Lake Park is also home to the North County Aquatic Complex, which features a 50-meter competition pool, a diving pool, and a water park.

title: Syria Accountability Act
text: The Syria Accountability Act is a United States federal law that was enacted on December 18, 2003. The Act imposes sanctions on Syria for its support of terrorism, its development of weapons of mass destruction, and its human rights abuses. The Act also authorizes the President to provide assistance to groups opposed to the Syrian government. The Syria Accountability Act has been criticized by some for being too lenient on Syria, while others have argued that it is too harsh.

title: Tea with Mussolini
text: "Tea with Mussolini" is a 1999 historical drama film directed by Franco Zeffirelli. Set in Florence, Italy, during World War II, it follows a group of British women who form an unexpected bond with a group of Italian women. The film stars Judi Dench, Maggie Smith, Joan Plowright, and Cher. It explores themes of friendship, love, and resilience in the face of adversity. "Tea with Mussolini" was a critical and commercial success, receiving an Academy Award nomination for Best Original Score.

title: Pigment
text: A pigment is a substance that imparts color to a material. Pigments are found in nature and can be extracted from minerals, plants, or animals. They can also be synthesized artificially. Pigments are used in a wide variety of applications, including paints, inks, dyes, cosmetics, and plastics. The color of a pigment is determined by its chemical composition and crystal structure. The size and shape of the pigment particles also affect its color. Pigments can be classified into two main types: organic and inorganic. Organic pigments are derived from plants or animals, while inorganic pigments are derived from minerals.

title: Niger
text: Niger, officially the Republic of Niger, is a landlocked country in West Africa. It is bordered by Libya to the northeast, Chad to the east, Nigeria and Benin to the south, Burkina Faso and Mali to the west, and Algeria to the northwest. Niger covers an area of 1,267,000 square kilometers (489,000 square miles), making it the largest country in West Africa. The country's population is estimated to be 22.3 million, with an annual growth rate of 3.3%. The capital and largest city is Niamey.

title: Surat Thani
text: Surat Thani is a province in southern Thailand, on the western shore of the Gulf of Thailand. Its neighboring provinces are (from north clockwise) Prachuap Khiri Khan, Phetchaburi, Nakhon Pathom, Ratchaburi, Samut Songkhram, Samut Sakhon, and Chumphon. The province is also home to the Khao Sok National Park, one of the oldest rainforests in the world. The park is home to a variety of plant and animal life, including elephants, tigers, and gibbons. Surat Thani is also a popular tourist destination, with many beautiful beaches and islands.

title: Chuluota, Florida
text: Chuluota is a town in Seminole County, Florida, United States. The population was 1,079 at the 2010 census. Chuluota is located on the southern shore of Lake Harney and is bordered by the cities of Oviedo to the west and Geneva to the east. The town was named after the Timucua Native American word for "sweet water". Chuluota is home to the Central Florida Railroad Museum, which features a collection of historic locomotives and rail cars.

title: Haven Township, Sherburne County, Minnesota
text: Haven Township is a township in Sherburne County, Minnesota, United States. The population was 1,093 at the 2010 census. Haven Township was organized in 1858. The township was named after Haven, Maine, the former home of a group of settlers. The township is located in the northwestern part of Sherburne County and is bordered by the Mississippi River to the west. The township is home to the Haven Resort and Spa.

title: Anti-Confederation Party
text: The Anti-Confederation Party was a political party in Canada that opposed the Canadian Confederation. The party was formed in 1864 by George Brown, who believed that Confederation would give too much power to the central government and would harm the interests of Ontario. The party won a number of seats in the Canadian House of Commons, but it was never able to form a government. The party disbanded in 1867, after Confederation was enacted.

title: Von Neumann universe
text: The von Neumann universe, named after mathematician John von Neumann, is a theoretical construct in cosmology that describes a physically possible universe that is infinite in both time and space. It is based on the assumption that the universe is homogeneous and isotropic, meaning that it has no preferred direction or location. The von Neumann universe is a hypothetical model that has been used to study the evolution of the universe and the formation of galaxies and stars. It is an important concept in cosmology, as it provides a framework for understanding the large-scale structure of the universe.

title: Edward Telfair
text: Edward Telfair (1735–1807) was an American merchant, planter, politician, and soldier. He was born in Scotland and emigrated to Virginia before settling in Georgia. During the American Revolution, Telfair commanded the Georgia militia at the Battle of Savannah. He later served as governor of Georgia from 1786 to 1787. Telfair was a signer of the Articles of Confederation and the United States Constitution. He owned several plantations and was a prominent slaveholder.

title: Proplyd
text: Proplyd is a type of astronomical object consisting of a dense clump of gas and dust that surrounds a newly formed star. The term "proplyd" is derived from the Greek words "pro" (before) and "plidene" (gate), referring to their location in front of the bright rims of H II regions, which are ionized by the radiation from the central star. Proplyds are often found in groups or clusters, and they can have a variety of shapes and sizes. They are typically a few hundred thousand years old and are thought to be an early stage in the evolution of stars.

title: RMS Olympic
text: RMS Olympic was the lead ship of the Olympic-class ocean liners of the White Star Line. She was the sister ship to RMS Titanic and HMHS Britannic. Olympic was built by Harland and Wolff in Belfast, Ireland, and launched on October 20, 1910. She was the largest ship afloat at the time of her completion. Olympic served as a transatlantic passenger liner from 1911 to 1935. During World War I, she was converted into a troop ship. After the war, she returned to passenger service, but her career was marred by several incidents, including a collision with HMS Hawke in 1911 and a fire in 1924. Olympic was retired from service in 1935 and scrapped in 1937.

title: Super Mario World
text: Super Mario World is a critically acclaimed side-scrolling platformer video game developed and published by Nintendo for the Super Nintendo Entertainment System (SNES). It is the first game in the Super Mario series to feature Yoshi as a playable character and marks the series debut of several recurring power-ups, enemies, and level types. Released in 1990, Super Mario World was praised for its colorful graphics, innovative gameplay, and memorable music. It became one of the best-selling games on the SNES, with over 20 million copies sold worldwide. The game has been re-released several times on various Nintendo platforms, including the Super Nintendo Classic Edition and Nintendo Switch Online.

title: Thomas W. Lamont
text: Thomas William Lamont (September 30, 1870 – February 2, 1948) was an American banker and philanthropist who served as a partner in J.P. Morgan & Co. from 1910 to 1943. He was a prominent figure in the financial world and played a significant role in shaping American economic policy during the early 20th century. Lamont was known for his involvement in international finance and his support for cultural institutions. He served as chairman of the board of trustees of Harvard University and was a major benefactor of the Metropolitan Opera and the Museum of Modern Art.

title: University of the West of England, Bristol
text: The University of the West of England, Bristol (UWE Bristol) is a public research university located in the city of Bristol, England. Founded as the Merchant Venturers' Technical College in 1856, it became a university in 1992. UWE Bristol has five academic faculties: Arts, Creative Industries and Education; Business and Law; Environment and Technology; Health and Applied Sciences; and Social Sciences and Humanities. The university has a number of campuses around Bristol, including the main campus at Frenchay.

title: Stichomythia
text: Stichomythia is a type of dialogue in drama where characters speak in alternating single lines, often creating a rapid-fire exchange. This technique originated in Greek tragedy and was later adopted by playwrights in other cultures. Stichomythia can heighten tension, create a sense of urgency, or provide comedic effect. Notable examples include the opening scene of Sophocles' "Oedipus Rex" and the famous balcony scene in Shakespeare's "Romeo and Juliet."

title: Parmelee, South Dakota
text: Parmelee is a town in Lyman County, South Dakota, United States. The population was 49 at the 2020 census. Parmelee was laid out in 1907, and named for Francis D. Parmelee, a railroad official. The town is located on the White River, and the economy is based on agriculture and tourism. Parmelee is home to the Lyman County Historical Society Museum, which houses exhibits on the history of the county and the town.

title: Sparta Township, Crawford County, Pennsylvania
text: Sparta Township is a township in Crawford County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 2,305 at the 2020 census. Sparta Township was founded in 1824 and is named after Sparta, Greece. The township is located in the northwestern corner of Crawford County and is bordered by Erie County to the north, Warren County to the east, and Mercer County to the south. The main industries in Sparta Township are agriculture and manufacturing. The township is home to several churches, schools, and businesses.

title: LaTanya Richardson
text: LaTanya Richardson Jackson (born October 21, 1949) is an American actress, director, and producer. She is best known for her roles in the films "Fried Green Tomatoes" (1991), "Malcolm X" (1992), and "The Fighting Temptations" (2003), and the television series "Ally McBeal" (1997-2002). She has also directed several films and television shows, including "Tuskegee Airmen" (1995) and "The Trip to Bountiful" (2014). In 2021, she received the Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actress in a Play for her role in "A Soldier's Play."

title: Speed 2: Cruise Control
text: Speed 2: Cruise Control is a 1997 American action thriller film directed by Jan de Bont and starring Sandra Bullock, Jason Patric, Willem Dafoe, and Temuera Morrison. It is the sequel to the 1994 film Speed. The film follows Annie Porter (Bullock), a police officer who must stop a deranged computer hacker (Dafoe) from crashing a cruise ship into an oil tanker.

title: Chessboard
text: A chessboard is an 8×8 checkered gameboard used in the game of chess. Each square is called a cell, and the 64 cells are arranged in eight rows (called ranks) and eight columns (called files). The colors of the squares alternate between light and dark, forming an 8×8 grid. The chessboard is placed with a light square on the bottom-left corner. Each player starts the game with 16 pieces: one king, one queen, two rooks, two knights, two bishops, and eight pawns. The objective of the game is to checkmate the opponent's king, which occurs when the king is under immediate threat of capture (check) and cannot escape.

title: Thomas Coram Foundation for Children
text: The Thomas Coram Foundation for Children is a British charity established in 1739 by social reformer Thomas Coram. Its mission is to provide care and education for orphaned and abandoned children. Founded as the Foundling Hospital, it was the first institution in England to take in any abandoned child, regardless of background. Today, the Foundation continues to provide services to vulnerable children through residential care, fostering, adoption, and education programs. It is one of the largest and oldest charities in the UK, having helped over 100,000 children since its inception.

title: PGM-17 Thor
text: The PGM-17 Thor was an intermediate-range ballistic missile (IRBM) developed by the United States Air Force in the 1950s. It was designed to carry a nuclear warhead and was deployed in the United Kingdom and Italy. The Thor was a liquid-fueled missile with a range of about 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometers). It was launched from a fixed pad and was primarily intended to target the Soviet Union. The Thor was phased out of service in the late 1960s.

title: California Air Resources Board
text: The California Air Resources Board (CARB) is a state agency in California, United States, responsible for regulating air pollution. It is responsible for implementing state and federal environmental laws and regulations aimed at reducing air pollution from motor vehicles, fuels, and consumer products. CARB has set some of the nation's most stringent environmental regulations, including the state's greenhouse gas reduction goals and zero-emission vehicle mandates. It also works with other states and international organizations to address air pollution issues.

title: Brentwood, Pennsylvania
text: Brentwood is a borough in Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located 6 miles (9.7 km) southeast of downtown Pittsburgh, on the Monongahela River. As of the 2020 census, the borough population was 9,410. Brentwood is home to several parks, including Brentwood Park, which offers a playground, picnic areas, and a walking trail. The borough is also home to the Brentwood Library, which is part of the Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh system. Brentwood is served by the Brentwood Borough School District.

title: Dulé Hill
text: Dulé Hill is an American actor, dancer, and singer. He is best known for his roles as Charlie Young on The West Wing (2000–2006), Gus Gorman on Psych (2006–2014), and Alex Williams on Suits (2011–2019). Hill has also appeared in numerous films, including The Departed (2006), Holes (2003), and She's All That (1999). He has also performed on Broadway, starring in productions such as Stick Fly and After Midnight.

title: Grille (car)
text: Grille, in automotive terms, refers to the perforated opening at the front of a vehicle that allows air to enter the engine compartment for cooling. It not only serves a functional purpose but also contributes to the aesthetic design of the car. The grille's shape, size, and pattern can vary significantly depending on the make, model, and year of the vehicle. Some grilles feature intricate designs incorporating brand logos or other decorative elements, while others opt for a more understated look. The grille is an important component of a car's cooling system, ensuring an adequate supply of air to the radiator and engine. It helps dissipate heat and maintain optimal operating temperatures.

title: Gandy dancer
text: Gandy dancer, a term used in the United States, refers to railroad laborers who maintain railroad tracks. The term originated in the 1800s when Irish immigrants were primarily employed for this work. They would sing traditional Irish folk songs while working, and the term "gandy dancer" is thought to derive from the song "The Gander in the Praties." Gandy dancers used specialized tools such as picks, shovels, and crowbars to tamp down the track bed, replace ties, and maintain the rails. Their work was physically demanding and often dangerous, requiring them to work in all weather conditions.

title: Boeing CH-47 Chinook
text: The Boeing CH-47 Chinook is a heavy-lift, tandem-rotor helicopter designed and manufactured by Boeing Vertol for the U.S. Army. It is one of the longest-serving helicopters in the U.S. military and has been exported to over 20 countries. The Chinook is known for its durability and versatility, and has been used in a wide range of operations, including combat, medical evacuation, and disaster relief.
