text: Donald "Duck" Dunn (November 24, 1941 – May 13, 2012) was an American bassist, best known for his work with Booker T. & the M.G.'s and Otis Redding. Dunn's distinctive bass playing, characterized by its melodic, syncopated style, greatly influenced soul and R&B music. He was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1992 as a member of Booker T. & the M.G.'s.

title: St. Joseph, Louisiana
text: St. Joseph is a town in Tensas Parish, Louisiana, United States. It is located on the Mississippi River, approximately 30 miles (48 km) north of Natchez, Mississippi, and 40 miles (64 km) south of Vicksburg, Mississippi. The town was founded in 1809 by a group of German immigrants led by Joseph Vidal. St. Joseph is the parish seat of Tensas Parish. As of the 2010 census, the town had a population of 1,175. The town's economy is based on agriculture, with soybeans and cotton being the primary crops. St. Joseph is also home to a number of historical landmarks, including the St. Joseph Catholic Church, which was built in 1853, and the Tensas Parish Courthouse, which was built in 1836.

title: Angeren
text: Angeren is a small village in the Dutch province of Gelderland. It is located in the municipality of Lingewaard, about 8 km (5 mi) west of Nijmegen. Angeren was first mentioned in 893 as "Anghrina". The village has a rich history and was once an important trading center. Today, Angeren is a peaceful village with a population of around 1,500 people. The village is home to a number of historical buildings, including the 12th-century St. Martin's Church.

title: Michael Alig
text: Michael Alig (1966–2020) was an American club kid and promoter who was convicted of the murder of Andre "Angel" Melendez in 1996. Alig was a prominent figure in the New York City club scene in the early 1990s and was known for his flamboyant style and excessive drug use. He was convicted of second-degree murder and sentenced to 10 to 20 years in prison. He was released in 2014 and died of a suspected drug overdose in 2020.

title: Carousel (musical)
text: "Carousel" is a musical with a book and lyrics by Oscar Hammerstein II and music by Richard Rodgers. It is based on the 1909 play "Liliom" by Ferenc Molnár. The story follows Billy Bigelow, a carnival barker who falls in love with Julie Jordan, a millworker. Despite their love for each other, Billy's temper and inability to hold a steady job lead to tragedy. After his death, he is given a chance to return to earth and make things right. "Carousel" premiered on Broadway in 1945 and was a critical and commercial success. It has since been revived several times and has been adapted into a film and a television series.

title: Alba, Pennsylvania
text: Alba is an unincorporated community in Bradford County, Pennsylvania, United States. It is located in northern Pennsylvania, near the border with New York. The community is situated on the banks of the Susquehanna River and is home to a small population of around 100 people. Alba is a quiet and peaceful community with a rich history. It was founded in the early 19th century and was once a thriving lumbering town. Today, Alba is a popular destination for fishing, camping, and other outdoor activities.

title: Ludwig Wittgenstein
text: Ludwig Wittgenstein (/ˈvɪtɡənʃtaɪn/; 26 April 1889 – 29 April 1951) was an Austrian-British philosopher who worked primarily in logic, the philosophy of language, and the philosophy of mind. He is widely considered one of the most important philosophers of the 20th century. Wittgenstein's work has had a profound influence on many areas of philosophy, including the philosophy of mathematics, the philosophy of science, and the philosophy of religion.

title: Fundamental Laws of England
text: The Fundamental Laws of England are a series of laws that form the constitutional basis of the English legal system. They are not codified in a single document, but are instead found in a variety of statutes, common law cases, and legal treatises. The most important of these laws include the Magna Carta (1215), the Petition of Right (1628), the Bill of Rights (1689), and the Act of Settlement (1701). These laws establish the principles of limited government, due process of law, and the supremacy of Parliament. They have been instrumental in shaping the development of constitutional law throughout the world.

title: Kim Beazley
text: Kim Christian Beazley AC (born 14 December 1948) is an Australian politician who served as the 38th Governor of Western Australia from 2018 to 2022. He was a senior minister in the Hawke and Keating Governments, serving as Minister for Employment and Industrial Relations from 1984 to 1990, Minister for Transport and Communications from 1990 to 1991, and Minister for Finance from 1991 to 1993. He was Leader of the Opposition from 1996 to 2001 and 2005 to 2006.

title: L'Île-Rousse
text: L'Île-Rousse is a commune in the Haute-Corse department of France on the island of Corsica. It is located on the northwest coast of the island, approximately 25 kilometers southeast of Calvi. The commune has a population of around 3,000 people and is a popular tourist destination due to its beautiful beaches, clear waters, and historic town center. The town was founded in the 15th century by the Genoese and was once a major port. Today, it is a popular base for exploring the surrounding area, including the nearby Agriates Desert.

title: Allegheny Township, Cambria County, Pennsylvania
text: Allegheny Township is a township in Cambria County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 1,008 at the 2010 census. It is part of the Johnstown, Pennsylvania Metropolitan Statistical Area. The township was first settled in the early 1800s by German and Irish immigrants. The township was incorporated in 1840. The main industry in the township is agriculture. The township is also home to several tourist attractions, including the Allegheny Portage Railroad National Historic Site.

title: Messenger RNA
text: Messenger RNA (mRNA) is a type of RNA molecule that carries genetic information from DNA to the ribosomes, where proteins are synthesized. It is a single-stranded molecule, unlike DNA, which has two strands. mRNA molecules are transcribed from the DNA template and then undergo processing, including splicing and modification, before they can be translated into proteins. The sequence of mRNA codons specifies the sequence of amino acids in a protein.

title: Low Mass
text: Low Mass, also known as Private Mass, is a form of Catholic Mass that is celebrated without music, incense, or a homily. It is typically celebrated on weekdays, with the priest reciting the prayers and readings aloud. Low Mass is a more intimate and personal form of the Mass, allowing for greater focus and contemplation. Although it is simpler in form, Low Mass still retains the essential elements of the Catholic Mass, including the Liturgy of the Word, the Liturgy of the Eucharist, and the Concluding Rites.

title: Steve McNair
text: Steve McNair (February 14, 1973 – July 4, 2009) was an American football quarterback who played in the National Football League (NFL). McNair played college football for Alcorn State University, where he set numerous NCAA Division I records. He was drafted by the Houston Oilers with the third overall pick in the 1995 NFL Draft. McNair spent the first 11 seasons of his career with the Oilers/Titans franchise before joining the Baltimore Ravens in 2006. He led the Titans to Super Bowl XXXIV, where they lost to the St. Louis Rams. McNair was killed in a murder-suicide in 2009.

title: Archer Daniels Midland
text: Archer Daniels Midland Company (ADM) is an American multinational food processing and commodities trading corporation headquartered in Chicago, Illinois. Founded in 1902, ADM is one of the world's largest agricultural processors and food ingredient providers. The company operates over 270 processing plants and 500 crop procurement facilities worldwide, handling a wide range of agricultural commodities, including soybeans, corn, wheat, and oilseeds. ADM's products include food ingredients, animal feed, biofuels, and industrial products. The company employs approximately 33,000 people in over 160 countries.

title: Antonio Vivaldi
text: Antonio Vivaldi (1678–1741) was an Italian priest, violinist, teacher, and composer. Widely regarded as one of the greatest Baroque composers, he is known for his concertos, especially the set of concertos for one or more violins known as The Four Seasons. His music was influenced by the Venetian baroque style and employed innovative techniques such as contrasting dynamics and textures. Vivaldi was a prolific composer, producing over 500 concertos, 90 operas, and numerous other works.

title: Silverstone Circuit
text: Silverstone Circuit, located in the United Kingdom, is renowned as the home of the British Grand Prix since 1987. The iconic track has hosted numerous Formula One, MotoGP, and British Touring Car Championship events. Silverstone's rich history dates back to World War II, when it served as a Royal Air Force base. In 1948, it was transformed into a motor racing venue and has since become a celebrated destination for motorsport enthusiasts worldwide.

title: Head-up display
text: A head-up display (HUD) is a transparent display that presents data without requiring users to look away from their usual viewpoint. HUDs are often used in aircraft, automobiles, and other vehicles to provide critical information to the operator in a quick and easily digestible manner. HUDs can also be used in other applications, such as in sports, gaming, and other areas where it is advantageous to have information readily available without diverting the user's attention.

title: Norwood Court, Missouri
text: Norwood Court is a village in St. Louis County, Missouri, United States. The population was 990 at the 2020 census. Norwood Court is located approximately 10 miles northwest of downtown St. Louis. The village is bordered by the cities of Olivette, Creve Coeur, and Frontenac. Norwood Court is home to the Norwood Hills Country Club, which is one of the most prestigious golf courses in the St. Louis area.

title: Beat (music)
text: Beat is a fundamental element of music, referring to the recurring pulse or rhythmic unit that establishes the tempo and provides a sense of structure and drive. It can be expressed through drums, percussion, or any instrument that provides a rhythmic foundation. The beat acts as a guide for other musical elements, such as melody and harmony, and helps to create a cohesive and propulsive flow in musical performances.

title: Funny River, Alaska
text: Funny River is a census-designated place (CDP) in Kenai Peninsula Borough, Alaska, United States. It is located on the Sterling Highway at the confluence of the Funny River and the Kenai River. The population was 750 at the 2010 census. Funny River is a popular destination for fishing, camping, and other outdoor activities. The river is stocked with rainbow trout and Dolly Varden. There are also several campgrounds in the area, including the Funny River RV Park and Campground. The community of Funny River is small and close-knit. There is a community center, a post office, and a few small businesses. The community is also home to the Funny River School, which serves students from kindergarten through 8th grade.

title: JAG (TV series)
text: JAG (Judge Advocate General) is an American legal drama television series that follows the personal and professional lives of the staff of the United States Navy Judge Advocate General Corps (JAG). The series ran for ten seasons from 1995 to 2005 and starred David James Elliott as Captain Harmon "Harm" Rabb Jr. and Catherine Bell as Lieutenant Colonel Sarah "Mac" MacKenzie. JAG explores the legal and moral dilemmas faced by the JAG officers as they investigate and prosecute crimes within the military justice system. The series tackles issues such as terrorism, espionage, and the conflict between duty and conscience.

title: The Fast and the Furious (1955 film)
text: "The Fast and the Furious" (1955) is an American crime drama film directed by Roger Corman. The film follows a group of teenagers who engage in illegal street racing and drag racing in Southern California. The film stars John Ashley, Anne Neyland, and Dolores Fuller. "The Fast and the Furious" is considered one of the first films in the "teen exploitation" genre. It was a critical and commercial success, grossing over $1 million at the box office. The film has since become a cult classic and has been cited as an influence on later car racing films.

title: Another World (TV series)
text: "Another World" was an American daytime soap opera that aired on NBC from May 4, 1964, to June 25, 1999. Created by Irna Phillips and William J. Bell, the series followed the intertwining lives of the residents of the fictional town of Bay City. The show was known for its complex storylines, social commentary, and memorable characters. One of "Another World"'s most iconic storylines was the love triangle between characters Vicky Hudson, Steve Frame, and Iris Carrington. The show also tackled controversial issues such as abortion, AIDS, and homosexuality. "Another World" won numerous awards, including 21 Daytime Emmy Awards. It was canceled in 1999 due to declining ratings.

title: History of Poland
text: Poland's history dates back to the 10th century, with the establishment of the Piast dynasty. In the 14th century, Poland became a powerful kingdom under the Jagiellonian dynasty, which ruled for over two centuries. During this time, Poland expanded its territory and became a major cultural center. In the 18th century, Poland was partitioned by its neighbors, Russia, Prussia, and Austria. Poland regained its independence in 1918, but was again occupied by Nazi Germany during World War II. After the war, Poland became a communist state under Soviet control until 1989. Since then, Poland has been a democratic republic, and joined the European Union in 2004.

title: Spike Spencer
text: Spike Spencer (born 1962) is an English actor and comedian, best known for his deadpan delivery. He made his name in the 1980s as a member of the Comic Strip group, appearing in films such as Bad Boys and The Supergrass. In the 1990s, he starred in his own sitcom, Absolutely, co-written by Richard Curtis. He has also appeared in numerous other television shows, including Blackadder, Not the Nine O'Clock News, and Little Britain. Spencer's film credits include The Crying Game, Trainspotting, and Four Weddings and a Funeral. He is also a regular performer on the stand-up comedy circuit.

title: Airolo
text: Airolo is a municipality in the canton of Ticino, Switzerland. The village lies at an elevation of 1,175 meters (3,855 ft) above sea level, at the southern foot of the Gotthard Pass. Airolo is a popular tourist destination in both summer and winter, offering a variety of outdoor activities. In the summer, visitors can enjoy hiking, biking, and fishing. In the winter, Airolo is a popular destination for skiing and snowboarding. The village is also home to a number of historical and cultural attractions, including the Church of San Gottardo and the Gotthard Museum.

title: Mission Zamora
text: Mission Zamora, founded in 1806, was a Franciscan mission in present-day California. Located near modern-day Sacramento, it was one of 21 missions established by Spain along the California coast. The mission's primary purpose was to convert Native Americans to Christianity and introduce them to Spanish culture. It also served as a military outpost and a trading center. However, due to disease and conflict with settlers, the mission declined and was eventually secularized in 1834. Today, Mission Zamora is a California Historical Landmark and a popular tourist destination.

title: Boeing 2707
text: The Boeing 2707 was a supersonic transport (SST) project undertaken by Boeing in the 1960s. It was intended to be a commercial airliner capable of flying at Mach 3 (three times the speed of sound). However, the project was canceled in 1971 due to technical difficulties, rising costs, and environmental concerns. The Boeing 2707 was a large aircraft with a delta wing design and four engines mounted on the fuselage. It was designed to carry up to 300 passengers. The aircraft was intended to fly at Mach 3, but it was determined that this would require a significant increase in engine power and would result in excessive fuel consumption.

title: Yosef Avni
text: Yosef Avni (1922-1968) was an Israeli dancer and choreographer. He was one of the pioneers of modern dance in Israel, and his work had a significant impact on the development of dance in the country. Avni founded the Batsheva Dance Company in 1964, which later became one of the leading contemporary dance companies in the world. He was also a leading figure in the Kibbutz Dance Movement, which sought to combine dance with the values of communal living. Avni's work was characterized by its expressive power, its focus on the human body, and its use of everyday movements.

title: Chemical synapse
text: A chemical synapse is the junction between two neurons, where chemical signals are transmitted from one neuron to another. When an action potential arrives at the presynaptic neuron, it causes the release of neurotransmitters from synaptic vesicles. These neurotransmitters then bind to receptors on the postsynaptic neuron, causing the opening of ion channels and a change in the membrane potential. The strength of the synaptic connection, known as synaptic strength, can be modulated by various factors, such as the number of neurotransmitter receptors and the affinity of the neurotransmitters for the receptors.

title: Married... with Children
text: Married... with Children is an American sitcom that aired on Fox from 1987 to 1997. The show follows the Bundy family, a dysfunctional clan consisting of Al, a chauvinistic shoe salesman; Peggy, a lazy and promiscuous housewife; Kelly, their ditzy and promiscuous daughter; and Bud, their dim-witted and awkward son. The show was a critical and commercial success, running for 11 seasons and becoming one of the longest-running sitcoms in American television history.

title: Triage
text: Triage, derived from the French word for "sorting," is a process used to prioritize the treatment of patients based on the severity of their injuries or illnesses. In emergency situations, triage helps medical professionals determine which patients require immediate attention and which can wait. Triage nurses or paramedics use a system of criteria to assess patients' conditions and assign them a triage level, typically color-coded from green (least urgent) to red (most urgent). By prioritizing patients, triage ensures that those with the most critical needs receive prompt treatment, maximizing the chances of survival and recovery.

title: Port Royal, South Carolina
text: Port Royal, South Carolina, is a town on the southern tip of the Sea Islands in Beaufort County. Founded in 1562 by French Huguenots, it was the first permanent European settlement in North America outside of Spanish Florida. Port Royal was a major port during the American Civil War, and it played a significant role in the Battle of Port Royal Sound in 1861, which gave the Union control of the South Carolina coast. Today, Port Royal is a popular tourist destination, known for its historic architecture, beautiful scenery, and mild climate.

title: Electrolyte imbalance
text: Electrolyte imbalance occurs when the levels of electrolytes—essential minerals such as sodium, potassium, calcium, and magnesium—in the body are abnormally high or low. This imbalance can disrupt various bodily functions, including fluid balance, nerve transmission, muscle contraction, and heart rhythm. Electrolyte imbalance can result from dehydration, excessive sweating, diarrhea, vomiting, kidney disease, or certain medications. Symptoms may include fatigue, muscle cramps, nausea, vomiting, confusion, and irregular heartbeats. Treatment typically involves restoring electrolyte levels through oral or intravenous fluids.

title: DigitalEurope
text: DigitalEurope is a Brussels-based association representing the digital technology industry in Europe. It was founded in 1999 as the European Information Technology Industry Association (EICTA) and changed its name to DigitalEurope in 2018. The association's members include large technology companies such as Microsoft, Google, and SAP, as well as smaller companies and industry associations. DigitalEurope advocates for a competitive and innovative digital economy in Europe. It works with the European Union and other stakeholders to develop policies that promote investment in digital technologies, foster innovation, and ensure a level playing field for digital businesses.

title: Pietro Perugino
text: Pietro Perugino (c. 1446–1523), born Pietro Vannucci, was an Italian Renaissance painter of the Umbrian school. He is best known for his frescoes in the Sistine Chapel in Rome and for his paintings of the Madonna and Child. Perugino's style is characterized by its clarity of form, its use of soft, muted colors, and its serene, contemplative mood. He was a major influence on the young Raphael, who worked in his workshop for several years.

title: Avoca, New York
text: Avoca is a town in Steuben County, New York, United States. The population was 1,110 at the 2020 census. The town was named after the Avoca River, which flows into Seneca Lake. Avoca is home to the Avoca Museum and Historical Society, which houses a collection of artifacts from the town's history. The town is also home to the Avoca Airport, a general aviation airport.

title: Isla de Mona
text: Isla de Mona, an isolated and uninhabited island, lies off the west coast of Puerto Rico in the Caribbean Sea. Covering an area of approximately 21 square kilometers (8 square miles), it is known for its rugged terrain, pristine beaches, and diverse ecosystem. The island has been designated as a nature reserve and a National Natural Landmark due to its unique flora and fauna, which include rare and endemic species. Archaeological evidence suggests that Mona was once inhabited by indigenous Taíno people, but it became uninhabited by the 17th century.

title: Hun Sen
text: Hun Sen (born August 5, 1952) is a Cambodian politician who has served as Prime Minister of Cambodia since 1985. A former military commander, he has led the Cambodian People's Party (CPP) since 1991. Under Hun Sen's rule, Cambodia has achieved economic growth and stability, but has also faced criticisms over human rights abuses, corruption, and authoritarianism.

title: Nuclear fission product
text: Nuclear fission products are radioactive isotopes that are created when a nucleus of an atom is split apart. These products are unstable and decay by emitting radiation, which can be harmful to living organisms. The most common type of nuclear fission product is uranium-235, which is used in nuclear reactors and nuclear weapons. Other nuclear fission products include plutonium-239, iodine-131, and cesium-137. These products can be released into the environment during nuclear accidents or explosions, and they can pose a significant health risk.

title: Constitution of Ireland
text: The Constitution of Ireland, known in Irish as Bunreacht na hÉireann, is the fundamental law of Ireland. It was approved by referendum on July 1, 1937, and came into effect on December 29, 1937. The Constitution establishes Ireland as a sovereign, independent, democratic state and sets out the fundamental rights and duties of Irish citizens. It has been amended several times over the years, most recently in 2018.

title: Sphericon
text: Sphericon is an extinct genus of echinoderms from the Paleozoic era. It is characterized by its spherical body, which was composed of numerous small plates. Sphericon had a single mouth, which was located on the ventral side of the body. The genus is known from two species, S. simplex and S. granulatus, which have been found in North America and Europe. Sphericon is thought to have lived in shallow marine environments, where it fed on plankton.

title: LAN party
text: A LAN party is a social gathering where people bring their own computers and connect them together over a local area network (LAN). The participants typically engage in multiplayer video games, but LAN parties can also involve other activities such as file sharing, collaborative projects, and social networking. LAN parties are often held in homes, businesses, or other public spaces. They can range in size from a few people to hundreds or even thousands of attendees. LAN parties provide a unique opportunity for gamers and computer enthusiasts to connect with others who share their interests.

title: John Goldthorpe
text: John Henry Goldthorpe (born 22 February 1935) is a British sociologist best known for his work on social stratification and social mobility. He is Emeritus Professor of Sociology at the University of Oxford and a Fellow of Nuffield College, Oxford. Goldthorpe is the author of several influential books, including "The Affluent Worker" (1968), "Social Mobility and Class Structure" (1980), and "Social Stratification in Modern Societies" (2000). He has also been a member of the British Academy since 1992.

title: Twelve O'Clock High (TV series)
text: Twelve O'Clock High (TV series) Twelve O'Clock High is an American television drama series originally broadcast from 1964 to 1967. The series is based on the 1949 novel and 1950 film of the same name. It follows the men of the 918th Bomb Group of the United States Army Air Forces during World War II. The series ran for three seasons and 78 episodes. The show starred Robert Lansing, Paul Burke, and Frank Overton.

title: Kenney Jones
text: Kenney Jones (born September 16, 1948) is an English drummer, best known as a member of The Who since 1978, following the death of Keith Moon. Born in Stepney, London, Jones began his drumming career in the mid-1960s. He initially played with The Birds and then briefly with The Faces before joining The Who. He has also worked with other artists, including The Rolling Stones, Bob Dylan, and Pete Townshend.

title: Fallis, Oklahoma
text: Fallis is a town in Lincoln County, Oklahoma, United States. The population was 297 at the 2010 census. Fallis was founded in 1902 as a stop on the St. Louis and San Francisco Railroad. The town is named after William Fallis, a local landowner and businessman. Fallis is located in the central part of Oklahoma, approximately 40 miles (64 km) northeast of Oklahoma City. The town is situated on the northern edge of the Arbuckle Mountains, and the landscape is characterized by rolling hills and forests.

title: Ørland
text: Ørland is a municipality in Trøndelag county, Norway. The administrative centre of the municipality is the village of Botngård. Other villages in Ørland include Brekstad, Uthaug, and Opphaug. The municipality is located on the Fosen peninsula, and it is bordered by the municipalities of Bjugn to the north, Åfjord to the east, and Indre Fosen to the south. The Trondheimsfjord lies to the west of Ørland. The economy of Ørland is based on fishing, agriculture, and tourism. The municipality is also home to Ørland Main Air Station, one of the main airbases of the Royal Norwegian Air Force.

title: Neo-orthodoxy
text: Neo-orthodoxy is a 20th-century theological movement that emerged in reaction to the perceived liberalism and rationalism of modern theology. Neo-orthodoxy emphasizes the transcendence and sovereignty of God, the sinfulness of humanity, and the need for divine grace through Jesus Christ. Notable proponents include Karl Barth, Emil Brunner, and Reinhold Niebuhr. Neo-orthodoxy has been influential in shaping Protestant theology, particularly in the areas of Christology, soteriology, and ecclesiology.

title: 1954 Formula One season
text: The 1954 Formula One season was the eighth season of Formula One motor racing. It began on 17 January and ended on 24 October, after nine races. Juan Manuel Fangio won his second consecutive World Drivers' Championship, his fourth overall. Mercedes-Benz won the International Cup for Manufacturers.

title: Legionella
text: Legionella is a genus of Gram-negative bacteria that can cause Legionnaires' disease, a type of pneumonia. The bacteria are found in natural water sources such as lakes, rivers, and streams, and they can also be found in man-made water systems such as cooling towers, hot tubs, and showers. Legionella is transmitted to humans when they inhale aerosolized water droplets that contain the bacteria. Legionnaires' disease is a serious illness, and it can be fatal in some cases. Symptoms of Legionnaires' disease include fever, chills, cough, shortness of breath, and muscle aches.

title: St. Louis Eagles
text: The St. Louis Eagles were an American professional basketball team based in St. Louis, Missouri. They were founded in 1946 and joined the Professional Basketball League of America (PBLA). In 1948, the PBLA merged with the National Basketball League (NBL) to form the Basketball Association of America (BAA), which later became the National Basketball Association (NBA). The Eagles played in the BAA for one season before folding in 1949.

title: Waddesdon Manor
text: Waddesdon Manor is a National Trust property located in Buckinghamshire, England. It was built in the Renaissance style for Baron Ferdinand de Rothschild between 1874 and 1889 as a weekend retreat. The manor is renowned for its opulent interiors and extensive art collection, which includes works by artists such as Rembrandt, Hals, and Boucher. The surrounding gardens are designed in the French style and feature a variety of sculptures, fountains, and exotic plants. Waddesdon Manor is a popular tourist destination and is open to the public year-round.

title: Cocaine
text: Cocaine is a powerful stimulant drug commonly extracted from the leaves of the coca plant. It produces intense feelings of euphoria, increased energy, and alertness. However, cocaine use carries significant health risks, including addiction, heart problems, seizures, and strokes. Chronic cocaine abuse can alter brain function and lead to severe psychological consequences. Its effects can be immediate and dangerous, necessitating immediate medical attention in cases of overdose.

title: Dawoodi Bohra
text: The Dawoodi Bohra are a Shia Isma'ili Muslim community originating from the Indian subcontinent. They are followers of the Dawoodi Bohra faith, a branch of Shia Islam that recognizes the Da'i al-Mutlaq as their spiritual leader. The Dawoodi Bohras are known for their strong sense of community and their adherence to traditional Islamic values. They have a distinct culture and lifestyle, including their own language, cuisine, and customs. The community is led by the Syedna, who is considered the direct descendant of the Prophet Muhammad and is the ultimate authority on all matters of faith and practice.

title: Bobby Doerr
text: Bobby Doerr (born April 7, 1918) was a German-born American professional baseball second baseman who played 14 seasons in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the Boston Red Sox from 1937 to 1951. He was known for his exceptional defense, leading the American League in fielding percentage seven times. Doerr was a nine-time All-Star and was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1986. He is widely considered one of the greatest second basemen in baseball history. Doerr died on November 13, 2017, at the age of 99.

title: Abietic acid
text: Abietic acid, a diterpenoid resin acid, is a major component of pine resin. It is found in the resin canals of pine trees and is responsible for the characteristic odor of pine trees. Abietic acid is a white to pale yellow solid with a melting point of 155-157 °C (311-315 °F) and a boiling point of 295 °C (563 °F). It is insoluble in water but soluble in organic solvents such as ethanol, ether, and benzene. Abietic acid is used in the production of paper, varnish, and soap. It is also used as a flux in soldering and as a component in some adhesives.

title: Martianus Capella
text: Martianus Capella was a North African-born writer and philosopher who flourished in the early 5th century in the Roman province of Mauretania Caesariensis. He is best known for his sole surviving work, the "De nuptiis Philologiae et Mercurii" ("On the Marriage of Philology and Mercury"), an encyclopedia of the seven liberal arts. The work is divided into nine books, each covering a different subject matter, including grammar, dialectic, rhetoric, geometry, arithmetic, astronomy, and music. Martianus's work was highly influential throughout the Middle Ages, serving as a standard textbook for the study of the liberal arts.

title: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution
text: The Atlanta Journal-Constitution is a daily newspaper covering metropolitan Atlanta and the state of Georgia, U.S. It is the result of the merger of two newspapers, The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution, in 1982. The Journal-Constitution is owned by Cox Enterprises, a privately held media company based in Atlanta. The newspaper has a circulation of over 600,000 and is the largest newspaper in Georgia. It is known for its in-depth coverage of local and state news, as well as its sports and entertainment sections.

title: Lincoln Beach, Oregon
text: Lincoln Beach is a city in Lincoln County, Oregon, United States. As of the 2020 census, the city had a population of 9,189. Lincoln Beach is located on the Oregon Coast, approximately 10 miles (16 km) south of Lincoln City and 50 miles (80 km) southwest of Portland. The city is known for its beaches, which are popular for surfing, fishing, and other recreational activities. Lincoln Beach is also home to several restaurants, shops, and art galleries.

title: Toxication
text: Toxication, also known as poisoning, is a condition in which a chemical substance injures an organism. The toxic substance can be anything from a chemical to a biological agent such as bacteria or a virus. Symptoms of toxication can range from mild to severe and may include vomiting, diarrhea, seizures, and even death. Treatment for toxication typically involves removing the toxic substance from the body and providing supportive care.

title: Marianna, Pennsylvania
text: Marianna is a census-designated place (CDP) located in Washington County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 477 at the 2010 census. Marianna is part of the Pittsburgh metropolitan statistical area. The community began as a coal mining town in the 1830s. The Marianna Historic District was listed on the National Register of Historic Places in 2005.

title: Alfonso VI of León and Castile
text: Alfonso VI (c. 1040/1041 – July 1, 1109), called the Brave (el Bravo) and the Battler (el Batallador), was King of León and Castile from 1072 until his death and King of Galicia from 1072 to 1109. He was the son of Ferdinand I of León and Castile and Sancha of León. He succeeded to the throne of León on his father's death, while his brother Sancho II inherited Castile. After Sancho's assassination, Alfonso also inherited Castile.

title: Clerical celibacy
text: Clerical celibacy is the practice of abstaining from sexual activity and marriage for religious reasons, typically by members of the clergy. It has been observed in various religions throughout history, including Christianity, Buddhism, and Hinduism. In the Catholic Church, clerical celibacy is a mandatory requirement for ordination as a priest or bishop. It is believed to promote spiritual purity, allow priests to focus fully on their ministry, and symbolize the undivided love of Christ for his Church. However, the practice of clerical celibacy has faced criticism and debate over the centuries, with some arguing that it is an unnecessary burden and can lead to sexual abuse scandals. Despite these criticisms, clerical celibacy remains an important tradition in many religious communities.

title: Robert Bresson
text: Robert Bresson (1901-1999) was a French film director and screenwriter known for his austere and spiritual style. Born into a wealthy family, Bresson began his career as a painter before turning to filmmaking in the 1930s. His films are characterized by their minimalist aesthetics, long takes, and non-professional actors, who often play characters on the margins of society. Bresson's work explores themes of grace, redemption, and the search for meaning in a secular world.

title: George Pell
text: George Pell, an Australian Cardinal of the Catholic Church, served as Archbishop of Melbourne from 1996 to 2001 and Archbishop of Sydney from 2001 to 2014. He was made a Cardinal in 2003. In 2014, Pell was appointed Prefect of the Secretariat for the Economy, a newly created Vatican office tasked with overseeing the financial affairs of the Holy See. He held this position until 2019. In 2017, Pell was convicted of sexual abuse charges in Australia and sentenced to six years in prison. He was released on appeal in 2020. Pell has denied any wrongdoing and has maintained his innocence.

title: Union, Iowa
text: Union is a city in Hardin County, Iowa, United States. The population was 397 at the 2020 census. It is part of the Waterloo-Cedar Falls Metropolitan Statistical Area. Union was founded in 1853 by a group of settlers from Ohio. The city was named after the Union Pacific Railroad, which was being built through the area at the time. Union is home to the Grout Museum of History and Science, which is one of the largest and most comprehensive museums in Iowa.

title: Courtesan
text: A courtesan is a woman who provides sexual services on a professional basis, typically in exchange for payment or other forms of compensation. Courtesans have existed throughout history in various cultures and societies, and have played a significant role in some of them. In some cultures, courtesans were highly respected and held a prominent social position, while in others they were stigmatized and marginalized.

title: Johan Sverdrup
text: Johan Sverdrup (1816-1892), Norwegian theologian and politician, led the Norwegian Liberal Party and served as prime minister from 1884 to 1889. As a strong advocate for religious tolerance and a proponent of a more democratic society, he played a pivotal role in the emergence of Norway as a modern, constitutional monarchy. Sverdrup's reforms encompassed the expansion of suffrage, the establishment of a parliamentary system, and the strengthening of local governments. His legacy continues to shape Norwegian politics and society.

title: Walker Evans
text: Walker Evans (November 3, 1903 – April 10, 1975) was an American photographer and photojournalist best known for his work for the Farm Security Administration (FSA) during the Great Depression. His stark, often unsettling images documented the plight of rural Americans during the economic crisis and helped shape the nation's understanding of the period. Evans's work is characterized by its simplicity, directness, and attention to detail, and he is considered one of the most important figures in American photography.

title: Retaining wall
text: A retaining wall is a structure designed to restrain soil or other loose material and prevent it from sliding or eroding. Retaining walls are typically constructed of concrete, stone, or brick and are used in a variety of applications, including: -Preventing soil erosion on hillsides -Creating level areas for building or landscaping -Supporting embankments and roadways -Providing structural support for slopes and excavations The design of a retaining wall depends on several factors, including the height of the wall, the type of soil being retained, and the amount of hydrostatic pressure that will be exerted on the wall. Retaining walls can be either gravity walls or cantilever walls. Gravity walls rely on their own weight to resist overturning, while cantilever walls are supported by a footing that extends below the ground surface.

title: Asian carp
text: Asian carp are a group of freshwater fish native to East Asia. They were introduced to the United States in the 1970s and have since become an invasive species in the Mississippi River and its tributaries. Asian carp are large, fast-growing fish that can reach up to 4 feet in length and weigh over 100 pounds. They are voracious eaters and compete with native fish for food. Asian carp have also been known to jump out of the water and injure boaters.

title: Woodstock (song)
text: "Woodstock" is a song written by Joni Mitchell and first performed by Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young. It was released on their 1970 album Déjà Vu and became a top ten hit in the United States and the United Kingdom. The song is a nostalgic look back at the Woodstock Festival, which was held in August 1969. Mitchell's lyrics capture the spirit of the festival, with its themes of peace, love, and music. The song has been covered by numerous artists, including Joan Baez, Bob Dylan, and Bruce Springsteen.

title: Telautograph
text: The telautograph, invented by Elisha Gray in 1888, was an early fax machine that allowed for the transmission of handwritten or drawn messages over telegraph wires. It consisted of a transmitting and receiving device, each with a stylus. The sender would write or draw on a sheet of paper at the transmitting end, and the stylus at the receiving end would reproduce the movements, creating a copy of the original. While not as widely used as later fax machines, the telautograph was an important precursor to the technology that would eventually become indispensable for transmitting documents over long distances.

title: Caitika
text: Caitika is a deity in Hinduism, particularly in Bengal, India. She is a manifestation of Shakti, the divine feminine energy. Caitika is considered the goddess of harvest and new growth. She is often depicted as a young girl with a pot of rice, symbolizing fertility and prosperity. Caitika is worshipped during the spring festival of Chaitra Sankranti, which marks the beginning of the new harvest season. Devotees offer prayers and make offerings to seek her blessings for a bountiful harvest and overall well-being.

title: Colosseum
text: The Colosseum, also known as the Flavian Amphitheatre, is an iconic amphitheatre in Rome, Italy. Built between 70 and 80 AD, it is the largest ancient amphitheatre ever built, and is still the largest standing amphitheatre in the world, despite its age. The Colosseum was used for gladiatorial contests and other public spectacles, and could accommodate an estimated 50,000 spectators. Today, it is one of the most popular tourist attractions in Rome and is considered one of the seven wonders of the modern world.

title: XFree86
text: XFree86 was a free and open-source implementation of the X Window System, developed by The XFree86 Project, Inc. It was the most popular X server for Unix-like operating systems from the mid-1990s until the early 2000s, when it was superseded by the X.Org Server. XFree86 supported a wide range of graphics cards and provided a stable and reliable X server environment. It was used by many Linux distributions, as well as other Unix-like operating systems such as FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD.

title: Elroy Hirsch
text: Elroy "Crazy Legs" Hirsch (June 17, 1923 – January 28, 2004) was an American gridiron football player and coach. He played college football at the University of Wisconsin–Madison, and played professional football for the Chicago Rockets/Cardinals, Los Angeles Rams, and Dallas Texans. Hirsch was a four-time NFL champion, having won titles with the Rams in 1945 and 1951, and with the Browns in 1954 and 1955. He was inducted into the College Football Hall of Fame in 1974, and the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1968.

title: Kraven the Hunter
text: Kraven the Hunter, real name Sergei Kravinoff, is a supervillain appearing in American comic books published by Marvel Comics. Created by Stan Lee and Steve Ditko, the character first appeared in The Amazing Spider-Man #15 (August 1964). Kraven is a skilled hunter who uses a variety of weapons and gadgets to track down and capture his prey. He is obsessed with defeating Spider-Man, whom he considers the ultimate game. Kraven is a complex and tragic character, driven by his obsession and his desire for recognition. He has been praised for his well-developed characterization and his memorable appearances in Spider-Man comics.

title: Jerry Cantrell
text: Jerry Cantrell (born March 18, 1966) is an American musician best known as the lead guitarist, co-lead vocalist, and primary songwriter for the rock band Alice in Chains. He has also released three solo albums and collaborated with various other artists. Cantrell's guitar playing style is characterized by his use of heavy distortion and wah-wah pedals, as well as his melodic lead work. He is also known for his distinctive singing voice, which has been described as "smoky" and "gravelly."

title: Visual flight rules
text: Visual flight rules (VFR) are a set of regulations that govern the operation of aircraft in visual meteorological conditions (VMC). VFR flights are conducted under the premise that the pilot has sufficient visibility to see and avoid other aircraft and obstacles. VFR flight plans are not required, but pilots are required to file a notice of intended departure (NOID) with the nearest air traffic control facility. VFR flights are typically conducted at altitudes below 10,000 feet above sea level (ASL) and at speeds below 250 knots.

title: Chalfont, Pennsylvania
text: Chalfont is a borough in Bucks County, Pennsylvania, United States. The population was 4,141 at the 2020 census. Chalfont was founded in 1735 by Quaker settlers. The borough is named after Chalfont St. Giles, a village in Buckinghamshire, England. Chalfont is located along the Neshaminy Creek and is home to the Chalfont Historical Society and the Chalfont Public Library. The borough is served by the Central Bucks School District and is home to Chalfont Elementary School.

title: Tributary
text: A tributary is a stream or river that flows into a larger river or lake. Tributaries are often smaller than the main river or lake they flow into, and they can be either permanent or intermittent (flowing only during certain times of the year). The point where a tributary meets the main river or lake is called a confluence. Tributaries play an important role in the water cycle by carrying water from smaller watersheds into larger ones. They also provide habitat for a variety of plants and animals, and they can be used for irrigation and recreation.

title: Catalan grammar
text: Catalan grammar, the grammar of the Catalan language, is a Romance grammar that shares many features with other Romance languages, such as Spanish, French, and Italian. However, Catalan also has some unique features that set it apart from these other languages. One of the most distinctive features of Catalan grammar is the use of personal pronouns. In Catalan, personal pronouns are used much more frequently than in English, and they are often used in cases where English would use a noun phrase. For example, instead of saying "I went to the store," a Catalan speaker would say "I went there." Another distinctive feature of Catalan grammar is the use of verb forms. In Catalan, there are two main types of verb forms: simple and compound. Simple verb forms are used for actions that are completed in the present, past, or future. Compound verb forms are used for actions that are ongoing or habitual.

title: Fayette County, Indiana
text: Fayette County is a county located in the east-central portion of the U.S. state of Indiana. As of the 2020 census, the population was 24,277. The county seat is Connersville. The county was established in 1818 and is named for the Marquis de Lafayette, a French aristocrat and military officer who served in the American Revolutionary War. Fayette County is part of the Indianapolis–Carmel–Muncie metropolitan statistical area. The county's economy is largely based on agriculture, industry, and tourism.

title: Hayes command set
text: The Hayes command set is a series of standardized commands used to control modems. Developed by Dennis Hayes in 1981, it has become the de facto standard for modem communication. Hayes commands are typically sent from a computer to a modem using a serial connection. They allow users to configure the modem, establish and terminate connections, and transfer data. Common Hayes commands include ATD (dial), ATH (hang up), ATS (answer), and ATZ (reset). The Hayes command set has been widely adopted by modem manufacturers and other devices that require modem control, including fax machines and point-of-sale (POS) systems.

title: Manchukuo
text: Manchukuo was a puppet state established in Manchuria by the Empire of Japan following its invasion of Manchuria in 1931. It existed from 1932 to 1945 and was ruled by Puyi, the last emperor of the Qing dynasty. Manchukuo was a key part of Japan's plans for a Greater East Asia Co-Prosperity Sphere and was used as a base for operations against the Chinese Nationalist government and the Soviet Union. The state was dissolved in 1945 after the Soviet invasion of Manchuria.

title: Hi-5 (Australian band)
text: Hi-5 is an Australian children's music group formed in 1998. The group has released 14 studio albums, four live albums, and numerous DVDs. Hi-5 has toured extensively throughout Australia and internationally, and has won multiple awards, including an ARIA Award for Best Children's Album in 2000. The group's current lineup consists of Ainsley Melham, Bailey Spalding, Courtney Clarke, Lachie Dearing, and Stevie Nicholson.

title: Canton of Basel-Landschaft
text: The Canton of Basel-Landschaft is located in northwestern Switzerland and is part of the Basel metropolitan area. It is bordered by Germany to the north and east, the Canton of Basel-Stadt to the west, and the Canton of Aargau to the south. The canton has a population of over 280,000 and an area of 518 square kilometers. The capital of the canton is Liestal. The canton is known for its beautiful countryside, historic villages, and world-class museums. The economy of the canton is based on industry, services, and agriculture.

title: Super Bowl XX
text: Super Bowl XX was an American football game between the National Football Conference (NFC) champion Chicago Bears and the American Football Conference (AFC) champion New England Patriots to decide the National Football League (NFL) champion for the 1985 season. The game was played on January 26, 1986, at the Louisiana Superdome in New Orleans, Louisiana. The Bears defeated the Patriots by a score of 46–10, the most lopsided Super Bowl victory to date. The game is also remembered for the "Super Bowl Shuffle," a rap song and dance video performed by the Bears in the weeks leading up to the game.

title: Arecaceae
text: Arecaceae, commonly known as the palm family, is a large and diverse family of flowering plants, comprising over 2,600 species. Palms are distributed throughout the tropical and subtropical regions of the world, with a few species extending into temperate zones. They are recognized by their unique growth form, with a single, unbranched stem topped by a crown of large, often pinnate leaves. Palms have a wide range of ecological and economic importance, providing food, shelter, and various other products for humans and animals alike. Well-known members of the family include coconut palms, date palms, and oil palms, all of which have significant commercial value.

title: Sled dog
text: Sled dogs are a type of dog that is used to pull sleds through snow and ice. They are typically strong, muscular dogs with thick coats to protect them from the cold. The most common breeds of sled dogs are the Siberian Husky, Alaskan Malamute, and Samoyed, although other breeds may also be used. Sled dogs are typically used in teams of four to six dogs, and they can pull heavy loads over long distances.

title: Collective business system
text: A collective business system, also known as a cooperative business, is an enterprise owned and democratically controlled by its members, who share the profits and risks. This structure differs from traditional businesses, where ownership and control are typically concentrated in the hands of a few shareholders or investors. Collective business systems prioritize the interests of their members, rather than external shareholders, and often operate with a focus on social and environmental responsibility. Examples include worker cooperatives, farmer cooperatives, and credit unions.

title: Roman Abramovich
text: Roman Abramovich, a Russian-Israeli billionaire, is well-known for his ownership of Chelsea Football Club from 2003 to 2022. During his tenure, the club achieved significant success, winning numerous titles, including five Premier League championships and two Champions League trophies. Abramovich's fortune derives from various sources, primarily from his former ownership of the Russian oil company Sibneft. Known for his philanthropy, he has made substantial donations to various causes, mainly in the areas of education, healthcare, and culture.

title: USS S-44 (SS-155)
text: USS S-44 (SS-155) was a S-class submarine of the United States Navy. Her keel was laid down by the Portsmouth Navy Yard in Kittery, Maine, on 19 November 1921. She was launched on 16 January 1924 sponsored by Mrs. Joseph S. McKean, and commissioned on 23 May 1925, with Lieutenant Commander Christian J. Wylie in command.

title: Steven Wilson
text: Steven John Wilson (born 3 November 1967) is an English musician, singer-songwriter, record producer, audio engineer and multi-instrumentalist. He is best known for his work as the frontman of progressive rock band Porcupine Tree. Wilson has also released several solo albums, and has collaborated with a wide range of artists, including Opeth, King Crimson, and Jethro Tull. He is known for his eclectic musical style, which incorporates elements of progressive rock, art rock, ambient music, and electronica.

title: Type theory
text: Type theory is a branch of mathematical logic that studies the formalization of type systems, which are systems for classifying mathematical objects according to their properties. Type theories are used to ensure the correctness of computer programs and to develop new programming languages. Simple type systems, such as the simply typed lambda calculus, assign a single type to each expression. More complex type systems, such as dependent type theories, allow types to depend on other types. This allows for the expression of more complex relationships between mathematical objects.

title: The Awful Truth
text: The Awful Truth is a 1937 American screwball comedy film directed by Leo McCarey and starring Irene Dunne and Cary Grant. The film follows the story of a feuding couple, Lucy and Jerry Warriner, who decide to divorce but continue to live together. As they try to sabotage each other's new relationships, they realize that they still love each other. The Awful Truth was a critical and commercial success, winning the Academy Award for Best Director and being nominated for Best Picture, Best Actor (Grant), Best Actress (Dunne), and Best Original Screenplay.

title: Digital object identifier
text: The Digital Object Identifier (DOI) is a unique identifier for digital objects, such as journal articles, datasets, and software. It is designed to be persistent, meaning that it will not change over time, and to be actionable, meaning that it can be used to locate the object online. DOIs are assigned by registration agencies, which are responsible for ensuring that each DOI is unique and resolves to the correct object. DOIs are used by a variety of stakeholders, including researchers, librarians, and publishers, to identify and access digital objects.

title: Truckee, California
text: Truckee is a town in and the county seat of Nevada County, California, United States. The population was 16,180 at the 2020 census. Truckee is located near the northwest shore of Lake Tahoe, a large freshwater lake in the Sierra Nevada. The town is served by the Truckee Tahoe Airport and is a popular destination for outdoor recreation, including skiing, snowboarding, hiking, and mountain biking. Truckee is also home to several casinos and resorts.

title: Olof Skötkonung
text: Olof Skötkonung (Old Norse: Óláfr sænski, Swedish: Olof Skötkonung, c. 980 – 1022) was the King of Sweden from c. 995 until his death. He was the son of Eric the Victorious and his second wife Sigrid the Haughty. Olof was the first Christian king of Sweden, and he is credited with spreading Christianity throughout the country. He also expanded the Swedish kingdom, conquering parts of Norway and Finland. Olof was succeeded by his son Anund Jacob.

title: Potsdamer Platz
text: Potsdamer Platz is a public square and major traffic intersection in the Mitte district of Berlin, Germany. Once known as the busiest square in Europe, Potsdamer Platz was heavily damaged during World War II and then divided by the Berlin Wall. After the reunification of Germany, the square was redeveloped and is now home to a number of landmark buildings, including the Sony Center, the DaimlerChrysler headquarters, and the Kollhoff Tower. Potsdamer Platz is also a popular tourist destination, with several museums, theaters, and shops.

title: Montgomery, Michigan
text: Montgomery is an unincorporated community in Hillsdale County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The community is located within Wheatland Township. As of the 2010 census, the community had a population of 274. Montgomery is located at 41°52′46″N 84°35′52″W, and is situated along M-34. The community is served by the Montgomery Community Schools, and is home to Montgomery Elementary School.

title: Archaeological culture
text: An archaeological culture is a group of material remains that share similar characteristics, such as pottery, tools, and architecture. These remains are often found in a particular geographic area and time period, and they can provide insights into the behavior and lifeways of past cultures. Archaeological cultures are often named after the type site where they were first identified, such as the Clovis culture or the Maya culture. The study of archaeological cultures helps archaeologists to understand the development and spread of human societies over time.

title: Archbasilica of St. John Lateran
text: The Archbasilica of St. John Lateran, officially known as the Papal Archbasilica of St. John Lateran, is the cathedral church of Rome and the official ecclesiastical seat of the Bishop of Rome, who is the Pope. It is one of the four major basilicas in Rome, and together with St. Peter's Basilica, is regarded as one of the holiest churches in Christianity. The Archbasilica holds the rank of the first Patriarchal Basilica among the seven pilgrim churches of Rome and is the oldest and highest-ranking of the four papal basilicas.

title: Jerry Lewis
text: Jerry Lewis (born Joseph Levitch; March 16, 1926 – August 20, 2017) was an American comedian, actor, singer, film producer, and director. He was known for his slapstick comedy routines, often working in tandem with Dean Martin. Lewis's career spanned over six decades, and he starred in over 40 films. He was also a popular nightclub and television performer, and hosted the annual Muscular Dystrophy Association Labor Day Telethon for over 40 years. Lewis was known for his philanthropy, and he raised millions of dollars for the Muscular Dystrophy Association and other charities.

title: VO2 max
text: VO2 max, also known as maximal oxygen uptake, is a measure of the maximum volume of oxygen a person can use during intense exercise. It is a key indicator of cardiovascular fitness and endurance capacity. VO2 max is typically measured in milliliters per minute per kilogram of body weight (mL/min/kg). VO2 max is primarily determined by genetic factors, but training can improve it by increasing the heart's stroke volume and the efficiency of the circulatory system.

title: Hors d'oeuvre
text: Hors d'oeuvre, also known as appetizers or starters, are small dishes served before the main course of a meal. They are typically served cold or at room temperature and are designed to stimulate the appetite. Hors d'oeuvre can vary widely in terms of ingredients, preparation, and presentation, and can include a variety of items such as canapés, crudités, dips, and salads. They are often served at parties, receptions, and other social gatherings as a way to provide guests with a light bite while they socialize.

title: Study of the Hebrew language
text: The study of the Hebrew language, known as Hebrew philology, encompasses the scientific analysis of the Hebrew language's history, grammar, and texts. It involves examining the language's evolution from its earliest attestations in the Proto-Canaanite script to its modern forms. Hebrew philology is essential for understanding the Hebrew Bible and other ancient Hebrew texts, as well as for tracing the development of the Hebrew language over time. Scholars engaged in Hebrew philology utilize linguistic methods to shed light on the language's phonology, morphology, syntax, and semantics.

title: Mercury dime
text: The Mercury dime, officially known as the Winged Liberty Head Dime, was a ten-cent coin struck by the United States Mint from 1916 to 1945. Designed by Adolph A. Weinman, it replaced the Barber dime and was itself replaced by the Roosevelt dime in 1946. The obverse of the coin features a left-facing bust of Liberty wearing a winged Phrygian cap, while the reverse depicts a fasces, an ancient Roman symbol of authority, surrounded by olive branches. The coin's distinctive design and high relief made it popular with collectors, and it remains one of the most recognizable coins in American history.

title: Go Seigen
text: Go Seigen (1914-2010), known as the "God of Go," was a Japanese professional Go player. He was widely regarded as one of the greatest Go players of all time and held the Meijin title for 24 consecutive years, a record unbroken to this day. Go Seigen's influence on the game of Go is immense, and his teachings and strategies continue to shape the way the game is played today. He was also a prolific writer, authoring several books on Go strategy.

title: Origins of the American Civil War
text: The American Civil War (1861-1865) had complex origins rooted in decades of political, economic, and social tensions between the Northern and Southern states. The key issues included the expansion of slavery into new territories, the balance of power between the federal government and state governments, and economic protectionism versus free trade. The election of Abraham Lincoln as president in 1860, on a platform opposing the expansion of slavery, triggered the secession of seven Southern states and the formation of the Confederate States of America. The outbreak of war in April 1861 marked the culmination of these tensions and the beginning of a bloody conflict that left over 600,000 Americans dead.

title: Heliox
text: Heliox is a mixture of helium and oxygen used for breathing in diving and medicine. It is less dense than air, reducing the work of breathing, and it is less soluble in blood, reducing the risk of decompression sickness. In diving, heliox is used to extend the depth and duration of dives, and to reduce the risk of nitrogen narcosis. In medicine, heliox is used to treat respiratory conditions such as asthma and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, and to deliver oxygen to patients in intensive care.

title: Volksdeutsche
text: Volksdeutsche were ethnic Germans living outside of Germany's borders. The term was used by the Nazi regime to justify the annexation of territories with significant German populations, such as Austria, the Sudetenland, and Poland. After the war, millions of Volksdeutsche were expelled from their homes in Eastern Europe, and many were resettled in West Germany. The term Volksdeutsche is controversial, as it implies that all ethnic Germans are part of a single German nation. This view was promoted by the Nazis, who sought to create a Greater Germany that included all areas where Germans lived. However, many Volksdeutsche did not identify as Germans, and some actively resisted Nazi rule.

title: Ferris Township, Michigan
text: Ferris Township is a civil township of Montcalm County in the U.S. state of Michigan. The population was 1,542 at the 2010 census. The township was founded in 1839 and named after Benjamin B. Ferris, an early settler and county surveyor. Ferris Township is located in the southern part of Montcalm County, approximately 10 miles south of the city of Greenville. The township is bordered by the Looking Glass River to the west and the Flat River to the east. The terrain is gently rolling, with a mix of forests and farmland.
